## How It Works (with practical examples)

### Currently Learning: Server Components (Next.js 14 / React 18)
**Why:** The shift towards Server Components is a fundamental change in how we think about rendering and data fetching in React. It offers significant performance benefits by reducing client-side JavaScript bundles, improving initial page load times, and simplifying data fetching logic by moving it closer to the data source. Understanding this paradigm shift is crucial for building modern, performant web applications.

**Practical Application:** I've been refactoring parts of a personal project (a blogging platform) to leverage Server Components. For instance, fetching blog posts and user data previously involved `useEffect` or client-side SWR/React Query. Now, I'm fetching data directly within Server Components, passing props down to Client Components only when interactivity is needed. This reduces hydration overhead and improves perceived performance.

**Example Scenario:**
Imagine a `BlogPost` page.
**Before (Client Component with `useEffect`):**
```typescript
// app/blog/[slug]/page.tsx (Client Component)
'use client';
import { useState, useEffect } from 'react';

interface Post {
  id: string;
  title: string;
  content: string;
}

export default function BlogPostPage({ params }: { params: { slug: string } }) {
  const [post, setPost] = useState<Post | null>(null);
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);

  useEffect(() => {
    async function fetchPost() {
      setLoading(true);
      const res = await fetch(`/api/posts/${params.slug}`);
      const data = await res.json();
      setPost(data);
      setLoading(false);
    }
    fetchPost();
  }, [params.slug]);

  if (loading) return <div>Loading post...</div>;
  if (!post) return <div>Post not found.</div>;

  return (
    <div>
      <h1>{post.title}</h1>
      <p>{post.content}</p>
    </div>
  );
}
```

**After (Server Component):**
```typescript
// app/blog/[slug]/page.tsx (Server Component)
import { notFound } from 'next/navigation';

interface Post {
  id: string;
  title: string;
  content: string;
}

// This function runs on the server
async function getPost(slug: string): Promise<Post | null> {
  // In a real app, this would fetch from a database or internal API
  const res = await fetch(`https://api.example.com/posts/${slug}`, { next: { revalidate: 3600 } });
  if (!res.ok) {
    if (res.status === 404) return null;
    throw new Error('Failed to fetch post');
  }
  return res.json();
}

export default async function BlogPostPage({ params }: { params: { slug: string } }) {
  const post = await getPost(params.slug);

  if (!post) {
    notFound(); // Next.js helper for 404
  }

  return (
    <div>
      <h1>{post.title}</h1>
      <p>{post.content}</p>
      {/* Any interactive parts would be separate client components passed as props */}
      {/* <CommentSection postId={post.id} /> */}
    </div>
  );
}
```
The Server Component fetches data directly, eliminating client-side loading states and reducing the JavaScript bundle for the initial load.

