hr {
  box-sizing: content-box;
  height: 0;
  overflow: visible;
}

/**
 * 1. Correct the inheritance and scaling of font size in all browsers.
 * 2. Correct the odd `em` font sizing in all browsers.
 */
pre {
  font-family: monospace, monospace; /* 1 */
  font-size: 1em; /* 2 */
}

/* Text-level semantics
   ========================================================================== */

/**
 * Remove the gray background on active links in IE 10.
 */
a {
  background-color: transparent;
}

/**
 * 1. Remove the bottom border in Chrome 57- and Firefox 39-.
 * 2. Add the correct text decoration in Chrome, Edge, IE, Opera, and Safari.
 */
abbr[title] {
  border-bottom: none; /* 1 */
  text-decoration: underline; /* 2 */
  text-decoration: underline dotted; /* 2 */
}

/**
 * Add the correct font size in all browsers.
 */
code,
kbd,
samp {
  font-family: monospace, monospace;
  font-size: 1em; /* Ensures consistent monospaced font size */
}

/**
 * Add the correct font size in all browsers.
 */
small {
  font-size: 80%;
}

/**
 * Prevent `sub` and `sup` elements from affecting the line height in
 * all browsers.
 */
sub,
sup {
  font-size: 75%;
  line-height: 0;
  position: relative;
  vertical-align: baseline;
}

sub {
  bottom: -0.25em;
}

sup {
  top: -0.5em;
}
```

## Key Takeaways

*   **Goal:** `reset.css` aims for a blank slate; `Normalize.css` aims for consistent, sensible defaults.
*   **Approach:** `reset.css` is destructive (removes all styles); `Normalize.css` is corrective (fixes inconsistencies, preserves useful styles).
*   **Developer Effort:** `reset.css` often requires more custom CSS to re-style basic elements; `Normalize.css` requires less re-styling as many elements will look good by default.
*   **File Size:** `reset.css` can sometimes be smaller if it only targets a few properties, but often comprehensive resets are larger. `Normalize.css` is usually a moderate size, focusing on specific fixes.
*   **Modern Usage:** `Normalize.css` or similar "opinionated normalizers" (like those built into frameworks like Bootstrap or specialized libraries like modern-normalize) are generally preferred in modern web development for their balance of consistency and usability. Many developers also use a minimal custom reset for a few elements combined with a normalizing approach.

## Quick Summary
Client-side routing allows a web application to change the URL and update the UI without making a full page refresh from the server. It provides a Single Page Application (SPA) experience, making navigation feel faster and more seamless, similar to a desktop application.

## How It Works
Client-side routing primarily leverages the browser's History API (`history.pushState` and `history.replaceState`) and listens for changes in the URL or user interactions.

Here's a breakdown of the typical workflow:

1.  **User Interaction:** The user clicks a navigation link (e.g., `<a href="/about">About</a>`).
2.  **Prevent Default:** Instead of letting the browser perform a full page navigation, the client-side router intercepts the click event and calls `event.preventDefault()`.
3.  **Update URL and History:** The router then uses `history.pushState()` to change the URL in the browser's address bar and add a new entry to the browser's history stack. This changes the URL without triggering a full page reload.
    *   `pushState(state, title, url)`: Pushes a new state onto the history stack.
    *   `replaceState(state, title, url)`: Replaces the current state in the history stack.
4.  **Route Matching:** The router analyzes the new URL (or a specific part of it, like the path name) and matches it against a predefined set of routes.
5.  **Component Rendering:** Based on the matched route, the router determines which UI component(s) should be rendered. It then dynamically updates the DOM to display the new content, typically by injecting or replacing components within a designated layout area.
6.  **`popstate` Event:** When the user uses the browser's back/forward buttons, the browser fires a `popstate` event. The client-side router listens for this event, re-evaluates the current URL, and renders the appropriate UI component, again without a full page refresh.

**Practical Example:**
Imagine a simple SPA with two routes: `/` (Home) and `/about`.

*   When the user navigates to `/about`, the router intercepts the click, calls `history.pushState(null, '', '/about')`, and then renders the `AboutComponent`.
*   If the user then clicks the back button, the browser fires `popstate`. The router detects the URL is now `/` and renders the `HomeComponent`.

## Code Example

```typescript
// A very basic client-side router implementation
class SimpleRouter {
    private routes: { [path: string]: () => void } = {};
    private root: HTMLElement;

    constructor(rootElementId: string) {
        const root = document.getElementById(rootElementId);
        if (!root) {
            throw new Error(`Root element with ID '${rootElementId}' not found.`);
        }
        this.root = root;

        // Listen for browser's back/forward button events
        window.addEventListener('popstate', () => this.handleLocation());

        // Intercept clicks on anchor tags
        document.body.addEventListener('click', (e) => {
            const target = e.target as HTMLElement;
            if (target.matches('a[data-route]')) { // Use a custom attribute to identify internal links
                e.preventDefault();
                const path = target.getAttribute('href');
                if (path) {
                    this.navigate(path);
                }
            }
        });
    }

    // Define a route and its corresponding handler
    addRoute(path: string, handler: () => void) {
        this.routes[path] = handler;
    }

    // Programmatically navigate to a new path
    navigate(path: string) {
        history.pushState(null, '', path);
        this.handleLocation();
    }

    // Handle the current URL and render content
    handleLocation() {
        const path = window.location.pathname;
        const handler = this.routes[path] || this.routes['/404']; // Fallback for unmatched routes

        if (handler) {
            this.root.innerHTML = ''; // Clear previous content
            handler(); // Execute the handler to render new content
        } else {
            this.root.innerHTML = '<h1>404 Not Found</h1>';
        }
    }

    // Start the router, handling the initial load
    start() {
        this.handleLocation();
    }
}

// --- Usage Example ---

const router = new SimpleRouter('app-root');

router.addRoute('/', () => {
    router.root.innerHTML = `
        <h1>Home Page</h1>
        <p>Welcome to the home page!</p>
        <p><a href="/about" data-route>Go to About</a></p>
        <p><a href="/contact" data-route>Go to Contact (404)</a></p>
    `;
});

router.addRoute('/about', () => {
    router.root.innerHTML = `
        <h1>About Page</h1>
        <p>Learn more about us.</p>
        <p><a href="/" data-route>Go to Home</a></p>
    `;
});

// Start the router on page load
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
    router.start();
});

// HTML Structure
/*
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Client-Side Routing Demo</title>
</head>
<body>
    <nav>
        <a href="/" data-route>Home</a> |
        <a href="/about" data-route>About</a>
    </nav>
    <div id="app-root">
        Loading...
    </div>
    <script src="router.ts"></script> <!-- Link to this TypeScript/JavaScript file -->
</body>
</html>
*/
```

## Key Takeaways

*   **SPA Experience:** Enables Single Page Applications by providing fast, seamless navigation without full page reloads.
*   **History API:** Relies heavily on `history.pushState()`, `history.replaceState()`, and the `popstate` event to manipulate the browser history and URL.
*   **Event Handling:** Intercepts link clicks (`event.preventDefault()`) to prevent default browser navigation.
*   **Dynamic UI Updates:** Renders different UI components based on the current URL path, updating only the necessary parts of the DOM.
*   **Framework Support:** Modern frontend frameworks (React Router, Angular Router, Vue Router) provide robust, feature-rich implementations of client-side routing.

Long Polling, Server-Sent Events (SSE), and WebSockets are all techniques for enabling real-time communication between a client and a server over HTTP. They differ in their underlying mechanisms, capabilities, and suitable use cases.

## Quick Summary
Long Polling is a client-initiated technique where the server holds a request open until new data is available or a timeout occurs. Server-Sent Events (SSE) provide a one-way, server-to-client communication stream over a single HTTP connection, ideal for publishing updates. WebSockets offer full-duplex, bi-directional communication over a persistent TCP connection, making them suitable for interactive applications requiring low-latency data exchange in both directions.

## How It Works (with practical examples)

### Long Polling
**How it works:**
1.  The client makes an HTTP request to the server, similar to a regular AJAX request.
2.  The server does not immediately respond if it has no new data. Instead, it holds the request open until new data becomes available or a predefined timeout period is reached.
3.  Once data is available (or timeout occurs), the server sends a response to the client.
4.  Upon receiving the response, the client processes the data and immediately sends a new request to the server, restarting the process.

**Practical Example:** A simple chat application where clients frequently check for new messages.
-   **Client:** "Are there new messages?" (request sent)
-   **Server:** "No, not yet. Hold on..." (holds request)
-   **Server:** (New message arrives) "Yes, here's a new message!" (sends response)
-   **Client:** (Receives message) "Okay, process that. Are there more new messages?" (sends new request)

### Server-Sent Events (SSE)
**How it works:**
1.  The client establishes a single, long-lived HTTP connection to the server.
2.  The server sends data to the client whenever new data is available. It uses a special `text/event-stream` content type.
3.  The connection remains open, allowing the server to push multiple events over time without the client repeatedly initiating requests.
4.  The browser's `EventSource` API automatically handles connection re-establishment if the connection is dropped.

**Practical Example:** Real-time stock tickers, news feeds, or progress updates for long-running tasks.
-   **Client:** "Subscribe to stock updates." (establishes connection)
-   **Server:** "Here's the current price for AAPL: $170." (sends event)
-   **Server:** "Here's the current price for GOOG: $150." (sends another event)
-   **Server:** (Connection remains open, continues pushing updates as they occur)

### WebSocket
**How it works:**
1.  The client sends a standard HTTP request to the server with an `Upgrade` header, requesting to switch to the WebSocket protocol.
2.  If the server supports WebSockets, it responds with an `Upgrade` header, establishing a persistent, full-duplex TCP connection. This initial handshake is HTTP-based.
3.  Once established, both client and server can send and receive messages independently at any time over the same connection, without HTTP overhead.
4.  Messages are framed and can be text (UTF-8) or binary data.

**Practical Example:** Online multiplayer games, collaborative editing tools, live chat applications with typing indicators.
-   **Client:** "Let's upgrade this connection to a WebSocket." (HTTP handshake)
-   **Server:** "Agreed, connection upgraded." (WebSocket connection established)
-   **Client:** "I moved my character to (x,y)." (sends data)
-   **Server:** "Player B typed 'hello'." (sends data)
-   **Client:** "I'm typing..." (sends data)
-   **Server:** (Both can send and receive messages simultaneously and independently)

## Code Example

```typescript
// --- Long Polling (Client-side conceptual) ---
async function pollForData() {
  try {
    const response = await fetch('/api/poll-updates'); // Server holds this request
    const data = await response.json();
    console.log('Long Polling received:', data);
    // Process data, then immediately poll again
    pollForData();
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Polling error:', error);
    // Implement back-off or retry logic
    setTimeout(pollForData, 5000); // Retry after 5 seconds
  }
}
// pollForData(); // Uncomment to start polling


// --- Server-Sent Events (Client-side) ---
if (typeof EventSource !== 'undefined') {
  const eventSource = new EventSource('/api/events'); // Connects to an SSE endpoint

  eventSource.onopen = () => {
    console.log('SSE connection opened.');
  };

  eventSource.onmessage = (event) => {
    // Default event for 'message' type
    console.log('SSE message:', event.data);
  };

  eventSource.addEventListener('stockUpdate', (event: MessageEvent) => {
    // Custom event type 'stockUpdate'
    console.log('Stock Update:', JSON.parse(event.data));
  });

  eventSource.onerror = (error) => {
    console.error('SSE error:', error);
    eventSource.close(); // Close on error, EventSource will try to reconnect automatically
  };

  // To close the connection explicitly:
  // setTimeout(() => eventSource.close(), 60000); // Close after 1 minute
} else {
  console.warn('Server-Sent Events are not supported by this browser.');
}


// --- WebSocket (Client-side) ---
const ws = new WebSocket('ws://localhost:8080/ws'); // Connects to a WebSocket server

ws.onopen = () => {
  console.log('WebSocket connection opened.');
  ws.send('Hello Server!'); // Send a message to the server
};

ws.onmessage = (event) => {
  console.log('WebSocket received:', event.data);
};

ws.onclose = (event) => {
  if (event.wasClean) {
    console.log(`WebSocket closed cleanly, code=${event.code}, reason=${event.reason}`);
  } else {
    console.error('WebSocket connection died');
  }
};

ws.onerror = (error) => {
  console.error('WebSocket error:', error);
};

// To send messages to the server:
// ws.send('Another message from client');

// To close the connection explicitly:
// setTimeout(() => ws.close(1000, 'Client leaving'), 5000); // Close after 5 seconds
```

## Key Takeaways

*   **Long Polling:**
    *   **Pros:** Simple to implement, works with older browsers, uses standard HTTP requests.
    *   **Cons:** High latency, inefficient (many short-lived connections), server resources tied up holding requests, potential for race conditions if not handled carefully.
    *   **Use Cases:** Simple real-time updates where latency isn't critical, or as a fallback for other methods.

*   **Server-Sent Events (SSE):**
    *   **Pros:** Simpler API than WebSockets (`EventSource`), built-in reconnection logic, lightweight over HTTP, good for unidirectional data flow.
    *   **Cons:** Unidirectional (server-to-client only), limited to text data (UTF-8), not suitable for interactive applications requiring client-to-server pushes.
    *   **Use Cases:** Real-time dashboards, stock tickers, news feeds, live score updates, progress bars, one-way notifications.

*   **WebSocket:**
    *   **Pros:** Full-duplex (bi-directional) communication, very low latency, persistent single connection, efficient (less overhead than HTTP), supports binary data.
    *   **Cons:** More complex API than SSE, requires a dedicated WebSocket server, not directly compatible with traditional HTTP proxies/load balancers without configuration.
    *   **Use Cases:** Online games, real-time chat, collaborative editing, video/audio conferencing, IoT dashboards, applications requiring frequent, low-latency data exchange in both directions.

## Quick Summary
Hot Module Replacement (HMR) in Webpack allows developers to exchange, add, or remove modules while an application is running, without a full page reload. This significantly speeds up development by preserving the application's state, only updating the changed components, styles, or scripts.

## How It Works
HMR works by creating a WebSocket connection between the browser and the Webpack development server. When a change is detected in a source file, Webpack recompiles the affected modules and sends an update to the browser via the WebSocket. The HMR runtime in the browser then intelligently applies these updates without refreshing the entire page.

Here's a step-by-step breakdown:

1.  **Webpack Dev Server Integration:** The Webpack Dev Server includes an HMR runtime and leverages a WebSocket server.
2.  **File Changes Detected:** When a developer saves a file, the `watch` mode in Webpack detects the change.
3.  **Module Recompilation:** Webpack recompiles only the changed modules and their direct dependencies, generating new "update" bundles (JSON manifest + new module code).
4.  **HMR Update Sent:** The Webpack Dev Server sends a signal to the browser (via WebSocket) that an update is available, along with the manifest of changes.
5.  **HMR Runtime in Browser:** The HMR runtime (injected into the client-side bundle) receives the update signal.
6.  **Module Acceptance/Propagation:**
    *   **Self-Accept:** If a module explicitly "accepts" its own update (e.g., a React component handling its own re-render logic), it will apply the new code.
    *   **Bubble Up:** If a module doesn't accept the update, the update "bubbles up" to its parent modules. This continues until an accepting module is found, or it reaches the entry point (which would usually trigger a full reload if no module accepts it).
    *   **Replacement:** The old module is removed from the module graph, and the new module replaces it.
7.  **DOM Update (if applicable):** For UI components (like React or Vue), the framework's reconciliation process takes over to update the DOM efficiently.

**Practical Example:**
Imagine you're developing a React component. You change some text in a `<p>` tag within that component. HMR will:
1.  Detect the change in your component's file.
2.  Recompile *only* that component.
3.  Send the updated component code to the browser.
4.  The HMR runtime will tell React to replace the old component with the new one.
5.  React's virtual DOM will detect the text change and update only that specific text node in the actual DOM, *without losing any state* in other parts of your application (e.g., form input values, modal visibility).

## Code Example

To enable HMR in Webpack, you primarily need to configure the `devServer` and add the `HotModuleReplacementPlugin`.

```typescript
// webpack.config.js

import webpack from 'webpack';

const config = {
  mode: 'development', // HMR is typically used in development mode
  entry: './src/index.ts', // Your main entry file
  output: {
    filename: 'bundle.js',
    path: path.resolve(__dirname, 'dist'),
  },
  module: {
    rules: [
      {
        test: /\.ts$/,
        use: 'ts-loader',
        exclude: /node_modules/,
      },
      {
        test: /\.css$/,
        use: ['style-loader', 'css-loader'],
      },
    ],
  },
  resolve: {
    extensions: ['.ts', '.js'],
  },
  devServer: {
    // Enable HMR on the dev server
    hot: true,
    // Optional: Specify host and port
    // host: 'localhost',
    // port: 8080,
    // Optional: Open browser automatically
    // open: true,
  },
  plugins: [
    // This is crucial for HMR. It creates a manifest of changes.
    new webpack.HotModuleReplacementPlugin(),
    // Optional: If you use React, you might need React Refresh Plugin for better HMR experience
    // new ReactRefreshWebpackPlugin(),
  ],
};

export default config;
```

And in your entry file, you might add HMR acceptance logic for non-framework-specific scenarios (frameworks like React often handle this via plugins):

```typescript
// src/index.ts

import './styles.css'; // Imagine this is a CSS file
import { greet } from './utils'; // Imagine this is a utility function

console.log(greet('Webpack HMR!'));

// Basic HMR acceptance for non-framework modules
// This tells HMR what to do when this module or its dependencies change
if (module.hot) {
  module.hot.accept('./utils', function () {
    // This callback runs when ./utils module is updated
    console.log('The utils module has been updated!');
    console.log(greet('Webpack HMR (updated)!'));
  });

  module.hot.accept('./styles.css', function () {
    // style-loader/css-loader usually handles this automatically
    console.log('Styles have been updated!');
  });

  // If you don't accept an update, it bubbles up.
  // If no parent accepts, a full reload might occur.
}
```

## Key Takeaways
*   **Faster Development:** Significantly reduces development cycle time by avoiding full page reloads and preserving application state.
*   **State Preservation:** A key benefit is that it keeps your application's state intact across updates.
*   **WebSocket Communication:** Relies on a WebSocket connection between the browser and the Webpack Dev Server.
*   **Module Acceptance:** Modules can explicitly "accept" updates via `module.hot.accept()`. If not accepted, updates bubble up the module graph.
*   **Plugin-Driven:** Requires `webpack.HotModuleReplacementPlugin` and often framework-specific plugins (e.g., React Refresh Webpack Plugin) for optimal experience.
*   **Development Only:** Primarily used in development mode; not typically for production builds.

## Quick Summary
`for...of` is a loop statement that iterates over the values of an iterable object (like Arrays, Maps, Sets, Strings, etc.), while `forEach` is a method available on Array and other collection prototypes that executes a provided function once for each array element. The main differences lie in their underlying mechanisms, control flow capabilities, and what types of objects they can iterate over.

## How It Works (with practical examples)

### `for...of`
`for...of` directly works with the iteration protocol. It creates a loop iterating over iterable objects, providing direct access to each element's value.

**Key Characteristics:**
*   **Iterates over iterable objects:** Works with Arrays, Strings, Maps, Sets, NodeLists, TypedArrays, and any custom iterable.
*   **Control flow:** Supports `break`, `continue`, and `return` statements, allowing you to exit or skip iterations.
*   **Synchronous:** Executes synchronously.
*   **No callback overhead:** No function call overhead per iteration.
*   **Direct access to values:** Provides the value directly, not the index (unless combined with `entries()`).

### `forEach`
`forEach` is an Array method (also available on `Map` and `Set` objects) that takes a callback function as an argument. This callback function is executed for each element in the array, typically receiving the element's value, index, and the array itself.

**Key Characteristics:**
*   **Array method:** Primarily used with Arrays (and Map/Set methods).
*   **No control flow:** Does **not** support `break`, `continue`, or `return` (a `return` inside `forEach` only exits the callback for the current iteration, not the `forEach` loop itself). To stop or skip, you'd typically use other array methods like `some` or `every`, or a traditional `for` loop.
*   **Callback function:** Involves a function call for each element, potentially adding overhead.
*   **Provides value, index, and array:** The callback function typically receives these three arguments.
*   **Synchronous:** Executes synchronously.

## Code Example

```typescript
// Example Array
const numbers = [10, 20, 30, 40, 50];
const myString = "hello";
const mySet = new Set([1, 2, 3]);

console.log("--- Using for...of ---");

// 1. Iterating over an Array
for (const num of numbers) {
    if (num === 30) {
        console.log(`Found 30, breaking loop.`);
        break; // Can break out of the loop
    }
    console.log(`for...of Array: ${num}`);
}
// Output:
// for...of Array: 10
// for...of Array: 20
// Found 30, breaking loop.

// 2. Iterating over a String
for (const char of myString) {
    console.log(`for...of String: ${char}`);
}
// Output:
// for...of String: h
// for...of String: e
// for...of String: l
// for...of String: l
// for...of String: o

// 3. Iterating over a Set
for (const item of mySet) {
    console.log(`for...of Set: ${item}`);
}
// Output:
// for...of Set: 1
// for...of Set: 2
// for...of Set: 3


console.log("\n--- Using forEach ---");

// 1. Iterating over an Array
numbers.forEach((num, index, arr) => {
    // Cannot break or continue here
    if (num === 30) {
        console.log(`Found 30, but cannot break forEach.`);
        // return; // This only exits the current callback iteration, not the forEach loop.
    }
    console.log(`forEach Array: ${num} at index ${index} (from array length: ${arr.length})`);
});
// Output:
// forEach Array: 10 at index 0 (from array length: 5)
// forEach Array: 20 at index 1 (from array length: 5)
// Found 30, but cannot break forEach.
// forEach Array: 30 at index 2 (from array length: 5)
// forEach Array: 40 at index 3 (from array length: 5)
// forEach Array: 50 at index 4 (from array length: 5)

// forEach is not available directly on primitive strings or sets in the same way
// myString.forEach(...) // Error: myString.forEach is not a function
// mySet.forEach(...) // Set does have a forEach method, but it's less common to use than for...of for Sets.
mySet.forEach((value, key, set) => {
    console.log(`forEach Set: value=${value}, key=${key} (Set key is same as value)`);
});
// Output:
// forEach Set: value=1, key=1 (Set key is same as value)
// forEach Set: value=2, key=2 (Set key is same as value)
// forEach Set: value=3, key=3 (Set key is same as value)
```

## Key Takeaways

*   **`for...of`**:
    *   Iterates over **any iterable object** (Arrays, Strings, Maps, Sets, etc.).
    *   **Supports `break`, `continue`, `return`** for fine-grained control.
    *   Offers direct access to values, no callback function overhead.
    *   Generally preferred for simple iteration or when control flow is needed.
*   **`forEach`**:
    *   A **method on Array** (and Map/Set) prototypes.
    *   **Does NOT support `break`, `continue`, `return`** to control the loop.
    *   Uses a **callback function** for each element, providing value, index, and the array itself.
    *   Useful for performing a side effect or transformation on each element when control flow isn't required.
    *   More declarative, often used with arrow functions for conciseness.

Let's break down the differences between `for...in` and `Object.keys()`.

## Quick Summary
`for...in` iterates over all **enumerable property names** (keys), including those from the prototype chain. `Object.keys()` returns an array of an object's **own, enumerable string-keyed property names**.

## How It Works (with practical examples)

### `for...in` Loop
The `for...in` loop iterates over all **enumerable properties** of an object, including properties inherited from its prototype chain. It yields the property names (keys) as strings.

**Key characteristics:**
*   **Includes inherited properties:** It will traverse the prototype chain.
*   **Includes non-numeric keys:** It works for string keys.
*   **Order not guaranteed:** The order of iteration is not guaranteed to be consistent across JavaScript engines, although modern engines often maintain insertion order for non-array properties.
*   **DO NOT use for iterating over arrays:** It can lead to unexpected behavior due to inherited properties and non-guaranteed order. Use `for...of`, `forEach`, or a traditional `for` loop for arrays.

### `Object.keys()`
`Object.keys()` is a static method that returns an array of an object's **own, enumerable string-keyed property names**. It does not look up the prototype chain.

**Key characteristics:**
*   **Own properties only:** It only considers properties directly defined on the object itself, not inherited ones.
*   **Enumerable properties only:** Only properties whose `enumerable` attribute is `true` are included.
*   **String-keyed properties only:** It ignores `Symbol` properties.
*   **Returns an array:** The result is always an array of strings.
*   **Order guaranteed:** The order of the properties in the returned array is the same as that provided by `for...of` loops (and generally the insertion order for non-integer keys).

## Code Example

```typescript
// Define a prototype object
const proto = {
    protoProp: 'I am from the prototype',
    protoEnumerable: true,
    // protoNonEnumerable: 'This will not be seen by Object.keys if non-enumerable'
};

// Create an object inheriting from proto
const myObject = Object.create(proto);

// Add own properties
myObject.ownProp1 = 'Value 1';
myObject.ownProp2 = 'Value 2';
myObject[0] = 'Array-like property'; // Numeric key
Object.defineProperty(myObject, 'nonEnumerableProp', {
    value: 'Will not be enumerated',
    enumerable: false, // Make this property non-enumerable
});

console.log('--- Using for...in ---');
for (const key in myObject) {
    if (myObject.hasOwnProperty(key)) { // Good practice to check for own properties
        console.log(`Own Property: ${key}: ${myObject[key]}`);
    } else {
        console.log(`Inherited Property: ${key}: ${myObject[key]}`);
    }
}
// Expected Output for for...in (order might vary slightly for non-numeric keys, but generally consistent):
// Own Property: 0: Array-like property
// Own Property: ownProp1: Value 1
// Own Property: ownProp2: Value 2
// Inherited Property: protoProp: I am from the prototype
// Inherited Property: protoEnumerable: true
// (Note: nonEnumerableProp is skipped regardless of hasOwnProperty check because it's non-enumerable)


console.log('\n--- Using Object.keys() ---');
const keys = Object.keys(myObject);
console.log(keys);
// Expected Output for Object.keys():
// [ '0', 'ownProp1', 'ownProp2' ]
// (Note: protoProp, protoEnumerable, and nonEnumerableProp are all excluded)


// Example with an array
const myArray = ['a', 'b', 'c'];

console.log('\n--- for...in on an Array ---');
for (const index in myArray) {
    console.log(`Index: ${index}, Value: ${myArray[index]}`);
}
// Expected Output for for...in on Array (can include array methods if not careful):
// Index: 0, Value: a
// Index: 1, Value: b
// Index: 2, Value: c
// (Potentially other inherited properties or methods if not careful, hence why it's discouraged)

console.log('\n--- Object.keys() on an Array ---');
console.log(Object.keys(myArray));
// Expected Output for Object.keys() on Array:
// [ '0', '1', '2' ]
```

## Key Takeaways

*   `for...in` iterates over **all enumerable property names**, including those from the prototype chain. Always use `hasOwnProperty()` inside `for...in` if you only want own properties.
*   `Object.keys()` returns an array of an object's **own, enumerable string-keyed property names**. It explicitly excludes inherited and non-enumerable properties.
*   **Use `Object.keys()`** when you need an array of an object's direct, enumerable property names, especially if you plan to iterate over them or manipulate them as an array.
*   **Avoid `for...in` for arrays.** Use `for...of`, `Array.prototype.forEach()`, or a traditional `for` loop for iterating over array elements.
*   `Object.keys()` is generally safer and more predictable for getting an object's direct property names.

## Quick Summary
A **Process** is an independent execution environment that encapsulates a program's resources like memory, files, and devices. A **Thread** is a lightweight unit of execution within a process, sharing the process's resources but having its own execution stack and program counter.

## How It Works (with practical examples)

### Process
Imagine you launch two separate applications on your computer, like a web browser and a text editor. Each of these applications runs as its own **process**.

*   **Isolation:** Processes are isolated from each other. If your web browser crashes, your text editor typically remains unaffected because they operate in separate memory spaces.
*   **Resource Ownership:** Each process owns its own set of resources:
    *   **Memory Space:** A dedicated virtual address space.
    *   **File Handles:** Open files, network connections.
    *   **Environment Variables:** Its own set of environment variables.
*   **Heavyweight:** Creating a new process is resource-intensive due to the overhead of allocating a new memory space and duplicating resources.
*   **Inter-Process Communication (IPC):** Processes communicate using specific mechanisms like pipes, sockets, shared memory, or message queues.

**Analogy:** Think of a process as a separate house. Each house has its own address, its own set of furniture (resources), and if one house burns down, the others are generally safe.

### Thread
Now, inside your web browser (which is a process), you might have multiple tabs open, or it might be simultaneously downloading a file, rendering a webpage, and running a JavaScript animation. Each of these concurrent activities within the browser could be handled by a separate **thread**.

*   **Shared Resources:** Threads within the same process share the process's memory space and most of its resources (e.g., open files).
*   **Lightweight:** Creating and managing threads is much less resource-intensive than processes because they don't require new memory spaces or resource duplication.
*   **Concurrency:** Threads are primarily used to achieve concurrency within a single application, allowing it to perform multiple tasks seemingly simultaneously.
*   **Context:** Each thread has its own:
    *   **Program Counter:** Keeps track of the next instruction to execute.
    *   **Stack:** For local variables and function calls.
    *   **Registers:** CPU registers.
*   **Inter-Thread Communication:** Threads within the same process can communicate easily by directly accessing shared memory. However, this also introduces challenges like race conditions and deadlocks, requiring synchronization mechanisms (locks, mutexes, semaphores).

**Analogy:** Continuing the house analogy, threads are like different people living in the same house. They share the same address and furniture, but each person has their own tasks, thoughts (stack/program counter), and can easily talk to others in the house.

### JavaScript Context
In JavaScript, especially in a browser or Node.js environment, the main execution model is **single-threaded**. This means there's typically one main thread of execution that handles the UI, script execution, and DOM manipulation.

However, modern JavaScript environments provide mechanisms to achieve concurrency that *simulate* multi-threading without directly exposing OS threads to the developer:

*   **Web Workers (Browser):** Allow running scripts in background threads, isolated from the main UI thread. They communicate via message passing and do not share memory directly. This is the closest JS gets to traditional multi-threading.
*   **Worker Threads (Node.js):** Similar to Web Workers but for Node.js. They can share `ArrayBuffer` instances, providing a form of shared memory.
*   **Asynchronous Operations:** Much of JavaScript's "concurrency" comes from its event loop and asynchronous APIs (e.g., `setTimeout`, `fetch`, `Promise`, `async/await`). These don't create new threads but rather schedule tasks to be executed by the single main thread when it's free.

## Code Example

```typescript
// --- JavaScript (Browser/Node.js) ---

// 1. Simulating a 'Process' ( conceptually )
//    In a real OS, launching two separate Node.js scripts
//    or opening two browser tabs would be two processes.
//    Here, we can't directly show OS processes from JS.
//    But imagine these are two independent executions.

// Node.js example: Two separate scripts run as two processes
// Script 1 (process1.js):
// console.log("Process 1 started.");
// setTimeout(() => console.log("Process 1 finished."), 2000);

// Script 2 (process2.js):
// console.log("Process 2 started.");
// setTimeout(() => console.log("Process 2 finished."), 1000);

// You would run these in separate terminal windows:
// node process1.js
// node process2.js
// They run independently, their memory spaces are separate.


// 2. Simulating 'Threads' with Web Workers (Browser)
//    This is the closest JavaScript gets to explicit multi-threading,
//    where a worker runs in a separate OS thread, but communication
//    is via message passing, not shared memory (by default).

// main.js (main thread)
if (typeof Worker !== 'undefined') {
    console.log("Main thread: Starting heavy computation in a Web Worker.");

    // Create a new Web Worker (which runs in a separate OS thread)
    const myWorker = new Worker('worker.js');

    myWorker.postMessage({ number: 1000000000 }); // Send data to the worker

    myWorker.onmessage = function(e) {
        console.log(`Main thread: Message from worker: Result is ${e.data.result}`);
        if (e.data.result === 0) {
            console.log("Main thread: Computation complete!");
        }
    };

    myWorker.onerror = function(e) {
        console.error("Main thread: Worker error:", e);
    };

    console.log("Main thread: UI is responsive while worker computes...");
    // The UI remains responsive because the heavy work is offloaded
    // You could update a progress bar here, for example.

} else {
    console.warn("Web Workers are not supported in this browser.");
}

// worker.js (worker thread)
// This file runs in a separate thread.
// It does NOT have access to the DOM or window object directly.

// self refers to the global scope of the worker
self.onmessage = function(e) {
    const { number } = e.data;
    console.log(`Worker thread: Received number ${number}, starting heavy calculation...`);

    let sum = 0;
    for (let i = 0; i < number; i++) {
        sum += i; // Simulate a long-running, CPU-bound task
        if (i % (number / 10) === 0 && i !== 0) {
            // Report partial progress
            self.postMessage({ progress: i / number * 100 });
        }
    }
    console.log(`Worker thread: Calculation finished. Sum = ${sum}`);
    self.postMessage({ result: sum }); // Send result back to the main thread
};

// In Node.js, you'd use 'worker_threads' module, which is conceptually similar
// but allows for more direct shared memory with SharedArrayBuffer.
```

## Key Takeaways

*   **Process:** Independent, heavyweight execution unit with its own dedicated resources (memory, files). Provides strong isolation.
*   **Thread:** Lightweight unit of execution within a process, sharing the process's resources but with its own execution context (stack, program counter). Enables concurrency within an application.
*   **Isolation vs. Sharing:** Processes are isolated; threads within a process share resources.
*   **Overhead:** Processes have high creation/context-switching overhead; threads have low overhead.
*   **Communication:** Processes use IPC; threads use shared memory (requires synchronization).
*   **JavaScript:** Primarily single-threaded (event loop handles concurrency). Web Workers (browser) and Worker Threads (Node.js) are the main mechanisms to achieve true multi-threading by offloading tasks to separate OS threads.

Let's break down how `@import` works in CSS, along with its advantages and disadvantages.

## Quick Summary
`@import` is a CSS at-rule that allows you to import style rules from other stylesheets into the current stylesheet. It effectively pulls in external CSS files, making their styles available as if they were defined directly in the importing file.

## How It Works (with practical examples)
When a browser encounters an `@import` rule, it makes an additional HTTP request to fetch the specified stylesheet. Once downloaded, the rules within the imported stylesheet are applied. The `@import` rule must be at the very top of the stylesheet, before any other non-`@charset` rules.

**Example:**

Suppose you have two CSS files:

**`base.css`:**
```css
/* base.css */
body {
    font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
}

h1 {
    color: #333;
}
```

**`theme.css`:**
```css
/* theme.css */
@import url("base.css"); /* Imports styles from base.css */

body {
    background-color: #f0f0f0;
}

h1 {
    text-align: center;
    border-bottom: 1px solid #ccc;
    padding-bottom: 10px;
}
```

In `theme.css`, the `@import url("base.css");` line tells the browser to fetch `base.css` first. After `base.css` is loaded and its styles are applied, the remaining rules in `theme.css` are then applied. This means `h1` will have a `color` of `#333` from `base.css`, and then its `text-align`, `border-bottom`, and `padding-bottom` will be added/overridden by `theme.css`.

You can also specify media queries directly with `@import`:

```css
@import url("print.css") print; /* Only imports for print media */
@import url("mobile.css") screen and (max-width: 768px); /* Only imports for screens up to 768px */
```

## Code Example
While `@import` is a CSS feature, here's how you might conceptually link to a stylesheet that uses `@import` in an HTML file:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Using @import</title>
    <!-- The browser will load theme.css, which in turn loads base.css via @import -->
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="theme.css">
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Welcome to My Page</h1>
    <p>This paragraph uses styles from both base.css and theme.css.</p>
</body>
</html>
```

## Key Takeaways

### Pros:
*   **Modularity and Organization:** Helps break down large stylesheets into smaller, more manageable, and logically grouped files (e.g., `base.css`, `typography.css`, `forms.css`).
*   **Readability:** Improves the readability of individual CSS files by keeping them focused on specific concerns.
*   **Theming (Limited):** Can be used to create different themes by importing a base stylesheet and then overriding specific rules in a theme-specific file.

### Cons:
*   **Performance (Multiple HTTP Requests):** The primary drawback. Each `@import` rule results in an *additional* HTTP request, which can delay the rendering of the page. Browsers cannot download stylesheets imported with `@import` in parallel, leading to a "flash of unstyled content" (FOUC) or slower initial load times compared to `<link>` tags.
*   **Cascading and Specificity Issues:** Can sometimes make it harder to debug cascading issues if you're not careful about the order of imports and the specificity of rules across multiple files.
*   **Not a Preprocessor Feature:** While similar in concept, `@import` is a native CSS feature and lacks the advanced capabilities of preprocessor `@import` directives (like variable sharing or mixins).
*   **Limited Browser Support (IE 4-9 for some features):** Older versions of Internet Explorer had specific quirks or limitations with `@import` that made it less reliable, though this is less of a concern with modern browsers.
*   **Can't be used inside Media Queries:** An `@import` rule itself cannot be nested inside a `@media` block.

As a Senior Software Architect, I prioritize a robust testing strategy that includes both unit and E2E tests to ensure the quality, reliability, and maintainability of web projects. Here's how I approach it:

## Unit Testing

Unit testing focuses on individual components or functions in isolation, ensuring they perform as expected.

### Core Principles

*   **Isolation:** Each test should run independently without relying on external factors like databases, APIs, or the UI. Mocks and stubs are crucial here.
*   **Speed:** Unit tests should be extremely fast to provide quick feedback to developers.
*   **Focus:** Test a single logical unit of work per test case.
*   **Deterministic:** Given the same input, a unit test should always produce the same output.

### Tools & Frameworks

*   **Test Runner:** [Jest](https://jestjs.io/) (for its speed, rich API, and built-in mocking capabilities).
*   **Assertion Library:** Jest's built-in `expect` API.
*   **Mocking Library:** Jest's built-in mocking.
*   **Testing React Components:** [React Testing Library](https://testing-library.com/react) (focuses on user behavior rather than implementation details).

### Architecture & Strategy

1.  **Placement:** Unit tests reside alongside the code they test (e.g., `src/components/MyComponent/MyComponent.tsx` and `src/components/MyComponent/MyComponent.test.tsx`).
2.  **Naming Convention:** `*.test.ts`, `*.spec.ts`, or `*.test.tsx`.
3.  **Testable Code:** Design components and functions to be easily testable. This implies:
    *   Pure functions where possible.
    *   Dependency injection (passing dependencies as arguments or props).
    *   Minimal side effects within components.

### Example (React Component Unit Test with React Testing Library)

```typescript
// src/components/Button/Button.tsx
import React from 'react';

interface ButtonProps {
  onClick: () => void;
  label: string;
  disabled?: boolean;
}

const Button: React.FC<ButtonProps> = ({ onClick, label, disabled = false }) => {
  return (
    <button onClick={onClick} disabled={disabled}>
      {label}
    </button>
  );
};

export default Button;

// src/components/Button/Button.test.tsx
import React from 'react';
import { render, screen, fireEvent } from '@testing-library/react';
import Button from './Button';

describe('Button', () => {
  it('renders with the correct label', () => {
    render(<Button onClick={() => {}} label="Click Me" />);
    expect(screen.getByText('Click Me')).toBeInTheDocument();
  });

  it('calls onClick handler when clicked', () => {
    const handleClick = jest.fn(); // Mock function
    render(<Button onClick={handleClick} label="Test Button" />);

    fireEvent.click(screen.getByText('Test Button'));

    expect(handleClick).toHaveBeenCalledTimes(1);
  });

  it('is disabled when the disabled prop is true', () => {
    const handleClick = jest.fn();
    render(<Button onClick={handleClick} label="Disabled Button" disabled />);

    const buttonElement = screen.getByText('Disabled Button');
    expect(buttonElement).toBeDisabled();

    fireEvent.click(buttonElement); // Attempt to click
    expect(handleClick).not.toHaveBeenCalled(); // Should not call handler
  });
});
```

### Trade-offs

*   **Pros:** Fast feedback, easy to pinpoint bugs, promotes modular design, good for regression testing.
*   **Cons:** Don't verify integration between units, can lead to brittle tests if mocking is overused or tied to implementation details.

## End-to-End (E2E) Testing

E2E tests simulate real user scenarios, interacting with the entire application stack (UI, API, database) from a user's perspective in a browser environment.

### Core Principles

*   **User Flow Simulation:** Mimic how a real user would interact with the application.
*   **Black Box Testing:** Focus on what the user sees and experiences, not internal implementation.
*   **High Confidence:** Provide the highest level of confidence that critical user journeys work.
*   **Environment Agnostic:** Run against a deployed version of the application (staging or production-like environment).

### Tools & Frameworks

*   **Test Runner & Automation:** [Cypress](https://www.cypress.io/) or [Playwright](https://playwright.dev/). I lean towards Cypress for its developer experience, time-travel debugging, and automatic waiting, but Playwright offers broader browser support and a unified API for multiple languages.
*   **Assertion Library:** Built-in with Cypress/Playwright.

### Architecture & Strategy

1.  **Critical User Journeys:** Prioritize testing the most important user flows (e.g., login, registration, adding an item to a cart, checkout). E2E tests are expensive, so focus on high-value paths.
2.  **Data Setup/Teardown:** Ensure tests start from a known state. This often involves:
    *   API calls to set up test data (e.g., create a test user, clear previous data).
    *   Cleaning up data after tests.
    *   Cypress plugins for database seeding.
3.  **Idempotency:** Tests should be repeatable and not leave the system in an undesirable state.
4.  **Selectors:** Use robust selectors that are less likely to change (e.g., `data-testid` attributes) rather than brittle CSS classes or element order.
5.  **Environment:** Run E2E tests against a dedicated staging or CI/CD environment that closely mirrors production.

### Example (Cypress E2E Test)

```typescript
// cypress/e2e/login.cy.ts
describe('Login Functionality', () => {
  // Before each test, visit the login page and ensure clean state
  beforeEach(() => {
    cy.visit('/login');
    // Optionally, clear local storage or cookies if needed
    cy.clearLocalStorage();
    cy.clearCookies();
  });

  it('should allow a user to log in successfully', () => {
    // Intercept API call for login (optional, but good for stability)
    cy.intercept('POST', '/api/auth/login', {
      statusCode: 200,
      body: {
        token: 'mock-jwt-token',
        user: { id: 1, username: 'testuser' },
      },
    }).as('loginRequest');

    // Type credentials
    cy.get('[data-testid="email-input"]').type('test@example.com');
    cy.get('[data-testid="password-input"]').type('password123');

    // Click submit
    cy.get('[data-testid="login-button"]').click();

    // Assert API call was made
    cy.wait('@loginRequest').its('request.body').should('deep.include', {
      email: 'test@example.com',
      password: 'password123',
    });

    // Assert redirection to dashboard
    cy.url().should('include', '/dashboard');
    cy.get('[data-testid="welcome-message"]').should('contain.text', 'Welcome, testuser');
  });

  it('should display an error message for invalid credentials', () => {
    cy.intercept('POST', '/api/auth/login', {
      statusCode: 401,
      body: { message: 'Invalid credentials' },
    }).as('invalidLoginRequest');

    cy.get('[data-testid="email-input"]').type('wrong@example.com');
    cy.get('[data-testid="password-input"]').type('wrongpassword');
    cy.get('[data-testid="login-button"]').click();

    cy.wait('@invalidLoginRequest');
    cy.get('[data-testid="error-message"]').should('contain.text', 'Invalid credentials');
    cy.url().should('include', '/login'); // Should remain on login page
  });
});
```

### Trade-offs

*   **Pros:** High confidence, verifies full system integration, catches issues that unit tests miss, ensures critical user paths work.
*   **Cons:** Slower execution, more brittle (UI changes can break them), harder to debug, more expensive to maintain.

## Integration Testing (Brief Mention)

While not explicitly asked, I often include a layer of integration tests (e.g., testing API endpoints directly, or a component with its real dependencies but without the full browser UI) using Jest or Supertest. These fill the gap between granular unit tests and broad E2E tests, offering a good balance of speed and coverage for specific integrations.

## Overall Strategy

My typical testing pyramid looks like this:

*   **Base (Largest):** Unit Tests (fast, numerous, granular)
*   **Middle:** Integration Tests (medium speed, fewer, cover module interactions)
*   **Top (Smallest):** E2E Tests (slowest, fewest, cover critical user flows)

This layered approach ensures comprehensive coverage, fast feedback for developers, and high confidence in the application's stability. Automated testing is a critical part of the CI/CD pipeline, blocking deployments if critical tests fail.

Let's break down how to implement lazy loading for images effectively.

## Implementing Lazy Loading for Images

Lazy loading images is a technique that defers the loading of an image until it is needed (i.e., when it enters the viewport). This improves initial page load time, reduces bandwidth consumption, and enhances the user experience, especially on pages with many images below the fold.

### Core Concept

The fundamental idea is to:

1.  **Replace the `src` attribute** of the image with a placeholder or data URI.
2.  **Store the actual image URL** in a custom data attribute (e.g., `data-src`).
3.  **Monitor the image's visibility** in the viewport.
4.  **Once visible**, move the URL from `data-src` to `src`, triggering the image load.

### Architecture Patterns & Approaches

There are two primary approaches for lazy loading:

1.  **Native Browser Lazy Loading (Recommended):** The most straightforward and performant method, now widely supported.
2.  **JavaScript-based Lazy Loading:** Provides more control and fallback for older browsers or specific use cases.

#### 1. Native Browser Lazy Loading

This is the simplest and most performant method. Modern browsers natively support lazy loading images and iframes using the `loading` attribute.

##### Implementation

```html
<img
  src="placeholder.jpg"
  data-src="actual-image.jpg"
  alt="Description"
  loading="lazy"
  width="600"
  height="400"
/>
```

##### Explanation

*   `src="placeholder.jpg"`: (Optional but recommended) A low-resolution placeholder image or a transparent GIF. This prevents layout shifts while the actual image loads.
*   `data-src="actual-image.jpg"`: The actual high-resolution image URL. This is technically not needed for native lazy loading if you just use `src` directly, but it's good practice for progressive enhancement or if you might combine with JS.
*   `loading="lazy"`: This is the magic attribute. When present, the browser defers loading the image until it is within a calculated distance from the viewport.
*   `width` and `height`: **Crucial** for preventing Cumulative Layout Shift (CLS). Always specify dimensions.

##### Trade-offs & Scalability

*   **Pros:**
    *   **Performance:** Handled by the browser's highly optimized engine.
    *   **Simplicity:** No JavaScript required.
    *   **Accessibility:** Works without JavaScript enabled.
    *   **Scalability:** Effortless to apply to thousands of images.
*   **Cons:**
    *   **Browser Support:** While good, it's not 100% across all older browsers (though polyfills or JS fallbacks can be used).
    *   **Control:** Less fine-grained control over when images load compared to JS.

#### 2. JavaScript-based Lazy Loading

This method uses JavaScript to detect when an image enters the viewport. The `Intersection Observer API` is the modern and most efficient way to achieve this.

##### Implementation (Using Intersection Observer API)

```typescript
// 1. HTML Structure
// <img data-src="actual-image.jpg" src="placeholder.jpg" alt="Description" class="lazy-load-img" width="600" height="400">

// 2. TypeScript/JavaScript Code
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
  const lazyImages = document.querySelectorAll('.lazy-load-img[data-src]');

  // Check for Intersection Observer API support
  if ('IntersectionObserver' in window) {
    const lazyImageObserver = new IntersectionObserver((entries, observer) => {
      entries.forEach(entry => {
        if (entry.isIntersecting) {
          const img = entry.target as HTMLImageElement;
          const dataSrc = img.dataset.src;

          if (dataSrc) {
            img.src = dataSrc; // Load the actual image
            img.removeAttribute('data-src'); // Clean up

            // Optional: Remove loading="lazy" if it was present
            // img.removeAttribute('loading');

            observer.unobserve(img); // Stop observing once loaded
          }
        }
      });
    });

    lazyImages.forEach(img => {
      lazyImageObserver.observe(img);
    });
  } else {
    // Fallback for browsers without Intersection Observer (e.g., older IE)
    // This could involve a scroll event listener with throttling/debouncing,
    // or loading all images directly if performance is less critical for old browsers.
    console.warn('Intersection Observer not supported. Loading all images directly.');
    lazyImages.forEach(img => {
      const dataSrc = img.dataset.src;
      if (dataSrc) {
        img.src = dataSrc;
        img.removeAttribute('data-src');
      }
    });

    // A more robust fallback for older browsers would involve:
    // 1. Initial check on page load for visible images.
    // 2. Throttled/Debounced scroll event listener.
    // 3. getBoundingClientRect() to check visibility.
  }
});
```

##### Explanation

1.  **HTML:** Images start with a placeholder `src` and the true URL in `data-src`. A class (`lazy-load-img`) is used for easy selection.
2.  **`DOMContentLoaded`:** Ensures the DOM is fully parsed before script execution.
3.  **`IntersectionObserver`:**
    *   It takes a callback function and options (e.g., `rootMargin`, `threshold`).
    *   The callback executes when an observed element enters or exits the root's `threshold`.
    *   `entry.isIntersecting` tells us if the element is currently visible.
    *   When an image becomes visible (`entry.isIntersecting` is `true`):
        *   The `data-src` is moved to `src`.
        *   `data-src` is removed to prevent re-loading.
        *   The observer stops watching that specific image (`observer.unobserve(img)`).
4.  **Fallback:** A basic fallback is shown for browsers that don't support `IntersectionObserver`, loading all images directly. For production, a more sophisticated fallback with scroll event listeners and `getBoundingClientRect()` would be necessary.

##### Trade-offs & Scalability

*   **Pros:**
    *   **Precise Control:** You can define `rootMargin` (how far outside the viewport an image should load) and `threshold` (percentage of visibility before loading).
    *   **Broad Compatibility:** Works in most modern browsers, with a fallback for older ones.
    *   **Performance:** `Intersection Observer` is highly optimized and doesn't block the main thread like scroll event listeners.
*   **Cons:**
    *   **JavaScript Dependency:** Requires JavaScript to be enabled.
    *   **Complexity:** More code than native lazy loading.
    *   **Fallback Management:** Requires careful consideration for older browsers.

### General Considerations & Best Practices

*   **Placeholder Images:** Always use a low-res placeholder or a solid background color (matching the dominant color of the actual image) to prevent layout shifts and provide a better visual experience.
    *   `src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAAD/ACwAAAAAAQABAAACADs="` (tiny transparent GIF)
*   **Dimensions:** Always specify `width` and `height` attributes on `<img>` tags. This reserves space, preventing Cumulative Layout Shift (CLS), which is a crucial Web Vitals metric.
*   **Critical Images:** Do NOT lazy load images in the initial viewport (above the fold). These should load immediately to ensure a fast Largest Contentful Paint (LCP). Use a tool like Lighthouse to identify LCP candidates.
*   **`noscript` Tag:** For accessibility and SEO in cases where JavaScript might be disabled, consider a `<noscript>` fallback:

    ```html
    <img
      data-src="actual-image.jpg"
      src="placeholder.jpg"
      alt="Description"
      class="lazy-load-img"
      width="600"
      height="400"
    />
    <noscript>
      <img src="actual-image.jpg" alt="Description" width="600" height="400" />
    </noscript>
    ```

*   **Libraries:** For complex scenarios or if you prefer battle-tested solutions, consider libraries like `lazysizes` (which also handles responsive images and background images).
*   **Server-Side Rendering (SSR):** If using SSR, ensure your server-rendered HTML includes the `data-src` and `placeholder src`. The client-side JavaScript will then "hydrate" and handle the lazy loading.
*   **Lighthouse/Web Vitals:** Regularly test your implementation with Lighthouse to ensure it positively impacts metrics like LCP and CLS.

### Conclusion

For most modern web applications, **native browser lazy loading (`loading="lazy"`) is the preferred and simplest solution**. It offers excellent performance with minimal effort. However, if precise control, broader browser compatibility (with fallbacks), or specific custom behaviors are required, a JavaScript-based approach using the `Intersection Observer API` is the robust alternative. Always prioritize specifying image dimensions and avoid lazy-loading above-the-fold content.

The Observer pattern is a software design pattern where an object, called the **subject**, maintains a list of its dependents, called **observers**, and notifies them automatically of any state changes, usually by calling one of their methods. It defines a one-to-many dependency between objects so that when one object changes state, all its dependents are notified and updated automatically.

## Quick Summary
The Observer pattern establishes a "publish-subscribe" mechanism. A "subject" (publisher) holds a list of "observers" (subscribers) and automatically notifies them of any state changes. This decouples the subject from its observers, making the system more modular and flexible.

## How It Works (with practical examples)
The Observer pattern typically involves two main types of objects:

1.  **Subject (Publisher):** This object holds the state and is responsible for notifying observers when its state changes. It usually provides methods to:
    *   `addObserver()` or `subscribe()`: To register an observer.
    *   `removeObserver()` or `unsubscribe()`: To unregister an observer.
    *   `notifyObservers()` or `publish()`: To iterate through the registered observers and call their update method.

2.  **Observer (Subscriber):** This object wants to be informed of changes in the subject's state. It usually implements an `update()` method that the subject calls when a change occurs.

**Practical Example:** Imagine a stock market application. A stock (the Subject) changes its price. Many users (Observers) are interested in this stock and want to be notified when its price changes. Instead of the stock object knowing about every user, it simply notifies all registered observers.

Another common example is event handling in web browsers:
*   The DOM element is the Subject.
*   Your event listener function is the Observer.
*   `addEventListener()` registers your observer.
*   When the event occurs, the DOM element `notifyObservers()` by calling your function.

## Code Example (TypeScript)

```typescript
// 1. Define the Observer interface
interface Observer {
    update(data: any): void;
}

// 2. Define the Subject (Publisher)
class StockSubject {
    private observers: Observer[] = [];
    private stockPrice: number;
    private stockName: string;

    constructor(name: string, initialPrice: number) {
        this.stockName = name;
        this.stockPrice = initialPrice;
    }

    // Method to add an observer
    addObserver(observer: Observer): void {
        this.observers.push(observer);
        console.log(`${observer.constructor.name} subscribed to ${this.stockName}`);
    }

    // Method to remove an observer
    removeObserver(observer: Observer): void {
        this.observers = this.observers.filter(obs => obs !== observer);
        console.log(`${observer.constructor.name} unsubscribed from ${this.stockName}`);
    }

    // Method to notify all registered observers
    private notifyObservers(): void {
        const data = { name: this.stockName, price: this.stockPrice };
        console.log(`Notifying observers about ${this.stockName} price change to $${this.stockPrice}`);
        for (const observer of this.observers) {
            observer.update(data);
        }
    }

    // Method to change the stock price (triggers notification)
    setPrice(newPrice: number): void {
        if (this.stockPrice !== newPrice) {
            this.stockPrice = newPrice;
            this.notifyObservers();
        }
    }

    getPrice(): number {
        return this.stockPrice;
    }
}

// 3. Define Concrete Observers
class UserDisplay implements Observer {
    private userName: string;

    constructor(name: string) {
        this.userName = name;
    }

    update(data: { name: string, price: number }): void {
        console.log(`[${this.userName}] Stock "${data.name}" price updated to: $${data.price}`);
    }
}

class TradingBot implements Observer {
    private botId: string;

    constructor(id: string) {
        this.botId = id;
    }

    update(data: { name: string, price: number }): void {
        if (data.price < 100) {
            console.log(`[TradingBot-${this.botId}] ALERT: ${data.name} price is $${data.price}. Consider buying!`);
        } else {
            console.log(`[TradingBot-${this.botId}] ${data.name} price is $${data.price}. Monitoring...`);
        }
    }
}

// --- Usage ---
const googleStock = new StockSubject("GOOG", 150);

const userAlice = new UserDisplay("Alice");
const userBob = new UserDisplay("Bob");
const botAlpha = new TradingBot("Alpha");

// Alice and Bot Alpha subscribe to Google stock updates
googleStock.addObserver(userAlice);
googleStock.addObserver(botAlpha);

console.log("\n--- First Price Change ---");
googleStock.setPrice(152); // Alice and Bot Alpha are notified

console.log("\n--- Second Price Change ---");
googleStock.setPrice(148); // Alice and Bot Alpha are notified (Bot Alpha triggers an alert)

// Bob subscribes
googleStock.addObserver(userBob);

console.log("\n--- Third Price Change ---");
googleStock.setPrice(95); // Alice, Bob, and Bot Alpha are notified (Bot Alpha triggers an alert)

// Alice unsubscribes
googleStock.removeObserver(userAlice);

console.log("\n--- Fourth Price Change ---");
googleStock.setPrice(105); // Only Bob and Bot Alpha are notified now
```

## Key Takeaways
*   **Decoupling:** Subjects and observers are loosely coupled. They don't need to know the concrete details of each other, only that they adhere to an interface (e.g., `update` method). This makes the system more maintainable and flexible.
*   **One-to-Many Dependency:** A single subject can have multiple observers, and all will be notified automatically upon state changes.
*   **Event-Driven Systems:** It's fundamental to building event-driven architectures and is extensively used in UI frameworks, reactive programming (RxJS), and general event handling.
*   **Scalability:** You can add new observers without modifying the subject, and vice-versa, as long as the interfaces are respected.
*   **Potential for Performance Issues:** If there are many observers or notifications are very frequent, it can lead to performance overhead. Also, managing observer subscriptions (especially unsubscription) can sometimes be tricky to prevent memory leaks.

The Proxy pattern is a structural design pattern that provides an object acting as a substitute or placeholder for another object. A proxy controls access to the original object, allowing you to perform something either before or after the request gets to the original object. This is useful for adding layers of control or functionality without modifying the original object.

## Quick Summary
The Proxy pattern provides a surrogate or placeholder for another object to control access to it. It acts as an intermediary, allowing you to add logic like lazy initialization, access control, logging, or caching around an object without directly interacting with it.

## How It Works
The core idea is to have a `Proxy` object that has the same interface as the `RealSubject` object. When a client interacts with the `Proxy`, the `Proxy` forwards the request to the `RealSubject` but can also perform additional actions before or after forwarding.

Common use cases include:

1.  **Virtual Proxy:** Lazy loading an expensive resource. The proxy creates the real object only when it's first requested.
2.  **Protection Proxy:** Controlling access to an object based on user permissions.
3.  **Remote Proxy:** Managing interactions with an object located in a different address space (e.g., a web service).
4.  **Logging Proxy:** Logging all calls to an object's methods.
5.  **Caching Proxy:** Caching results of operations to avoid re-executing them.

In JavaScript, the built-in `Proxy` object (note the capital 'P') provides a powerful and native way to implement this pattern, allowing you to intercept fundamental operations for any object.

**Example Scenario:** Imagine a sensitive `BankAccount` object where every deposit or withdrawal should be logged for auditing purposes. Instead of cluttering `BankAccount` with logging logic, we can use a `Proxy` to handle it.

## Code Example

```typescript
// 1. The Real Subject Interface (optional, but good practice for clarity)
interface BankAccount {
    getBalance(): number;
    deposit(amount: number): void;
    withdraw(amount: number): boolean;
}

// 2. The Real Subject
class RealBankAccount implements BankAccount {
    private balance: number;

    constructor(initialBalance: number) {
        this.balance = initialBalance;
        console.log(`RealBankAccount: Account created with balance $${this.balance}`);
    }

    getBalance(): number {
        return this.balance;
    }

    deposit(amount: number): void {
        if (amount > 0) {
            this.balance += amount;
            console.log(`RealBankAccount: Deposited $${amount}. New balance: $${this.balance}`);
        }
    }

    withdraw(amount: number): boolean {
        if (amount > 0 && this.balance >= amount) {
            this.balance -= amount;
            console.log(`RealBankAccount: Withdrew $${amount}. New balance: $${this.balance}`);
            return true;
        }
        console.log(`RealBankAccount: Withdrawal of $${amount} failed. Current balance: $${this.balance}`);
        return false;
    }
}

// 3. The Proxy
class BankAccountLoggingProxy implements BankAccount {
    private realAccount: RealBankAccount;

    constructor(initialBalance: number) {
        // The proxy holds a reference to the real subject
        this.realAccount = new RealBankAccount(initialBalance);
    }

    getBalance(): number {
        console.log("Proxy: Getting account balance.");
        return this.realAccount.getBalance();
    }

    deposit(amount: number): void {
        console.log(`Proxy: Logging deposit attempt of $${amount}.`);
        this.realAccount.deposit(amount);
        console.log("Proxy: Deposit operation completed.");
    }

    withdraw(amount: number): boolean {
        console.log(`Proxy: Logging withdrawal attempt of $${amount}.`);
        const success = this.realAccount.withdraw(amount);
        if (success) {
            console.log("Proxy: Withdrawal operation successful.");
        } else {
            console.log("Proxy: Withdrawal operation failed.");
        }
        return success;
    }
}

// Client Code
console.log("--- Using Proxy Account ---");
const account = new BankAccountLoggingProxy(1000); // Client interacts with the proxy

console.log(`Current Balance: $${account.getBalance()}`);

account.deposit(200);
account.withdraw(150);
account.withdraw(1500); // Should fail

console.log(`Final Balance: $${account.getBalance()}`);

console.log("\n--- Using Real Account Directly (for comparison) ---");
const directAccount = new RealBankAccount(500);
directAccount.deposit(100); // No logging from the proxy
```

**Using Native JavaScript `Proxy` object:**

The native `Proxy` object in JavaScript offers a more dynamic and less verbose way to implement this pattern, especially for generic logging, validation, or access control.

```typescript
// The Real Subject
class RealBankAccountNative {
    private _balance: number;

    constructor(initialBalance: number) {
        this._balance = initialBalance;
        console.log(`RealBankAccountNative: Account created with balance $${this._balance}`);
    }

    get balance(): number {
        return this._balance;
    }

    set balance(amount: number) {
        this._balance = amount;
    }

    deposit(amount: number): void {
        if (amount > 0) {
            this._balance += amount;
            console.log(`RealBankAccountNative: Deposited $${amount}. New balance: $${this._balance}`);
        }
    }

    withdraw(amount: number): boolean {
        if (amount > 0 && this._balance >= amount) {
            this._balance -= amount;
            console.log(`RealBankAccountNative: Withdrew $${amount}. New balance: $${this._balance}`);
            return true;
        }
        console.log(`RealBankAccountNative: Withdrawal of $${amount} failed. Current balance: $${this._balance}`);
        return false;
    }
}

console.log("\n--- Using Native JavaScript Proxy ---");
const realAccountNative = new RealBankAccountNative(700);

const bankAccountProxy = new Proxy(realAccountNative, {
    get: function(target, prop, receiver) {
        if (prop === 'balance') {
            console.log("Native Proxy: Intercepted 'balance' get.");
            return Reflect.get(target, prop, receiver);
        }
        // Log all method calls
        if (typeof target[prop as keyof RealBankAccountNative] === 'function') {
            return function(...args: any[]) {
                console.log(`Native Proxy: Calling method '${String(prop)}' with args: ${JSON.stringify(args)}`);
                const result = Reflect.apply(target[prop as keyof RealBankAccountNative] as Function, target, args);
                console.log(`Native Proxy: Method '${String(prop)}' returned: ${result}`);
                return result;
            };
        }
        return Reflect.get(target, prop, receiver);
    },
    set: function(target, prop, value, receiver) {
        if (prop === 'balance') {
            console.log(`Native Proxy: Intercepted 'balance' set to ${value}.`);
            // Add validation, e.g., balance cannot be negative
            if (value < 0) {
                console.error("Native Proxy: Cannot set balance to a negative value!");
                return false;
            }
        }
        return Reflect.set(target, prop, value, receiver);
    }
});

// Client interacts with the native proxy
console.log(`Current Balance via Proxy: $${bankAccountProxy.balance}`); // Triggers get trap

bankAccountProxy.deposit(300); // Triggers get trap for 'deposit', then apply trap
bankAccountProxy.withdraw(100); // Triggers get trap for 'withdraw', then apply trap

bankAccountProxy.balance = -50; // Triggers set trap, shows error
console.log(`Final Balance via Proxy: $${bankAccountProxy.balance}`);
```

## Key Takeaways

*   **Controlled Access:** The primary purpose of the Proxy pattern is to provide controlled access to another object.
*   **Decoupling:** It allows you to add extra functionality (like logging, caching, security) without modifying the original object, promoting the Single Responsibility Principle.
*   **Same Interface:** The proxy usually implements the same interface as the real subject, so clients can use them interchangeably.
*   **Lazy Loading:** A common application is virtual proxies, which defer the creation of expensive objects until they are actually needed.
*   **Native `Proxy` in JS:** JavaScript offers a built-in `Proxy` object that provides a powerful and flexible way to implement this pattern by intercepting fundamental operations on objects.
*   **Trade-offs:** While powerful, using proxies can add a layer of indirection, which might slightly impact performance or make debugging more complex if not used judiciously.

## Quick Summary
Both `setTimeout` and `setInterval` are global JavaScript functions used to schedule the execution of a function after a specified delay. The key difference is that `setTimeout` executes a function **once** after the delay, while `setInterval` executes a function **repeatedly** after every given delay until it's explicitly stopped.

## How It Works (with practical examples)

### setTimeout
`setTimeout(function, delayInMilliseconds)` schedules a function to run **one time** after the `delayInMilliseconds` has passed. It returns a numeric `timeoutID` which can be used with `clearTimeout()` to cancel the scheduled execution before it happens.

**Practical Use Case:** Displaying a "Thank you" message after a form submission delay, or deferring an animation to allow other rendering to complete first.

### setInterval
`setInterval(function, delayInMilliseconds)` schedules a function to run **repeatedly** every `delayInMilliseconds`. It returns a numeric `intervalID` which can be used with `clearInterval()` to stop the recurring execution. If not cleared, the function will continue to run indefinitely.

**Practical Use Case:** Creating a real-time clock display, updating a stock price ticker, or implementing a slideshow that changes images every few seconds.

## Code Example

```typescript
// --- setTimeout Example ---
console.log("setTimeout: Start");

const timeoutId = setTimeout(() => {
  console.log("setTimeout: This message appears after 2 seconds (once).");
}, 2000); // 2000 milliseconds = 2 seconds

// You can cancel setTimeout before it executes
// clearTimeout(timeoutId); // Uncomment to prevent the message from showing

console.log("setTimeout: End (will display before the timeout message)");

// --- setInterval Example ---
console.log("\nsetInterval: Start");

let counter = 0;
const intervalId = setInterval(() => {
  counter++;
  console.log(`setInterval: This message appears every 1 second. Counter: ${counter}`);

  if (counter >= 3) {
    clearInterval(intervalId); // Stop the interval after 3 executions
    console.log("setInterval: Stopped after 3 counts.");
  }
}, 1000); // 1000 milliseconds = 1 second

console.log("setInterval: End (will display before the interval messages)");
```

**Expected Output (approximately):**
```
setTimeout: Start
setTimeout: End (will display before the timeout message)

setInterval: Start
setInterval: End (will display before the interval messages)
setInterval: This message appears every 1 second. Counter: 1
setInterval: This message appears every 1 second. Counter: 2
setInterval: This message appears every 1 second. Counter: 3
setInterval: Stopped after 3 counts.
setTimeout: This message appears after 2 seconds (once).
```
*Note: The exact order of `setTimeout`'s final message relative to `setInterval`'s messages might vary slightly due to event loop timing, but the key is that `setTimeout` fires once while `setInterval` fires repeatedly.*

## Key Takeaways
*   **`setTimeout`**: Executes a function **once** after a specified delay.
*   **`setInterval`**: Executes a function **repeatedly** at a fixed interval until stopped.
*   **Cancellation**: Both return an ID (`timeoutID` or `intervalID`) that can be used with `clearTimeout()` or `clearInterval()` respectively to cancel scheduled execution.
*   **Use Cases**: `setTimeout` for one-off delayed tasks; `setInterval` for continuous, periodic tasks.
*   **Accuracy**: The specified delay is a *minimum* delay. The actual execution might be slightly longer due to factors like the event queue being busy or browser tab throttling.

Finding performance bottlenecks in a web application involves a systematic approach of measurement, analysis, and optimization. It's an iterative process that requires understanding both client-side and server-side performance characteristics.

## Quick Summary
Identifying performance bottlenecks requires a blend of tooling and methodology. It typically involves using browser developer tools, profiling server-side code, and leveraging specialized monitoring services to pinpoint specific areas (e.g., slow network requests, heavy JavaScript execution, inefficient rendering, or database queries) that are slowing down the user experience.

## How It Works (with practical examples)

### 1. Define Performance Goals & Baseline
Before optimizing, understand what "fast" means for your application. Use metrics like Largest Contentful Paint (LCP), First Input Delay (FID), Cumulative Layout Shift (CLS), Time to Interactive (TTI), and Total Blocking Time (TBT). Establish a baseline by measuring current performance.

**Example:** For an e-commerce product page, a goal might be LCP < 2.5s and TTI < 3s on a mobile device with a slow 3G connection.

### 2. Client-Side Analysis (Browser Developer Tools)
This is typically the first place to look as many bottlenecks are client-side.

*   **Lighthouse/PageSpeed Insights:** Provides an automated audit with actionable recommendations for performance, accessibility, best practices, and SEO. It gives a good high-level overview and points to common issues.
    *   **Practical Use:** Run Lighthouse on your key pages (homepage, product page, checkout) to get an initial score and list of opportunities.
*   **Performance Tab (Chrome DevTools):** Records a timeline of network requests, JavaScript execution, rendering, and painting.
    *   **Practical Use:**
        1.  Open DevTools, go to the "Performance" tab.
        2.  Click the record button.
        3.  Interact with your app (e.g., load a page, click a button).
        4.  Stop recording.
        5.  Analyze the flame chart:
            *   **Long tasks (red triangles):** Indicate JavaScript blocking the main thread. Zoom into these to see which functions are taking time.
            *   **Layout/Recalculate Style:** Frequent or complex layout recalculations can indicate rendering bottlenecks.
            *   **Scripting:** See which JavaScript functions are consuming the most time.
            *   **Network:** Identify large resources or slow requests.
*   **Network Tab (Chrome DevTools):** Shows all network requests, their timing, size, and type.
    *   **Practical Use:**
        1.  Filter by type (JS, CSS, Img, XHR).
        2.  Sort by size or time.
        3.  Look for:
            *   **Large assets:** Images not optimized, unminified JS/CSS.
            *   **Slow requests:** API calls taking too long.
            *   **Request waterfalls:** Identify blocking resources or too many sequential requests.
*   **Memory Tab (Chrome DevTools):** Helps identify memory leaks or excessive memory usage.
    *   **Practical Use:** Take heap snapshots before and after a sequence of actions (e.g., opening/closing a modal multiple times). Compare snapshots to see if detached DOM nodes or other objects are accumulating.

### 3. Server-Side Analysis
If client-side analysis doesn't fully explain the slowness, the backend is the next suspect.

*   **Application Performance Monitoring (APM) Tools:** Services like New Relic, Datadog, Dynatrace, or Sentry monitor server-side application performance, database queries, external service calls, and error rates.
    *   **Practical Use:** Instrument your backend code. APM tools will show you:
        *   Which API endpoints are slowest.
        *   Which database queries are taking the most time.
        *   External service dependencies that are slow.
        *   CPU/memory usage of your servers.
*   **Server Logs:** Review server logs for errors, slow query warnings, or unusual activity.
*   **Database Profiling:** Most databases (PostgreSQL, MySQL, MongoDB) have built-in profiling tools to identify slow queries, missing indexes, or inefficient schema designs.
    *   **Practical Use (PostgreSQL example):** Use `EXPLAIN ANALYZE` to understand query execution plans.
        ```sql
        EXPLAIN ANALYZE SELECT * FROM products WHERE category = 'electronics' AND price > 100 ORDER BY price DESC;
        ```
        This output will show the cost and actual execution time of each step, highlighting potential index issues or full table scans.
*   **Load Testing:** Tools like JMeter, k6, or Artillery can simulate high user loads to find bottlenecks under stress, which might not appear in local testing.

### 4. Real User Monitoring (RUM)
Tools like Google Analytics (with speed reports), Sentry, or dedicated RUM services (e.g., SpeedCurve, Raygun) collect performance data from actual users in the wild.

*   **Practical Use:** RUM data helps identify performance issues specific to certain demographics, devices, network conditions, or geographic regions that synthetic testing might miss. It provides a holistic view of user experience.

## Code Example (Identifying a Client-Side JS Bottleneck)

Let's say you've identified a "long task" in the Performance tab. Zooming in, you see a function `processLargeData` is taking a significant amount of time.

```typescript
// Original problematic function
function processLargeData(data: number[]): number[] {
    console.time('processLargeData');
    const result: number[] = [];
    for (let i = 0; i < data.length; i++) {
        // Simulate a CPU-intensive operation
        let sum = 0;
        for (let j = 0; j < 1000; j++) { // This inner loop makes it slow
            sum += Math.sqrt(data[i] + j);
        }
        result.push(sum);
    }
    console.timeEnd('processLargeData');
    return result;
}

// Example usage
const largeArray = Array.from({ length: 5000 }, (_, i) => i);
// const processedData = processLargeData(largeArray); // This would block the UI

// Optimization using requestIdleCallback or setTimeout to break up the work
function processLargeDataOptimized(data: number[], onComplete: (result: number[]) => void) {
    const result: number[] = [];
    let currentIndex = 0;
    const chunkSize = 50; // Process 50 items at a time

    function processChunk(deadline?: IdleDeadline) {
        const startTime = performance.now();
        while (currentIndex < data.length &&
               (deadline ? deadline.timeRemaining() > 0 : performance.now() - startTime < 10)) { // Process for max 10ms
            let sum = 0;
            for (let j = 0; j < 1000; j++) {
                sum += Math.sqrt(data[currentIndex] + j);
            }
            result.push(sum);
            currentIndex++;
        }

        if (currentIndex < data.length) {
            // If not done, schedule the next chunk
            if (window.requestIdleCallback) {
                requestIdleCallback(processChunk);
            } else {
                setTimeout(() => processChunk(), 16); // Fallback for older browsers
            }
        } else {
            // All data processed
            onComplete(result);
        }
    }

    if (window.requestIdleCallback) {
        requestIdleCallback(processChunk);
    } else {
        setTimeout(() => processChunk(), 0); // Start processing
    }
}

// How to use the optimized version
console.log("Starting optimized processing...");
processLargeDataOptimized(largeArray, (processedData) => {
    console.log("Optimized processing complete!", processedData.length);
});
console.log("UI remains responsive during processing...");
```
In this example, the original `processLargeData` function would block the main thread, leading to a "long task" and unresponsive UI. The optimized `processLargeDataOptimized` breaks the work into smaller chunks using `requestIdleCallback` (or `setTimeout` as a fallback), allowing the browser to render and respond to user input between chunks, improving perceived performance and interactivity.

## Key Takeaways

*   **Start with Lighthouse/PageSpeed Insights:** Get a quick overview and identify common issues.
*   **Deep Dive with DevTools:** Use the Performance tab for JS/rendering bottlenecks and the Network tab for resource loading issues.
*   **Balance Client-Side & Server-Side:** Don't forget the backend. APM tools and database profiling are crucial.
*   **Measure, Optimize, Verify:** Performance optimization is an iterative cycle. Always measure before and after changes.
*   **Context Matters:** Understand your user base, devices, and network conditions. What's fast for one might be slow for another.
*   **Focus on User-Centric Metrics:** Prioritize metrics that directly impact user experience (LCP, FID, CLS).
*   **Don't Guess, Measure:** Avoid premature optimization. Always base your efforts on data.

## Quick Summary
The Decorator pattern is a structural design pattern that allows behavior to be added to an individual object, dynamically, without affecting the behavior of other objects from the same class. It wraps an object with a "decorator" object that provides the new functionality while delegating to the original object.

## How It Works (with practical examples)
The Decorator pattern works by creating a set of decorator classes that wrap a component. Both the component and the decorators share a common interface (or base class), ensuring that a client can interact with either a plain component or a decorated one in the same way. When a method is called on a decorator, it can perform its own logic before or after calling the same method on the wrapped component.

**Practical Example:** Imagine a coffee shop. You start with a basic coffee. You can then "decorate" it with milk, sugar, or whipped cream. Each addition changes the coffee's description and cost without changing the fundamental `Coffee` object itself.

1.  **Component Interface:** Defines the common operations for both concrete components and decorators.
2.  **Concrete Component:** The original object to which new behaviors can be attached.
3.  **Base Decorator:** An abstract class (or interface in TypeScript) that holds a reference to a component object and implements the component interface.
4.  **Concrete Decorators:** Specific decorator classes that add new behaviors or responsibilities.

## Code Example (TypeScript)

Let's implement the coffee example:

```typescript
// 1. Component Interface
interface Coffee {
    getCost(): number;
    getDescription(): string;
}

// 2. Concrete Component
class SimpleCoffee implements Coffee {
    getCost(): number {
        return 5;
    }

    getDescription(): string {
        return "Simple Coffee";
    }
}

// 3. Base Decorator
// Note: In TypeScript, we can use an abstract class to implement the interface
// and hold the component reference, acting as the base for concrete decorators.
abstract class CoffeeDecorator implements Coffee {
    protected coffee: Coffee;

    constructor(coffee: Coffee) {
        this.coffee = coffee;
    }

    // Delegate to the wrapped coffee by default
    getCost(): number {
        return this.coffee.getCost();
    }

    getDescription(): string {
        return this.coffee.getDescription();
    }
}

// 4. Concrete Decorators
class MilkDecorator extends CoffeeDecorator {
    constructor(coffee: Coffee) {
        super(coffee);
    }

    getCost(): number {
        return super.getCost() + 2; // Add cost of milk
    }

    getDescription(): string {
        return super.getDescription() + ", Milk"; // Add milk to description
    }
}

class SugarDecorator extends CoffeeDecorator {
    constructor(coffee: Coffee) {
        super(coffee);
    }

    getCost(): number {
        return super.getCost() + 1; // Add cost of sugar
    }

    getDescription(): string {
        return super.getDescription() + ", Sugar"; // Add sugar to description
    }
}

class WhippedCreamDecorator extends CoffeeDecorator {
    constructor(coffee: Coffee) {
        super(coffee);
    }

    getCost(): number {
        return super.getCost() + 3; // Add cost of whipped cream
    }

    getDescription(): string {
        return super.getDescription() + ", Whipped Cream"; // Add whipped cream to description
    }
}

// Client Usage
let myCoffee: Coffee = new SimpleCoffee();
console.log(`Cost: $${myCoffee.getCost()}, Description: ${myCoffee.getDescription()}`);
// Output: Cost: $5, Description: Simple Coffee

myCoffee = new MilkDecorator(myCoffee);
console.log(`Cost: $${myCoffee.getCost()}, Description: ${myCoffee.getDescription()}`);
// Output: Cost: $7, Description: Simple Coffee, Milk

myCoffee = new SugarDecorator(myCoffee);
console.log(`Cost: $${myCoffee.getCost()}, Description: ${myCoffee.getDescription()}`);
// Output: Cost: $8, Description: Simple Coffee, Milk, Sugar

myCoffee = new WhippedCreamDecorator(myCoffee);
console.log(`Cost: $${myCoffee.getCost()}, Description: ${myCoffee.getDescription()}`);
// Output: Cost: $11, Description: Simple Coffee, Milk, Sugar, Whipped Cream

// You can also create a coffee with decorators in a different order or combination
let anotherCoffee: Coffee = new SimpleCoffee();
anotherCoffee = new SugarDecorator(new MilkDecorator(anotherCoffee));
console.log(`Cost: $${anotherCoffee.getCost()}, Description: ${anotherCoffee.getDescription()}`);
// Output: Cost: $8, Description: Simple Coffee, Milk, Sugar
```

## Key Takeaways

*   **Dynamic Behavior Addition:** Allows adding new responsibilities to objects at runtime, rather than compile-time.
*   **Alternative to Subclassing:** Provides a flexible alternative to extending classes via inheritance, which can lead to a "class explosion" when many combinations of features are needed.
*   **Open/Closed Principle:** Adheres to the Open/Closed Principle (open for extension, closed for modification) because you can introduce new decorator types without changing existing component or decorator classes.
*   **Composition over Inheritance:** Favors composition (wrapping objects) over inheritance for extending functionality.
*   **Transparency:** Clients can treat decorated objects and original objects uniformly if they share a common interface.

## Quick Summary
ES6 Classes provide a much cleaner, more syntactical sugar way to create constructor functions and manage prototypes compared to the verbose and often confusing ES5 constructor/prototype pattern. While ES6 classes are not truly "classes" in the traditional object-oriented sense (they are still prototype-based under the hood), they offer a more familiar and maintainable syntax for developers.

## How It Works
The core difference lies in their syntax and how they express the concept of an object blueprint and inheritance.

**ES5 Implementation:**
In ES5, you create a "class" by defining a constructor function. Methods are then added to the constructor's `prototype` property to ensure they are shared among all instances, saving memory. Inheritance is achieved by manually chaining prototypes using `Object.create()` and reassigning the constructor.

**ES6 Class Implementation:**
ES6 Classes provide a dedicated syntax for defining classes, constructors, methods, getters, setters, static methods, and inheritance (`extends`, `super`). This syntax abstracts away the direct manipulation of the prototype chain, making the code much easier to read and write, especially for those familiar with class-based languages like Java or C++.

**Practical Example:**
Let's consider a simple `Person` class with a `greet` method and then extend it to a `Developer` class.

### ES5 Implementation Example
```javascript
// ES5 Constructor Function
function Person(name, age) {
  this.name = name;
  this.age = age;
}

// ES5 Prototype Methods
Person.prototype.greet = function() {
  return `Hello, my name is ${this.name} and I am ${this.age} years old.`;
};

// ES5 Inheritance
function Developer(name, age, skills) {
  // Call the parent constructor
  Person.call(this, name, age);
  this.skills = skills;
}

// Inherit prototype methods from Person
Developer.prototype = Object.create(Person.prototype);
// Reset the constructor to Developer
Developer.prototype.constructor = Developer;

// Add a method specific to Developer
Developer.prototype.code = function() {
  return `${this.name} is coding with ${this.skills.join(', ')}.`;
};

const person5 = new Person('Alice', 30);
console.log(person5.greet()); // Hello, my name is Alice and I am 30 years old.

const dev5 = new Developer('Bob', 25, ['JavaScript', 'TypeScript']);
console.log(dev5.greet()); // Hello, my name is Bob and I am 25 years old.
console.log(dev5.code());  // Bob is coding with JavaScript, TypeScript.
```

### ES6 Class Implementation Example
```typescript
// ES6 Class
class Person {
  name: string;
  age: number;

  constructor(name: string, age: number) {
    this.name = name;
    this.age = age;
  }

  greet(): string {
    return `Hello, my name is ${this.name} and I am ${this.age} years old.`;
  }
}

// ES6 Class Inheritance
class Developer extends Person {
  skills: string[];

  constructor(name: string, age: number, skills: string[]) {
    // Call the parent constructor
    super(name, age);
    this.skills = skills;
  }

  code(): string {
    return `${this.name} is coding with ${this.skills.join(', ')}.`;
  }
}

const person6 = new Person('Alice', 30);
console.log(person6.greet()); // Hello, my name is Alice and I am 30 years old.

const dev6 = new Developer('Bob', 25, ['JavaScript', 'TypeScript']);
console.log(dev6.greet()); // Hello, my name is Bob and I am 25 years old.
console.log(dev6.code());  // Bob is coding with JavaScript, TypeScript.
```

## Key Takeaways
*   **Syntactic Sugar:** ES6 Classes are primarily syntactic sugar over ES5's prototype-based inheritance. They don't introduce a new object model but provide a more convenient syntax.
*   **Readability & Maintainability:** ES6 Classes significantly improve code readability and maintainability, especially for complex inheritance hierarchies, by abstracting away the manual prototype manipulation.
*   **`constructor` Method:** In ES6, the `constructor` method within a class is equivalent to the ES5 constructor function.
*   **`extends` and `super`:** ES6 introduces `extends` for inheritance and `super` to call the parent class's constructor or methods, making inheritance much cleaner than ES5's manual `Object.create()` and `call()` patterns.
*   **Hoisting:** ES5 constructor functions are hoisted, meaning you can call `new Person()` before its definition. ES6 classes are not hoisted in the same way; you must define a class before you can instantiate it (similar to `let`/`const` behavior, they exist in the Temporal Dead Zone).
*   **Strict Mode:** ES6 class bodies are always executed in strict mode, even if the surrounding code is not. ES5 functions are not inherently strict mode.

The Factory Pattern is a creational design pattern that provides an interface for creating objects in a superclass, but allows subclasses to alter the type of objects that will be created. It centralizes object creation, making the system more robust and less coupled by delegating the instantiation logic to specialized "factory" methods.

## Quick Summary
The Factory Pattern simplifies object creation by defining a dedicated method (the "factory method") that handles the instantiation logic. This allows you to create different types of objects based on an input parameter or configuration without exposing the complex creation logic to the client code, promoting loose coupling and easier maintenance.

## How It Works
The core idea is to encapsulate the object creation process. Instead of directly calling a constructor (e.g., `new Car()`), you call a factory method (e.g., `vehicleFactory.createVehicle('car')`) which then returns an instance of the desired object.

This is particularly useful when:
1.  **You don't know the exact types of objects your code will need to work with beforehand.** The factory can decide which concrete class to instantiate based on runtime conditions or configuration.
2.  **You want to centralize object creation.** If the creation logic for an object is complex (e.g., involves multiple steps, dependency injection), the factory can handle it, keeping the client code clean.
3.  **You want to decouple the client code from the concrete classes.** The client only interacts with the factory and the common interface/superclass of the created objects, not the specific implementations.

**Practical Example:**
Imagine you're building a game where you need to create different types of enemies (e.g., `Goblin`, `Orc`, `Dragon`). Each enemy might have unique properties or methods, but they all share a common `Enemy` interface. A factory can take an enemy type as input and return the corresponding enemy instance. If you add a new enemy type later, you only need to modify the factory, not all the places where enemies are created.

## Code Example

```typescript
// 1. Define a common interface for the products
interface Enemy {
    attack(): string;
    health: number;
}

// 2. Implement concrete products
class Goblin implements Enemy {
    health = 50;
    attack() {
        return "Goblin attacks with a rusty dagger!";
    }
}

class Orc implements Enemy {
    health = 100;
    attack() {
        return "Orc smashes with a club!";
    }
}

class Dragon implements Enemy {
    health = 500;
    attack() {
        return "Dragon breathes fire!";
    }
}

// 3. Implement the Factory
class EnemyFactory {
    public static createEnemy(type: string): Enemy | null {
        switch (type.toLowerCase()) {
            case "goblin":
                return new Goblin();
            case "orc":
                return new Orc();
            case "dragon":
                return new Dragon();
            default:
                console.warn(`Unknown enemy type: ${type}`);
                return null;
        }
    }
}

// 4. Client code uses the factory to create objects
console.log("--- Creating Enemies ---");

const goblin = EnemyFactory.createEnemy("goblin");
if (goblin) {
    console.log(`Goblin health: ${goblin.health}`);
    console.log(goblin.attack());
}

const orc = EnemyFactory.createEnemy("Orc");
if (orc) {
    console.log(`Orc health: ${orc.health}`);
    console.log(orc.attack());
}

const dragon = EnemyFactory.createEnemy("DRAGON");
if (dragon) {
    console.log(`Dragon health: ${dragon.health}`);
    console.log(dragon.attack());
}

const unknownEnemy = EnemyFactory.createEnemy("slime"); // This will log a warning
if (unknownEnemy) {
    console.log(unknownEnemy.attack());
} else {
    console.log("Failed to create unknown enemy.");
}

console.log("\n--- Applying polymorphism ---");
const enemies: Enemy[] = [];
enemies.push(EnemyFactory.createEnemy("goblin")!);
enemies.push(EnemyFactory.createEnemy("orc")!);
enemies.push(EnemyFactory.createEnemy("dragon")!);

enemies.forEach(enemy => {
    console.log(`Enemy health: ${enemy.health}, Attack: ${enemy.attack()}`);
});
```

## Key Takeaways
*   **Encapsulates Creation Logic:** Hides the complexity of object instantiation from the client code.
*   **Promotes Loose Coupling:** Client code depends on the factory and the common interface, not on concrete product classes. This makes the system more flexible.
*   **Centralized Control:** All object creation logic is managed in one place, making it easier to maintain and extend (e.g., adding new product types only requires modifying the factory).
*   **Polymorphism:** Allows the creation of different objects that share a common interface, enabling polymorphic behavior in client code.
*   **Scalability:** Easier to add new product types without altering existing client code, adhering to the Open/Closed Principle.

## Quick Summary
A Promise is an object representing the eventual completion or failure of an asynchronous operation and its resulting value. It allows you to write asynchronous code in a more synchronous-like, readable manner, avoiding callback hell.

## How It Works
A Promise can be in one of three states:
1.  **Pending**: Initial state, neither fulfilled nor rejected.
2.  **Fulfilled (Resolved)**: Meaning that the operation completed successfully.
3.  **Rejected**: Meaning that the operation failed.

Once a Promise is fulfilled or rejected, it becomes **settled** and its state cannot change again. You attach callbacks to a Promise using `.then()` for success and `.catch()` for failure.

### Resolving a bunch of Promises in order:
To resolve a bunch of Promises in a specific, sequential order (one after another), you can use `async/await` with a `for...of` loop or `Array.prototype.reduce()`. This ensures that each Promise fully settles before the next one in the sequence begins execution.

**Practical Example:** Imagine fetching data for a list of user IDs, but you want to fetch them one by one to avoid overwhelming the server or to process them sequentially based on some dependency.

## Code Example

```typescript
// --- Part 1: What is a Promise? ---

// A simple function that returns a Promise
function fetchData(id: number): Promise<string> {
    return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
        const delay = Math.random() * 1000 + 500; // Random delay between 500ms and 1500ms
        setTimeout(() => {
            if (id % 2 === 0) {
                resolve(`Data for ID ${id} fetched successfully!`);
            } else {
                reject(new Error(`Failed to fetch data for ID ${id}`));
            }
        }, delay);
    });
}

console.log("--- Demonstrating a single Promise ---");

// Using .then() and .catch()
fetchData(2)
    .then(data => console.log(data)) // Output: Data for ID 2 fetched successfully!
    .catch(error => console.error(error.message));

fetchData(3)
    .then(data => console.log(data))
    .catch(error => console.error(error.message)); // Output: Failed to fetch data for ID 3

// --- Part 2: Resolving a bunch of Promises in order ---

console.log("\n--- Resolving Promises in order (sequential) ---");

const userIds = [101, 102, 103, 104, 105];

// Method 1: Using async/await with a for...of loop
async function fetchSequentiallyAsyncAwait(ids: number[]) {
    console.log("Starting sequential fetch with async/await...");
    for (const id of ids) {
        try {
            const result = await fetchData(id); // Await each promise
            console.log(`[Async/Await] ${result}`);
        } catch (error: any) {
            console.error(`[Async/Await] Error for ID ${id}: ${error.message}`);
        }
    }
    console.log("Finished sequential fetch with async/await.");
}

// Method 2: Using Array.prototype.reduce()
function fetchSequentiallyReduce(ids: number[]) {
    console.log("Starting sequential fetch with .reduce()...");
    let promiseChain = Promise.resolve(); // Initial resolved promise

    ids.forEach(id => {
        promiseChain = promiseChain.then(() => fetchData(id))
            .then(data => console.log(`[Reduce] ${data}`))
            .catch(error => console.error(`[Reduce] Error for ID ${id}: ${error.message}`));
    });

    return promiseChain.finally(() => console.log("Finished sequential fetch with .reduce()."));
}

// Execute the sequential fetches
fetchSequentiallyAsyncAwait(userIds);

// To avoid race conditions in console output, you might want to chain them
// or run them separately. For demonstration, we'll just call both.
// Note: Output order of the two methods might interleave due to async nature
// if not explicitly chained.
// fetchSequentiallyReduce(userIds); // Uncomment to see reduce method in action
```

## Key Takeaways
*   **Asynchronous Handling**: Promises are fundamental for managing asynchronous operations gracefully, preventing "callback hell."
*   **States**: A Promise transitions from `pending` to either `fulfilled` or `rejected`, becoming `settled`.
*   **Chaining (`.then()`, `.catch()`)**: Allows sequential execution of asynchronous tasks and robust error handling.
*   **Sequential Resolution**: To execute promises one after another, `async/await` with a loop (e.g., `for...of`) or `Array.prototype.reduce()` are effective patterns. This ensures that the previous promise completes before the next one starts.
*   **`Promise.all()` vs. Sequential**: `Promise.all()` executes promises concurrently (in parallel) and waits for all to settle. Sequential execution runs them one by one. Choose based on whether tasks are independent or dependent.

## Quick Summary
Non-strict mode (also known as "sloppy mode") is the default operating mode for JavaScript that predates the introduction of strict mode in ECMAScript 5. We typically need to use it when dealing with legacy codebases that were written before strict mode became common practice, or when working with environments that don't fully support strict mode (though this is increasingly rare for modern browsers/Node.js).

## How It Works (with practical examples)
Non-strict mode allows for certain behaviors that are considered problematic or error-prone in modern JavaScript development. These include:

1.  **Implicit Global Variables:** Assigning a value to an undeclared variable without `var`, `let`, or `const` will implicitly create a global variable. This can lead to unintended side effects and pollute the global namespace.

    ```javascript
    // Non-strict mode
    function createGlobal() {
        undeclaredVar = "I am global!"; // Creates a global variable
    }
    createGlobal();
    console.log(undeclaredVar); // "I am global!"
    ```

    In strict mode, this would throw a `ReferenceError`.

2.  **`this` value coercion:** When a function is called without an explicit context (e.g., as a standalone function, not a method of an object), `this` will default to the global object (`window` in browsers, `global` in Node.js) if not explicitly bound.

    ```javascript
    // Non-strict mode
    function showThis() {
        console.log(this);
    }
    showThis(); // 'this' refers to the global object (window or global)
    ```

    In strict mode, `this` would be `undefined` in this scenario, preventing accidental modification of the global object.

3.  **Duplicate parameter names:** Functions can be declared with multiple parameters having the same name.

    ```javascript
    // Non-strict mode
    function sum(a, a, b) { // 'a' is duplicated
        return a + b; // Uses the *last* 'a' value passed
    }
    console.log(sum(1, 2, 3)); // 2 + 3 = 5
    ```

    In strict mode, this would be a `SyntaxError`.

4.  **Octal literals:** Numbers prefixed with `0` (e.g., `010`) are interpreted as octal numbers.

    ```javascript
    // Non-strict mode
    console.log(010); // 8 (decimal)
    ```

    In strict mode, this is a `SyntaxError` (or `SyntaxWarning` in some older environments), as octal literals are confusing and often unintended. Modern JavaScript uses `0o` for octal (e.g., `0o10`).

5.  **`delete` operator on variables/functions:** Attempting to delete a variable, function, or function argument is allowed but does nothing.

    ```javascript
    // Non-strict mode
    let x = 10;
    delete x; // Does nothing, no error
    console.log(x); // 10
    ```

    In strict mode, this would throw a `TypeError`.

**When do we *need* it?**

The primary reason to use non-strict mode is **compatibility with existing legacy codebases**. If you're working on an old JavaScript project that was written before strict mode was widely adopted (ES5+), forcing strict mode on it might introduce new errors or change behavior in unexpected ways. Migrating such a codebase to strict mode often requires extensive refactoring and testing.

In modern development, non-strict mode is generally avoided. New code should almost always be written in strict mode to leverage its benefits in catching common programming errors early and promoting more predictable code.

## Code Example
This example demonstrates a common "gotcha" in non-strict mode: implicit globals.

```javascript
// This file is NOT in strict mode by default (unless bundled with 'use strict' by a tool)

function processData(data) {
    // Intended to be a local variable, but 'result' was mistyped as 'reult'
    // In non-strict mode, this creates an accidental global variable 'reult'
    reult = data.map(item => item * 2); 
    console.log("Inside processData, reult:", reult);
}

function displayResults() {
    // Later, another part of the application might accidentally use 'reult'
    // thinking it's a legitimate global or trying to access a different variable.
    // This could lead to hard-to-debug issues.
    if (typeof reult !== 'undefined') {
        console.log("Inside displayResults, accidental global 'reult':", reult);
    } else {
        console.log("Inside displayResults, 'reult' is not defined.");
    }
}

const numbers = [1, 2, 3];
processData(numbers); // Creates the accidental global 'reult'
displayResults();     // Accesses the accidental global 'reult'

// To explicitly use strict mode within a file or function:
// "use strict"; 
// function strictModeFunction() {
//    "use strict";
//    // In here, 'undeclaredVar = 1;' would throw a ReferenceError
// }
```

## Key Takeaways
*   **Legacy Code:** The primary use case for non-strict mode is compatibility with older JavaScript codebases that were not designed with strict mode in mind.
*   **Default Behavior:** Non-strict mode is the default for JavaScript files unless `use strict` is explicitly declared or a build tool applies it.
*   **Error Prone:** It allows for problematic behaviors like implicit global variables, permissive `this` binding, duplicate parameter names, and silent failures, which can lead to hard-to-debug issues.
*   **Avoid in New Code:** For all new development, strict mode is highly recommended as it helps catch common mistakes, improves code quality, and makes JavaScript more predictable and secure.

## Quick Summary
Array-like objects in JavaScript are objects that have a `length` property and indexed elements (like `obj[0]`, `obj[1]`), making them structurally similar to arrays. However, they lack the built-in methods of `Array.prototype` (e.g., `map`, `forEach`, `push`), meaning you can't directly call array methods on them.

## How It Works
Array-like objects are often encountered when working with the DOM or function arguments. They look like arrays but aren't true `Array` instances.

Common examples include:
*   `arguments` object inside a function
*   DOM collections returned by methods like `document.getElementsByTagName()`, `document.querySelectorAll()` (which returns a `NodeList`), or `element.children` (which returns an `HTMLCollection`).
*   Strings (though less commonly treated this way, they have a `length` and are indexable)

Because they don't inherit from `Array.prototype`, you cannot directly use array methods like `forEach`, `map`, `filter`, or `reduce` on them. To use array methods, you typically convert them into a true array first.

**Practical Example:**
Imagine you want to iterate over all `div` elements on a page and log their `id`. `document.querySelectorAll('div')` returns a `NodeList`, which is array-like.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <title>Array-Like Example</title>
</head>
<body>
  <div id="div1">Div 1</div>
  <div id="div2">Div 2</div>
  <div id="div3">Div 3</div>

  <script>
    const divs = document.querySelectorAll('div');
    console.log(typeof divs); // object
    console.log(divs instanceof Array); // false
    console.log(divs.length); // 3
    console.log(divs[0].id); // div1

    // This would throw an error if NodeList didn't have its own forEach (modern browsers)
    // but historically or for other array-likes, it would fail.
    // divs.map(div => div.id); // TypeError: divs.map is not a function (if NodeList didn't implement map)

    // How to use array methods:
    // 1. Using Array.from()
    const divIdsArrayFrom = Array.from(divs).map(div => div.id);
    console.log('Using Array.from():', divIdsArrayFrom); // ['div1', 'div2', 'div3']

    // 2. Using the spread operator (...)
    const divIdsSpread = [...divs].map(div => div.id);
    console.log('Using spread operator:', divIdsSpread); // ['div1', 'div2', 'div3']

    // 3. Using Array.prototype.slice.call() (older method)
    const divIdsSlice = Array.prototype.slice.call(divs).map(div => div.id);
    console.log('Using slice.call():', divIdsSlice); // ['div1', 'div2', 'div3']

    // The arguments object is another common array-like
    function sumAll(...args: number[]): number {
      console.log(typeof arguments); // object
      console.log(arguments instanceof Array); // false
      console.log(arguments.length); // 3
      console.log(arguments[0]); // 1

      // Cannot directly use map on arguments
      // arguments.map(x => x * 2); // TypeError: arguments.map is not a function

      // Convert arguments to a real array
      const argsArray = Array.from(arguments);
      return argsArray.reduce((sum: number, current: number) => sum + current, 0);
    }
    console.log('Sum of arguments:', sumAll(1, 2, 3)); // 6
  </script>
</body>
</html>
```

## Code Example

```typescript
// Example 1: The arguments object (array-like)
function logArguments(...args: string[]) {
    console.log("--- Arguments Object ---");
    console.log("Type:", typeof arguments); // object
    console.log("Is Array instance?", arguments instanceof Array); // false
    console.log("Length:", arguments.length); // 3
    console.log("First element:", arguments[0]); // 'hello'

    // Attempting to use an array method directly will fail
    // arguments.forEach(arg => console.log(arg)); // TypeError: arguments.forEach is not a function (in strict mode)

    // Convert to a real array to use array methods
    const realArgsArray: string[] = Array.from(arguments as unknown as string[]);
    console.log("Converted array:", realArgsArray);
    realArgsArray.forEach(arg => console.log(`Arg: ${arg}`)); // Works!
}

logArguments('hello', 'world', 'javascript');

// Example 2: NodeList from DOM (array-like) - requires a browser environment
// Assuming some HTML: <p class="item">Item 1</p><p class="item">Item 2</p>
if (typeof document !== 'undefined') { // Check if running in a browser
    document.body.innerHTML += '<p class="item">Item 1</p><p class="item">Item 2</p>';
    const paragraphs = document.querySelectorAll('.item');

    console.log("\n--- NodeList Object ---");
    console.log("Type:", typeof paragraphs); // object
    console.log("Is Array instance?", paragraphs instanceof Array); // false
    console.log("Length:", paragraphs.length); // 2
    console.log("First element text:", paragraphs[0].textContent); // Item 1

    // NodeList in modern browsers *does* have forEach, but historically didn't,
    // and still lacks other Array.prototype methods like map, filter, reduce.
    paragraphs.forEach(p => console.log(`Paragraph text (via NodeList.forEach): ${p.textContent}`));

    // To use other array methods, convert it
    const paragraphTexts: string[] = Array.from(paragraphs).map(p => p.textContent || '');
    console.log("Paragraph texts (via Array.from().map()):", paragraphTexts);
}

// Example 3: A custom array-like object
const myCustomArrayLike = {
    0: 'apple',
    1: 'banana',
    2: 'orange',
    length: 3
};

console.log("\n--- Custom Array-Like Object ---");
console.log("Type:", typeof myCustomArrayLike); // object
console.log("Is Array instance?", myCustomArrayLike instanceof Array); // false
console.log("Length:", myCustomArrayLike.length); // 3
console.log("First element:", myCustomArrayLike[0]); // apple

// Convert and iterate
const fruits: string[] = Array.from(myCustomArrayLike as unknown as string[]);
console.log("Fruits (via Array.from()):", fruits);
fruits.filter(fruit => fruit.startsWith('a')).forEach(f => console.log(`A-fruit: ${f}`));
```

## Key Takeaways
*   **Structure, Not Type:** Array-like objects have a `length` property and indexed elements (`obj[0]`, `obj[1]`), resembling arrays in structure.
*   **No Array Methods:** They do not inherit from `Array.prototype`, so they lack methods like `map`, `filter`, `forEach` (unless implemented specifically, like `NodeList.forEach` in modern browsers), `push`, `pop`, etc.
*   **Common Examples:** `arguments` object, `NodeList`, `HTMLCollection`, and strings.
*   **Conversion is Key:** To use full `Array.prototype` methods, convert array-like objects into true arrays using:
    *   `Array.from(arrayLikeObject)`
    *   The spread operator: `[...arrayLikeObject]`
    *   (Less common now) `Array.prototype.slice.call(arrayLikeObject)`

## Quick Summary
An HTTP request is a message sent by a client (like a web browser) to a server to ask for a resource or to submit data. It consists of a start line, headers, and an optional body, all formatted as plain text.

## How It Works (with practical examples)
When you type a URL into your browser or click a link, your browser constructs an HTTP request and sends it over the network to the server hosting the website. The server then processes this request and sends back an HTTP response.

A typical HTTP request has three main parts:

1.  **Start Line:** This is the first line of the request and specifies the type of request. It contains:
    *   **HTTP Method:** An action to be performed (e.g., `GET`, `POST`, `PUT`, `DELETE`).
    *   **Path (or Request-URI):** The specific resource being requested on the server (e.g., `/index.html`, `/api/users`).
    *   **HTTP Version:** The version of the HTTP protocol being used (e.g., `HTTP/1.1`, `HTTP/2.0`).

    *Example:* `GET /index.html HTTP/1.1`

2.  **Headers:** These are lines following the start line, providing additional information about the request, the client, or the body. Each header is a key-value pair separated by a colon, followed by a newline. Common headers include:
    *   `Host`: The domain name of the server (required for HTTP/1.1).
    *   `User-Agent`: Information about the client software (e.g., browser).
    *   `Accept`: Media types the client can handle (e.g., `text/html`, `application/json`).
    *   `Content-Type`: The media type of the request body (if present, e.g., `application/json`).
    *   `Content-Length`: The size of the request body in bytes (if present).
    *   `Authorization`: Credentials for authenticating the client.

    Headers are terminated by an empty line.

3.  **Body (Optional):** This part contains the actual data being sent to the server. It's typically used with methods like `POST` or `PUT` to send form data, JSON, XML, or files. `GET` requests usually do not have a body.

    *Example:* When submitting a form, the body might contain the form field values. When sending JSON data for an API, the body would be the JSON string.

## Code Example
While HTTP requests are text-based and sent over a network socket, we can simulate how they are constructed and sent using JavaScript's `fetch` API, which abstracts away the low-level details.

```typescript
// Example 1: A simple GET request
async function makeGetRequest() {
  const url = 'https://api.example.com/users';

  try {
    const response = await fetch(url, {
      method: 'GET', // HTTP Method
      headers: {
        'Accept': 'application/json', // Header: tells server we prefer JSON
        'User-Agent': 'MyCustomApp/1.0', // Header: custom user agent
        // 'Host': 'api.example.com' // Host header is automatically added by browsers/fetch
      }
      // GET requests typically don't have a body
    });

    if (!response.ok) {
      throw new Error(`HTTP error! status: ${response.status}`);
    }

    const data = await response.json();
    console.log('GET Response Data:', data);

  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Error making GET request:', error);
  }
}

// Example 2: A POST request with a JSON body
async function makePostRequest() {
  const url = 'https://api.example.com/users';
  const userData = {
    name: 'John Doe',
    email: 'john.doe@example.com'
  };

  try {
    const response = await fetch(url, {
      method: 'POST', // HTTP Method
      headers: {
        'Content-Type': 'application/json', // Header: tells server the body is JSON
        'Accept': 'application/json', // Header: tells server we prefer JSON in response
        'Authorization': 'Bearer your_access_token' // Header: for authentication
      },
      body: JSON.stringify(userData) // Optional Body: JSON string of user data
    });

    if (!response.ok) {
      throw new Error(`HTTP error! status: ${response.status}`);
    }

    const result = await response.json();
    console.log('POST Response Result:', result);

  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Error making POST request:', error);
  }
}

// Call the functions to see them in action (in a browser environment)
// makeGetRequest();
// makePostRequest();
```

**What the raw request for `makePostRequest` might look like on the wire (simplified for HTTP/1.1):**

```
POST /users HTTP/1.1
Host: api.example.com
Content-Type: application/json
Accept: application/json
Authorization: Bearer your_access_token
Content-Length: 46

{"name":"John Doe","email":"john.doe@example.com"}
```

## Key Takeaways
*   An HTTP request is a structured text message from client to server.
*   It consists of a **Start Line** (Method, Path, HTTP Version), **Headers** (key-value pairs for metadata), and an optional **Body** (for data submission).
*   Different HTTP methods (`GET`, `POST`, `PUT`, `DELETE`) indicate the intended action on the resource.
*   Headers provide crucial context, like the client type, acceptable response formats, and authentication details.
*   The body is primarily used with `POST` and `PUT` to send data to the server.

## Quick Summary
HTTP request methods, also known as HTTP verbs, define the actions to be performed on a resource identified by a URL. They are a fundamental part of the HTTP protocol, allowing clients to interact with web servers to create, read, update, and delete data.

## How It Works
Each method has a specific semantic meaning and associated properties like idempotence and safety. Understanding these helps in designing RESTful APIs and interacting with web services correctly.

Here are the most common HTTP request methods and their uses:

*   **GET**:
    *   **Use**: Retrieves a representation of the specified resource. It should only retrieve data and have no other effect.
    *   **Properties**: Safe (doesn't alter server state) and Idempotent (multiple identical requests have the same effect as a single one).
    *   **Example**: Fetching a blog post, an image, or a list of users. Data is typically sent via URL parameters.

*   **POST**:
    *   **Use**: Submits data to be processed to a specified resource. It often results in a change in state or the creation of a new resource on the server.
    *   **Properties**: Neither safe nor idempotent (repeated requests can create multiple resources or have different effects).
    *   **Example**: Submitting a new user registration form, creating a new blog post, or uploading a file. Data is typically sent in the request body.

*   **PUT**:
    *   **Use**: Replaces all current representations of the target resource with the request payload. If the resource does not exist, it can create it.
    *   **Properties**: Not safe but Idempotent (sending the same PUT request multiple times will result in the same state on the server).
    *   **Example**: Updating an entire user profile, replacing a document at a specific URL. Data is typically sent in the request body.

*   **DELETE**:
    *   **Use**: Deletes the specified resource.
    *   **Properties**: Not safe but Idempotent (deleting a resource multiple times will have the same effect as deleting it once – the resource will still be gone).
    *   **Example**: Removing a blog post, deleting a user account.

*   **PATCH**:
    *   **Use**: Applies partial modifications to a resource. It's used to update specific fields of a resource without replacing the entire resource.
    *   **Properties**: Not safe and not idempotent (repeated requests might have different effects if the patch describes a state change, e.g., "increment by 1").
    *   **Example**: Updating only a user's email address or password, changing the status of an order. Data is typically sent in the request body.

*   **HEAD**:
    *   **Use**: Identical to GET, but it retrieves only the HTTP headers and not the actual resource body. Useful for checking resource existence, metadata, or caching information without downloading the entire content.
    *   **Properties**: Safe and Idempotent.
    *   **Example**: Checking if a file exists before attempting a GET request, verifying if a resource has been modified.

*   **OPTIONS**:
    *   **Use**: Describes the communication options for the target resource. Clients can use it to determine the allowed methods and other capabilities of a web server or resource.
    *   **Properties**: Safe and Idempotent.
    *   **Example**: Pre-flight requests in CORS (Cross-Origin Resource Sharing) to check which methods are allowed from a different origin.

## Code Example (using JavaScript with `fetch` API)

```typescript
async function makeHttpRequest(method: string, url: string, body?: object) {
  const options: RequestInit = {
    method: method,
    headers: {
      'Content-Type': 'application/json',
    },
  };

  if (body && (method === 'POST' || method === 'PUT' || method === 'PATCH')) {
    options.body = JSON.stringify(body);
  }

  try {
    const response = await fetch(url, options);
    const data = await response.json();

    if (!response.ok) {
      throw new Error(`HTTP error! Status: ${response.status}, Message: ${JSON.stringify(data)}`);
    }

    console.log(`${method} request to ${url} successful:`, data);
    return data;
  } catch (error) {
    console.error(`${method} request to ${url} failed:`, error);
    throw error;
  }
}

// Example Usage:
const API_BASE_URL = 'https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com'; // A public API for testing

// 1. GET: Retrieve a post
async function getPost(id: number) {
  console.log('\n--- GET Example ---');
  return makeHttpRequest('GET', `${API_BASE_URL}/posts/${id}`);
}

// 2. POST: Create a new post
async function createPost(title: string, bodyContent: string, userId: number) {
  console.log('\n--- POST Example ---');
  return makeHttpRequest('POST', `${API_BASE_URL}/posts`, {
    title: title,
    body: bodyContent,
    userId: userId,
  });
}

// 3. PUT: Update an existing post (replace entire resource)
async function updatePost(id: number, title: string, bodyContent: string, userId: number) {
  console.log('\n--- PUT Example ---');
  return makeHttpRequest('PUT', `${API_BASE_URL}/posts/${id}`, {
    id: id, // Typically, the ID is also sent in the body for PUT
    title: title,
    body: bodyContent,
    userId: userId,
  });
}

// 4. PATCH: Partially update an existing post (e.g., just the title)
async function patchPostTitle(id: number, newTitle: string) {
  console.log('\n--- PATCH Example ---');
  return makeHttpRequest('PATCH', `${API_BASE_URL}/posts/${id}`, {
    title: newTitle,
  });
}

// 5. DELETE: Delete a post
async function deletePost(id: number) {
  console.log('\n--- DELETE Example ---');
  // DELETE requests often don't return a body, or an empty object,
  // but the server might still send a 200 OK or 204 No Content.
  const options: RequestInit = { method: 'DELETE' };
  try {
    const response = await fetch(`${API_BASE_URL}/posts/${id}`, options);
    if (!response.ok) {
      throw new Error(`HTTP error! Status: ${response.status}`);
    }
    console.log(`DELETE request to ${API_BASE_URL}/posts/${id} successful. Status: ${response.status}`);
    return { status: response.status };
  } catch (error) {
    console.error(`DELETE request to ${API_BASE_URL}/posts/${id} failed:`, error);
    throw error;
  }
}

// 6. HEAD: Get headers without body
async function getHeadInfo(url: string) {
  console.log('\n--- HEAD Example ---');
  try {
    const response = await fetch(url, { method: 'HEAD' });
    console.log(`HEAD request to ${url} successful. Headers:`, Array.from(response.headers.entries()));
    return response.headers;
  } catch (error) {
    console.error(`HEAD request to ${url} failed:`, error);
    throw error;
  }
}

// Run the examples
(async () => {
  try {
    const post = await getPost(1);
    console.log('Retrieved Post:', post);

    const newPost = await createPost('My New Title', 'This is the body of my new post.', 1);
    console.log('Created Post:', newPost);

    const updatedPost = await updatePost(1, 'Updated Title for Post 1', 'Completely new body content.', 1);
    console.log('PUT Updated Post 1:', updatedPost);

    const patchedPost = await patchPostTitle(1, 'Partially Updated Title');
    console.log('PATCH Updated Post 1 (title only):', patchedPost);

    // Note: jsonplaceholder actually "deletes" but returns the original object,
    // in a real API, you'd get a 204 No Content or similar.
    await deletePost(1);
    console.log('Post 1 deleted (simulated).');

    await getHeadInfo(`${API_BASE_URL}/posts/1`);

  } catch (err) {
    console.error('An error occurred during example execution:', err);
  }
})();
```

## Key Takeaways
*   **Semantics Matter**: Each HTTP method has a well-defined purpose, crucial for designing clear and maintainable APIs (RESTful principles).
*   **Safety**: A method is "safe" if it doesn't alter the state of the server (e.g., GET, HEAD, OPTIONS).
*   **Idempotence**: A method is "idempotent" if making the same request multiple times has the same effect as making it once (e.g., GET, PUT, DELETE, HEAD, OPTIONS). POST and PATCH are generally not idempotent.
*   **Data Transfer**: GET requests typically send data in URL query parameters, while POST, PUT, and PATCH send data in the request body.
*   **Status Codes**: The server's response status code (e.g., 200 OK, 201 Created, 204 No Content, 404 Not Found) indicates the outcome of the request and is equally important.

## Tracking Errors in Web Applications

Tracking errors is crucial for maintaining the health, reliability, and user experience of a web application. A robust error tracking strategy involves capturing, reporting, storing, and analyzing errors in a structured way.

### Core Principles

1.  **Comprehensive Capture:** Don't just catch unhandled exceptions; capture network errors, UI errors, promise rejections, and custom application-specific errors.
2.  **Rich Context:** Each error report should include metadata that helps in debugging (e.g., user info, browser, OS, URL, component state, stack trace, user actions leading to the error).
3.  **Real-time Reporting:** Errors should be reported as quickly as possible to enable prompt investigation.
4.  **Centralized Storage & Analysis:** A dedicated system for storing, aggregating, and visualizing errors is essential for identifying trends and prioritizing fixes.
5.  **Alerting:** Proactive notification when critical errors occur or error rates spike.

### Architecture Patterns & Components

#### 1. Client-Side Error Interceptors

These are the primary mechanisms for capturing errors within the user's browser.

*   **`window.onerror`:** Catches uncaught JavaScript errors.
*   **`window.onunhandledrejection`:** Catches unhandled promise rejections.
*   **Event Listeners:** For network errors (`fetch` or `XMLHttpRequest`), UI errors (e.g., image loading failures), and specific component errors.
*   **Framework-Specific Error Boundaries/Handlers:** React's Error Boundaries, Angular's `ErrorHandler`, Vue's `errorHandler`.

#### 2. Error Reporting Service/SDK

A small client-side library (often provided by a third-party service) that:
*   Collects error details and context.
*   Batches errors (to reduce network requests).
*   Sends error reports to a backend endpoint.

#### 3. Backend Error Ingestion Endpoint

A dedicated API endpoint on your server (or a third-party service's server) that:
*   Receives error reports from the client.
*   Validates and sanitizes the data.
*   Persists the error data to a database.

#### 4. Error Storage & Database

A database (e.g., PostgreSQL, MongoDB, Elasticsearch) optimized for storing and querying error logs. Elasticsearch is often preferred for its full-text search and analytical capabilities.

#### 5. Error Aggregation & Deduplication

Grouping similar errors (e.g., same stack trace, same message) to avoid noise and focus on unique issues. This often happens within the error tracking service.

#### 6. Dashboard & Alerting System

A user interface to visualize error trends, search for specific errors, and configure alerts (email, Slack, PagerDuty) based on error frequency, type, or impact.

### Practical Implementation Steps & Code Examples

#### Step 1: Initialize an Error Tracking Service

Using a third-party service like Sentry, LogRocket, Bugsnag, or Rollbar is highly recommended. They provide robust SDKs, backend infrastructure, and dashboards out-of-the-box.

**Example (Sentry):**

```typescript
// app.ts or index.ts
import * as Sentry from "@sentry/browser";
import { Integrations } from "@sentry/tracing";

if (process.env.NODE_ENV === "production") {
  Sentry.init({
    dsn: "YOUR_SENTRY_DSN",
    integrations: [
      new Integrations.BrowserTracing({
        tracingOrigins: ["localhost", /^\//],
      }),
    ],
    tracesSampleRate: 1.0, // Adjust this in production
    // Add custom context like user info
    beforeSend(event, hint) {
      if (window.currentUser) {
        event.user = {
          id: window.currentUser.id,
          email: window.currentUser.email,
          // ... more user data
        };
      }
      return event;
    },
  });
}

// You might also want to set user context after login
// Sentry.setUser({ id: "user123", email: "test@example.com" });
```

#### Step 2: Capture Different Error Types

**a) Uncaught JavaScript Errors & Unhandled Promise Rejections (Automatically Handled by Sentry SDK)**

The Sentry SDK automatically hooks into `window.onerror` and `window.onunhandledrejection`.

**b) Manual Error Reporting**

For caught errors or specific application logic failures.

```typescript
try {
  // Some risky operation
  throw new Error("Something went wrong during data processing!");
} catch (error) {
  console.error("Caught error:", error);
  Sentry.captureException(error); // Report to Sentry
  // Optionally, show a user-friendly message
}
```

**c) Component-Specific Errors (React Error Boundaries)**

```typescript jsx
// ErrorBoundary.tsx
import React, { ErrorInfo, ReactNode } from 'react';
import * as Sentry from "@sentry/browser";

interface ErrorBoundaryProps {
  children: ReactNode;
}

interface ErrorBoundaryState {
  hasError: boolean;
}

class ErrorBoundary extends React.Component<ErrorBoundaryProps, ErrorBoundaryState> {
  constructor(props: ErrorBoundaryProps) {
    super(props);
    this.state = { hasError: false };
  }

  static getDerivedStateFromError(error: Error): ErrorBoundaryState {
    // Update state so the next render shows the fallback UI.
    return { hasError: true };
  }

  componentDidCatch(error: Error, errorInfo: ErrorInfo) {
    // Log the error to an error reporting service
    Sentry.captureException(error, { extra: errorInfo });
    console.error("Error caught by boundary:", error, errorInfo);
  }

  render() {
    if (this.state.hasError) {
      // You can render any custom fallback UI
      return <h1>Something went wrong. Please refresh the page.</h1>;
    }

    return this.props.children;
  }
}

// Usage in your app:
// <ErrorBoundary>
//   <MyProblematicComponent />
// </ErrorBoundary>
```

**d) Network Errors (Using Fetch Interceptors)**

```typescript
// fetch-interceptor.ts
const originalFetch = window.fetch;

window.fetch = async (...args: Parameters<typeof fetch>): Promise<Response> => {
  try {
    const response = await originalFetch(...args);
    if (!response.ok && response.status >= 400) {
      // Treat non-OK HTTP responses (e.g., 4xx, 5xx) as potential errors
      const errorDetails = await response.text(); // Or response.json()
      const error = new Error(`HTTP Error: ${response.status} ${response.statusText} - ${args[0]}`);
      (error as any).response = {
        status: response.status,
        statusText: response.statusText,
        url: response.url,
        details: errorDetails,
      };
      Sentry.captureException(error, {
        level: 'warning', // Or 'error' depending on severity
        tags: { type: 'network_error', url: response.url },
        extra: {
          request: args[0],
          requestOptions: args[1],
          responseBody: errorDetails,
        }
      });
    }
    return response;
  } catch (error) {
    // Catch actual network failures (e.g., DNS error, no internet)
    console.error("Network request failed:", error);
    Sentry.captureException(error, {
      tags: { type: 'network_failure', url: args[0]?.toString() },
      extra: {
        request: args[0],
        requestOptions: args[1],
      }
    });
    throw error; // Re-throw to propagate the original error
  }
};
```

#### Step 3: Add Context to Errors

This is critical for debugging.

```typescript
// Setting user context (e.g., after login)
Sentry.setUser({
  id: "user-123",
  email: "john.doe@example.com",
  username: "johndoe",
});

// Adding extra data or tags to a specific error
try {
  // ...
} catch (error) {
  Sentry.captureException(error, {
    tags: {
      component: "ProductDetail",
      environment: "production",
    },
    extra: {
      productId: "SKU12345",
      userAction: "Added to cart",
      currentUrl: window.location.href,
    },
  });
}
```

### Trade-offs and Considerations

*   **Performance Overhead:** Error tracking SDKs add a small amount of JavaScript and network requests. Choose lightweight SDKs and consider sampling for high-volume events.
*   **Privacy:** Be mindful of what user data is sent with error reports. Anonymize or redact sensitive information (PII, passwords). Most services offer data scrubbing capabilities.
*   **Cost:** Third-party services have costs based on event volume. Monitor usage and configure appropriate sampling rates.
*   **Security:** Ensure the error ingestion endpoint is secure and can't be abused.
*   **Self-Hosted vs. SaaS:**
    *   **SaaS (e.g., Sentry.io, Bugsnag):** Easier setup, managed infrastructure, rich features, often better dashboards. Recommended for most teams.
    *   **Self-Hosted (e.g., open-source Sentry, ELK stack):** Full control over data, potentially lower cost for very high volume, but requires significant operational overhead.
*   **Local Development:** Disable or reduce error reporting in development environments to avoid polluting production error logs.
*   **Source Maps:** Essential for translating minified, transpiled production code back to original source code in stack traces. Ensure your build process generates and uploads source maps to your error tracking service.

### Conclusion

A comprehensive error tracking strategy is indispensable for modern web applications. By combining client-side error interception, robust third-party reporting services, and thoughtful context inclusion, development teams can quickly identify, diagnose, and resolve issues, leading to a more stable and reliable user experience.

## Quick Summary
Performance metrics are quantifiable measurements used to assess the speed, responsiveness, and user experience of a website or application. They help identify bottlenecks, track improvements over time, and ensure that a digital product meets user expectations for performance.

## How It Works
These metrics are collected through various tools (browser developer tools, Lighthouse, WebPageTest, RUM solutions) and represent different stages of the page loading and rendering lifecycle. They provide insights into how quickly content appears, becomes interactive, and feels smooth to the user.

Here are some common performance metrics:

1.  **First Contentful Paint (FCP):**
    *   **What it measures:** The time from when the page starts loading to when any part of the page's content is rendered on the screen. This is the first point at which a user can see something happening.
    *   **Why it matters:** It's the first impression of load speed. A quick FCP reassures users that the page is loading.

2.  **Largest Contentful Paint (LCP):**
    *   **What it measures:** The render time of the largest image or text block visible within the viewport. This is a crucial user-centric metric for perceived load speed.
    *   **Why it matters:** It approximates when the main content of the page has likely loaded. A low LCP score indicates that users can see the primary content quickly. It's a Core Web Vital.

3.  **Total Blocking Time (TBT):**
    *   **What it measures:** The total amount of time between FCP and Time to Interactive where the main thread was blocked for long enough to prevent input responsiveness (i.e., long tasks).
    *   **Why it matters:** High TBT indicates that the page might look ready but isn't responding to user input (clicks, scrolls). It's a good proxy for interactivity and a Core Web Vital.

4.  **Cumulative Layout Shift (CLS):**
    *   **What it measures:** The sum total of all individual layout shift scores for every unexpected layout shift that occurs during the entire lifespan of the page. A layout shift occurs when a visible element changes its position from one rendered frame to the next.
    *   **Why it matters:** Unexpected layout shifts are annoying and can lead to users clicking the wrong thing. A low CLS means a stable visual experience. It's a Core Web Vital.

5.  **Time to Interactive (TTI):**
    *   **What it measures:** The time it takes for the page to become fully interactive. This is when the page displays useful content, event handlers are registered for most visible elements, and the page responds to user interactions within 50 milliseconds.
    *   **Why it matters:** A user might see content (FCP/LCP) but can't interact with it. TTI ensures the page is usable.

6.  **Speed Index:**
    *   **What it measures:** How quickly the contents of a page are visibly populated. It's calculated by visually comparing frames of the page load and assigning a score based on the completeness of the visual display over time.
    *   **Why it matters:** Provides a single number that summarizes the visual progress of the page load, offering a more holistic view than just FCP.

## Code Example
While performance metrics aren't directly "coded" by developers in the application logic, they are measured using browser APIs. Here's how you might access some of these metrics using the [Performance API](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Performance_API) in JavaScript, specifically `PerformanceObserver` for Core Web Vitals.

```typescript
// Function to report Core Web Vitals
function reportWebVitals() {
  // Largest Contentful Paint (LCP)
  new PerformanceObserver((entryList) => {
    for (const entry of entryList.getEntries()) {
      console.log('LCP:', entry.startTime, entry.element);
      // Send to analytics or a reporting service
    }
  }).observe({ type: 'largest-contentful-paint', buffered: true });

  // Cumulative Layout Shift (CLS)
  new PerformanceObserver((entryList) => {
    let cls = 0;
    for (const entry of entryList.getEntries()) {
      if (!entry.hadRecentInput) { // Exclude layout shifts caused by user input
        cls += entry.value;
      }
    }
    console.log('CLS:', cls);
    // Send to analytics or a reporting service
  }).observe({ type: 'layout-shift', buffered: true });

  // First Input Delay (FID) - *Note: TBT is not directly available via PerformanceObserver for RUM*
  // FID measures the delay in processing the first user interaction.
  // Although not TBT, it's the interactivity Core Web Vital for RUM.
  new PerformanceObserver((entryList) => {
    for (const entry of entryList.getEntries()) {
      console.log('FID:', entry.delay); // delay is the difference between processing start and actual handler start
      // Send to analytics or a reporting service
    }
  }).observe({ type: 'first-input', buffered: true });

  // First Contentful Paint (FCP)
  new PerformanceObserver((entryList) => {
    for (const entry of entryList.getEntriesByName('first-contentful-paint')) {
      console.log('FCP:', entry.startTime);
      // Send to analytics or a reporting service
    }
  }).observe({ type: 'paint', buffered: true });

  // You can also get other metrics via `performance.getEntriesByType()`
  const navigationTiming = performance.getEntriesByType('navigation')[0];
  if (navigationTiming) {
    const domContentLoaded = navigationTiming.domContentLoadedEventEnd - navigationTiming.domContentLoadedEventStart;
    const loadTime = navigationTiming.loadEventEnd - navigationTiming.loadEventStart;
    console.log('DOM Content Loaded Time:', domContentLoaded);
    console.log('Page Load Time:', loadTime);
  }
}

// Call the function once the DOM is ready
if (document.readyState === 'complete') {
  reportWebVitals();
} else {
  window.addEventListener('load', reportWebVitals);
}
```

## Key Takeaways
*   **User-Centric:** Many modern metrics (especially Core Web Vitals) focus on how users *perceive* performance, not just technical load times.
*   **Phased Loading:** Different metrics capture performance at different stages of the page load (visual readiness, interactivity).
*   **Identify Bottlenecks:** Analyzing these metrics helps pinpoint specific areas for optimization (e.g., slow image loading, heavy JavaScript execution, layout shifts).
*   **Tools for Measurement:** Google Lighthouse, WebPageTest, browser DevTools, and Real User Monitoring (RUM) solutions are essential for collecting and analyzing these metrics.
*   **Continuous Monitoring:** Performance is not a one-time fix; it requires continuous monitoring and optimization.

## Quick Summary
`WeakSet` and `WeakMap` are specialized collections in JavaScript that store objects weakly. This means that if there are no other references to an object stored in a `WeakSet` or used as a key in a `WeakMap`, the object can be garbage collected. This prevents memory leaks that can occur with `Set` and `Map` when storing object references.

## How It Works
Both `WeakSet` and `WeakMap` are designed to hold references to objects without preventing those objects from being garbage collected. This is their primary distinction from `Set` and `Map`, which hold strong references.

**WeakSet:**
*   **Stores only objects:** You cannot store primitive values (strings, numbers, booleans, symbols, null, undefined) in a `WeakSet`. Attempting to do so will throw an error.
*   **No iteration:** `WeakSet`s are not enumerable. You cannot iterate over them using `forEach`, `for...of`, or get their size. This is because their contents can change unpredictably due to garbage collection, making iteration unreliable.
*   **Methods:** `add(value)`, `has(value)`, `delete(value)`.
*   **Use case:** Useful for tracking objects that "belong" to a certain group or state without preventing their eventual removal from memory. For example, tracking which DOM elements are currently active or have had a specific event listener attached.

**WeakMap:**
*   **Keys must be objects:** Like `WeakSet` values, `WeakMap` keys must be objects. Primitive values cannot be used as keys.
*   **Values can be anything:** The values stored in a `WeakMap` can be any JavaScript data type, including primitives or other objects.
*   **No iteration:** Similar to `WeakSet`, `WeakMap`s are not enumerable. You cannot iterate over keys or values, or get their size.
*   **Methods:** `set(key, value)`, `get(key)`, `has(key)`, `delete(key)`.
*   **Use case:** Attaching private data or metadata to objects without modifying the objects themselves and without preventing their garbage collection. For example, caching computation results for specific object instances, or storing configuration data related to particular DOM nodes.

**Garbage Collection Example:**
If an object is added to a `WeakSet` or used as a key in a `WeakMap`, and all other strong references to that object are removed, the object becomes eligible for garbage collection. Once collected, it will automatically be removed from the `WeakSet` or `WeakMap`. This happens silently and asynchronously.

## Code Example

```typescript
// --- WeakSet Example ---
console.log('--- WeakSet Example ---');
let user1 = { name: 'Alice' };
let user2 = { name: 'Bob' };
let user3 = { name: 'Charlie' };

const activeUsers = new WeakSet();

activeUsers.add(user1);
activeUsers.add(user2);

console.log('Has user1:', activeUsers.has(user1)); // true
console.log('Has user3:', activeUsers.has(user3)); // false

// Remove the strong reference to user1
// user1 is now eligible for garbage collection.
// If collected, it will also be removed from activeUsers.
user1 = null; 

// We cannot iterate or check size of activeUsers directly.
// console.log(activeUsers.size); // Error or undefined behavior
// for (let user of activeUsers) { ... } // Error

console.log('--- WeakMap Example ---');
// --- WeakMap Example ---
let element1 = document.createElement('div');
let element2 = document.createElement('span');

const elementData = new WeakMap();

// Attach some private data to element1
elementData.set(element1, {
  id: 'div-123',
  config: { draggable: true }
});

// Attach some private data to element2
elementData.set(element2, {
  id: 'span-456',
  config: { resizable: false }
});

console.log('Element1 data:', elementData.get(element1));
console.log('Has element2:', elementData.has(element2)); // true
console.log('Has element3 (non-existent):', elementData.has(document.createElement('p'))); // false

// If element1 is removed from the DOM and no other references exist,
// it will be garbage collected, and its entry in elementData will be removed.
// Example: element1.remove(); (assuming no other strong references to element1)
// We cannot iterate or check size of elementData directly.
// console.log(elementData.size); // Error or undefined behavior
// for (let [key, value] of elementData) { ... } // Error

// Attempting to use a primitive as a key will throw an error
try {
  elementData.set('stringKey', 'some value');
} catch (e) {
  console.error("Error setting primitive key in WeakMap:", e.message);
}
```

## Key Takeaways
*   **Weak References:** The core feature is that they hold *weak* references to objects, allowing garbage collection if no other strong references exist. This prevents memory leaks.
*   **Object-Only Keys/Values:** `WeakSet` can only store objects as values. `WeakMap` can only use objects as keys. Primitives are not allowed.
*   **Non-Enumerable:** Neither `WeakSet` nor `WeakMap` are iterable, and you cannot get their size. This is due to their dynamic nature with garbage collection.
*   **Use Cases:**
    *   `WeakSet`: Tracking membership of objects in a group (e.g., active DOM elements, objects with a specific state) without preventing their garbage collection.
    *   `WeakMap`: Associating private data or metadata with objects without modifying the objects themselves, ensuring the data is also garbage collected when the object is.
*   **Memory Management:** They are primarily tools for advanced memory management in scenarios where you need to associate data with objects that might be transient or whose lifecycle is managed externally (e.g., DOM elements).

Let's break down Webpack loaders and plugins.

## Quick Summary
Webpack loaders are tools used to pre-process different types of files (like TypeScript, Sass, or images) before they're added to the bundle. Plugins are more powerful tools that can modify how Webpack works during various stages of the compilation lifecycle, such as optimizing bundles, managing assets, or injecting environment variables.

## How It Works

### Loaders
Webpack, by default, only understands JavaScript. Loaders provide a way to teach Webpack how to process other types of files. When Webpack encounters a file type it doesn't understand (e.g., a `.ts` file or a `.scss` file), it looks for a configured loader that can transform that file into a valid JavaScript module or a dependency that can be included in the bundle.

**Practical Examples:**
*   **`ts-loader`**: Transpiles TypeScript files (`.ts`, `.tsx`) into JavaScript.
*   **`babel-loader`**: Transpiles modern JavaScript (ES6+) into backward-compatible JavaScript, allowing you to use the latest language features.
*   **`css-loader` + `style-loader`**: `css-loader` interprets `@import` and `url()` like `import/require()` and resolves them, while `style-loader` injects the CSS into the DOM.
*   **`sass-loader`**: Compiles Sass/SCSS files into CSS.
*   **`file-loader` / `asset modules` (Webpack 5)**: Manages assets like images, fonts, or other files, outputting them to the build directory and providing their public URLs.

Loaders are applied from right to left (or bottom to top in an array). For example, `use: ['style-loader', 'css-loader']` means `css-loader` runs first, then `style-loader`.

### Plugins
While loaders operate on individual files *before* they are bundled, plugins operate on the bundled modules or chunks during the compilation process. They "hook" into various stages of Webpack's build lifecycle, giving them access to the entire compilation and its output. This allows them to perform a wide range of tasks that loaders cannot.

**Practical Examples:**
*   **`HtmlWebpackPlugin`**: Simplifies creation of HTML files to serve your webpack bundles. It injects the script tags for your bundles automatically.
*   **`MiniCssExtractPlugin`**: Extracts CSS into separate files, creating a CSS file per JS file which contains CSS. This is useful for production builds to avoid FOUC (Flash of Unstyled Content).
*   **`DefinePlugin`**: Allows you to create global constants that can be configured at compile time. Useful for injecting environment variables (e.g., `process.env.NODE_ENV`).
*   **`CleanWebpackPlugin`**: Cleans up the `dist` folder before each build.
*   **`TerserWebpackPlugin`**: Minifies JavaScript files in the output bundle (often used in production).

## Code Example

```typescript
// webpack.config.js
import path from 'path';
import HtmlWebpackPlugin from 'html-webpack-plugin';
import MiniCssExtractPlugin from 'mini-css-extract-plugin';
import { CleanWebpackPlugin } from 'clean-webpack-plugin';
import webpack from 'webpack'; // For DefinePlugin

const config = {
  mode: 'development', // or 'production'
  entry: './src/index.ts',
  output: {
    filename: 'bundle.[contenthash].js',
    path: path.resolve(__dirname, 'dist'),
    clean: true, // Webpack 5 built-in clean functionality
  },
  module: {
    rules: [
      // Loader for TypeScript files
      {
        test: /\.tsx?$/,
        use: 'ts-loader',
        exclude: /node_modules/,
      },
      // Loaders for CSS/SASS files
      {
        test: /\.(sa|sc|c)ss$/,
        use: [
          // Injects CSS into the DOM (development)
          // or extracts to a file (production via MiniCssExtractPlugin)
          MiniCssExtractPlugin.loader, 
          'css-loader',   // Interprets @import and url()
          'sass-loader',  // Compiles Sass to CSS
        ],
      },
      // Loader for images (Webpack 5 asset modules)
      {
        test: /\.(png|svg|jpg|jpeg|gif)$/i,
        type: 'asset/resource', // Emits a separate file and exports the URL
      },
    ],
  },
  resolve: {
    extensions: ['.tsx', '.ts', '.js'],
  },
  plugins: [
    // Cleans the 'dist' folder before each build (if not using output.clean)
    // new CleanWebpackPlugin(), 

    // Generates an HTML file and injects the bundle
    new HtmlWebpackPlugin({
      template: './src/index.html',
      filename: 'index.html',
    }),

    // Extracts CSS into separate files
    new MiniCssExtractPlugin({
      filename: '[name].[contenthash].css',
    }),

    // Defines global constants at compile time
    new webpack.DefinePlugin({
      'process.env.NODE_ENV': JSON.stringify(process.env.NODE_ENV || 'development'),
      'APP_VERSION': JSON.stringify('1.0.0'),
    }),
  ],
};

export default config;
```

## Key Takeaways
*   **Loaders transform individual files:** They pre-process files like `.ts`, `.scss`, or images into modules Webpack can understand. Applied *before* bundling.
*   **Plugins modify the compilation process:** They hook into Webpack's lifecycle to perform broader tasks, such as optimizing bundles, managing assets, or injecting environment variables. Applied *during* or *after* bundling.
*   **Loaders are configured in `module.rules`:** They have `test` (regex for file types) and `use` (array of loader names/objects).
*   **Plugins are instantiated in `plugins` array:** They are classes that you `new` up with configuration options.
*   **They are complementary:** You often need both loaders and plugins to build a complete and optimized application with Webpack.

## Quick Summary
Server-Side Rendering (SSR) is a web rendering technique where a web page's content is rendered on the server into a complete HTML page before being sent to the client's browser. This means the browser receives fully formed HTML, which it can display immediately, improving initial page load times and SEO.

## How It Works
Traditionally, with Client-Side Rendering (CSR), the browser receives a minimal HTML file (often just a `div` element), then fetches JavaScript, executes it, and finally renders the content. With SSR, when a user requests a page, the server executes the application's code (e.g., a React or Vue app) to generate the full HTML string for that specific page. This HTML, along with any necessary JavaScript and CSS, is then sent to the client. The browser displays the HTML immediately. Once the JavaScript loads, it "hydrates" the static HTML, attaching event listeners and making the page interactive, effectively turning it into a client-side application.

**Practical Example:**
Imagine a blog post page.
1.  **User Request:** User navigates to `/blog/my-first-post`.
2.  **Server Process:** The Node.js server (running a framework like Next.js or Nuxt.js) receives this request. It fetches the blog post data from a database, renders the React component for the blog post using that data into an HTML string.
3.  **Server Response:** The server sends this complete HTML string to the browser.
4.  **Browser Display:** The browser instantly displays the blog post content because it received full HTML.
5.  **Hydration:** In the background, JavaScript for the React app loads. Once loaded, it takes over the already rendered HTML, making buttons clickable, forms interactive, etc.

## Code Example (Conceptual - Next.js `getServerSideProps`)

While a full SSR setup is complex, here's a conceptual example using Next.js's `getServerSideProps` to illustrate data fetching on the server and passing it to a component for rendering.

```typescript
// pages/post/[id].tsx
import { GetServerSideProps } from 'next';
import React from 'react';

interface Post {
  id: string;
  title: string;
  content: string;
}

interface PostPageProps {
  post: Post;
}

const PostPage: React.FC<PostPageProps> = ({ post }) => {
  if (!post) {
    return <div>Post not found</div>;
  }
  return (
    <div>
      <h1>{post.title}</h1>
      <p>{post.content}</p>
      {/* Imagine other interactive components here that will be hydrated by client-side JS */}
      <button onClick={() => alert('Liked!')}>Like Post</button>
    </div>
  );
};

// This function runs on the server for every request to this page.
export const getServerSideProps: GetServerSideProps<PostPageProps> = async (context) => {
  const { id } = context.params as { id: string };

  try {
    // In a real app, you'd fetch from an API or database
    const response = await fetch(`https://api.example.com/posts/${id}`);
    if (!response.ok) {
        throw new Error(`Failed to fetch post: ${response.statusText}`);
    }
    const post: Post = await response.json();

    return {
      props: {
        post,
      },
    };
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Error fetching post:', error);
    return {
      notFound: true, // Render a 404 page if post not found or error
    };
  }
};

export default PostPage;
```

In this Next.js example, `getServerSideProps` is executed on the server *before* the component is rendered and sent to the browser. The `post` data is fetched, and the `PostPage` component is rendered into a complete HTML string on the server, including the post's title and content.

## Key Takeaways

### Pros:
*   **Improved Initial Page Load & Perceived Performance:** Users see content much faster because the browser receives a fully rendered HTML page immediately, rather than waiting for JavaScript to download and execute.
*   **Better SEO:** Search engine crawlers can easily parse the fully rendered HTML content, leading to better indexing and ranking compared to pages that rely heavily on client-side JavaScript for content.
*   **Accessibility for Non-JS Users/Bots:** Users with JavaScript disabled or bots that don't execute JavaScript can still access and view the core content.
*   **Easier to Share:** When sharing a link, the preview often shows the actual content because the HTML is fully formed.

### Cons:
*   **Increased Server Load:** Rendering pages on the server for every request consumes server resources (CPU, memory). This can be a bottleneck for high-traffic applications.
*   **Time To First Byte (TTFB) Can Be Slower:** While initial content display is faster, the server needs to process the request, fetch data, and render HTML, which can increase the time it takes for the *first byte* of the response to reach the client compared to just serving a static HTML file.
*   **Complexity:** Setting up and maintaining an SSR application can be more complex than a purely client-side rendered SPA, requiring server-side logic and environment management.
*   **"Hydration" Overhead:** After the initial HTML is displayed, the client-side JavaScript still needs to load and "hydrate" the page to make it interactive. If the JavaScript bundle is large, this can lead to a brief period where the page looks ready but isn't yet interactive (known as "time to interactive").

## Quick Summary
React Hooks are functions that let you "hook into" React state and lifecycle features from function components. They allow developers to write React components without classes, making code more readable, reusable, and easier to test.

## How It Works
Before Hooks, stateful logic and lifecycle methods were primarily managed within class components. Function components were "stateless" or "presentational." Hooks bridge this gap by providing functions like `useState` and `useEffect` that enable function components to manage state, perform side effects, and utilize other React features previously exclusive to classes.

**Practical Examples:**

1.  **`useState` for managing component state:**
    Instead of `this.state` and `this.setState`, `useState` returns a stateful value and a function to update it.

    ```typescript
    import React, { useState } from 'react';

    function Counter() {
      const [count, setCount] = useState(0); // Initialize count to 0

      return (
        <div>
          <p>Count: {count}</p>
          <button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>Increment</button>
        </div>
      );
    }
    ```

2.  **`useEffect` for side effects:**
    Replaces `componentDidMount`, `componentDidUpdate`, and `componentWillUnmount`. It runs after every render by default, but you can control when it runs using a dependency array.

    ```typescript
    import React, { useState, useEffect } from 'react';

    function Timer() {
      const [seconds, setSeconds] = useState(0);

      useEffect(() => {
        const interval = setInterval(() => {
          setSeconds(prevSeconds => prevSeconds + 1);
        }, 1000);

        // Cleanup function: runs when component unmounts or before re-running effect
        return () => clearInterval(interval);
      }, []); // Empty dependency array means effect runs once on mount and cleans up on unmount

      return (
        <div>
          <p>Elapsed seconds: {seconds}</p>
        </div>
      );
    }
    ```

## Code Example

```typescript
import React, { useState, useEffect, useCallback } from 'react';

interface Product {
  id: number;
  name: string;
  price: number;
}

function ProductDisplay() {
  const [products, setProducts] = useState<Product[]>([]);
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState<boolean>(true);
  const [error, setError] = useState<string | null>(null);
  const [filterText, setFilterText] = useState<string>('');

  // Effect to fetch products when the component mounts
  useEffect(() => {
    const fetchProducts = async () => {
      try {
        const response = await fetch('https://api.example.com/products'); // Replace with a real API endpoint
        if (!response.ok) {
          throw new Error(`HTTP error! status: ${response.status}`);
        }
        const data: Product[] = await response.json();
        setProducts(data);
      } catch (err: any) {
        setError(err.message);
      } finally {
        setLoading(false);
      }
    };

    fetchProducts();
  }, []); // Empty dependency array means this effect runs only once on mount

  // Memoized callback for filtering products
  const filteredProducts = useCallback(() => {
    return products.filter(product =>
      product.name.toLowerCase().includes(filterText.toLowerCase())
    );
  }, [products, filterText]); // Re-run only if products or filterText changes

  if (loading) return <p>Loading products...</p>;
  if (error) return <p>Error: {error}</p>;

  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Product List</h1>
      <input
        type="text"
        placeholder="Filter products..."
        value={filterText}
        onChange={(e) => setFilterText(e.target.value)}
      />
      <ul>
        {filteredProducts().map(product => (
          <li key={product.id}>
            {product.name} - ${product.price.toFixed(2)}
          </li>
        ))}
      </ul>
    </div>
  );
}
```

## Key Takeaways

*   **Pros:**
    *   **No Classes:** Write React components purely as functions, avoiding `this` binding issues and simplifying component structure.
    *   **Better Reusability:** Custom Hooks allow for easy extraction and reuse of stateful logic across multiple components.
    *   **Improved Readability:** Logic related to a single feature (e.g., data fetching) can be co-located within one or more Hooks, rather than split across different lifecycle methods in a class.
    *   **Smaller Bundle Sizes:** Hooks can lead to slightly smaller bundle sizes compared to classes due to less boilerplate.
    *   **Easier Testing:** Function components with Hooks are often simpler to test than class components.

*   **Cons:**
    *   **Learning Curve:** Can be a mental shift for developers accustomed to class components and their lifecycle methods.
    *   **Rules of Hooks:** Must follow specific rules (only call Hooks at the top level of a function component or custom Hook, and not inside loops, conditions, or nested functions) which can sometimes be tricky.
    *   **Stale Closures:** If dependencies in `useEffect` or `useCallback` are not correctly specified, you can encounter stale closures, leading to unexpected behavior.
    *   **Performance Optimization:** Requires careful use of `useMemo` and `useCallback` to prevent unnecessary re-renders, which can sometimes add complexity.

Redux is a predictable state container for JavaScript applications. It helps you write applications that behave consistently across different environments (client, server, and native), and are easy to test. While it's often used with React, it can be used with any view layer.

## Quick Summary
Redux provides a centralized store for managing application state, enforcing a strict unidirectional data flow. Its core benefits include predictability, debuggability, and a robust ecosystem, making complex state management more manageable. However, it comes with a learning curve and often requires more boilerplate code, which can be overkill for simpler applications.

## How It Works
Redux operates on three fundamental principles:

1.  **Single Source of Truth:** The entire state of your application is stored in a single object tree within a single *store*.
2.  **State is Read-Only:** The only way to change the state is to emit an *action*, an object describing what happened.
3.  **Changes are Made with Pure Functions:** To specify how the state tree is transformed by actions, you write pure *reducers*.

When an action is dispatched, it goes through a reducer, which computes the new state. Components subscribe to the store and re-render when relevant parts of the state change.

**Practical Example:** Imagine managing a user's login status and preferences. Without Redux, different components might hold pieces of this state, leading to prop drilling or complex callback chains. With Redux, `isLoggedIn` and `userPreferences` live in the central store. Any component can access them, and any state change (e.g., user logs out) is dispatched as an action, processed by a reducer, and updates the store predictably.

## Code Example

```typescript
// 1. Actions: Describe what happened
interface UserLoginAction {
  type: 'USER_LOGIN';
  payload: { username: string };
}

interface UserLogoutAction {
  type: 'USER_LOGOUT';
}

type UserAction = UserLoginAction | UserLogoutAction;

// 2. Reducer: How the state changes in response to actions
interface UserState {
  isLoggedIn: boolean;
  username: string | null;
}

const initialState: UserState = {
  isLoggedIn: false,
  username: null,
};

function userReducer(state: UserState = initialState, action: UserAction): UserState {
  switch (action.type) {
    case 'USER_LOGIN':
      return {
        ...state,
        isLoggedIn: true,
        username: action.payload.username,
      };
    case 'USER_LOGOUT':
      return {
        ...state,
        isLoggedIn: false,
        username: null,
      };
    default:
      return state;
  }
}

// 3. Store: Holds the application state
import { createStore } from 'redux';
const store = createStore(userReducer);

// Subscribe to state changes (e.g., in a React component)
store.subscribe(() => {
  console.log('Current state:', store.getState());
});

// Dispatch actions to change the state
store.dispatch({ type: 'USER_LOGIN', payload: { username: 'Alice' } });
// Output: Current state: { isLoggedIn: true, username: 'Alice' }

store.dispatch({ type: 'USER_LOGOUT' });
// Output: Current state: { isLoggedIn: false, username: null }
```

## Key Takeaways

### Pros:
*   **Predictable State Management:** Strict unidirectional data flow and pure reducers make state changes highly predictable and easy to reason about.
*   **Excellent Debugging:** Tools like Redux DevTools allow time-travel debugging, action replay, and state inspection, greatly simplifying bug identification.
*   **Centralized State:** A single source of truth makes it easy to understand where state lives and how it's updated.
*   **Maintainability & Testability:** Pure functions (reducers) are easy to test in isolation. The predictable nature aids in maintaining large applications.
*   **Robust Ecosystem & Middleware:** A rich ecosystem of middleware (e.g., Redux Thunk, Redux Saga for async logic) extends its capabilities.
*   **Server-Side Rendering (SSR):** State can be easily rehydrated on the client side, which is beneficial for SSR applications.

### Cons:
*   **Boilerplate Code:** Even for simple state changes, Redux often requires defining actions, action creators, and reducers, leading to more code than necessary for small apps.
*   **Steep Learning Curve:** Understanding concepts like immutability, pure functions, actions, reducers, and middleware can be challenging for beginners.
*   **Overkill for Simple Applications:** For applications with minimal state management needs, Redux can introduce unnecessary complexity and overhead.
*   **Performance Concerns (if not optimized):** If not properly optimized (e.g., using `reselect` for memoized selectors), frequent state updates can lead to unnecessary re-renders.
*   **Bundle Size:** Redux and its associated libraries can add to the application's bundle size, though often negligibly for larger projects.
*   **Modern Alternatives:** For React, the Context API combined with `useReducer` or state management libraries like Zustand or Jotai often offer simpler, less verbose solutions for many use cases.

Higher-Order Components (HOCs) are an advanced technique in React for reusing component logic. They are not part of the React API directly; rather, they are a pattern that emerges from React's compositional nature.

## Quick Summary
A Higher-Order Component (HOC) is a function that takes a component as an argument and returns a new component with enhanced props or behavior. It's a pattern for reusing stateful logic and UI-agnostic functionalities across multiple components without duplicating code.

## How It Works (with practical examples)
HOCs are essentially "component transformers." They wrap an original component, injecting additional props, state, or methods, or even modifying its rendering behavior. This is achieved by returning a new component (often an anonymous class or functional component) that renders the original component inside it, passing down the new props.

**Common use cases for HOCs:**
1.  **Code Reusability:** Share common functionalities like data fetching, subscriptions, or authentication logic.
2.  **Prop Manipulation:** Add, modify, or remove props from the wrapped component.
3.  **State Abstraction:** Abstract away stateful logic, making the wrapped component purely presentational.
4.  **Conditional Rendering:** Control when the wrapped component is rendered (e.g., `withAuth` to check logged-in status).

**Example: `withLogger` HOC**
Imagine you want to log whenever a component mounts and updates. Instead of adding `componentDidMount` and `componentDidUpdate` (or `useEffect` with dependencies) to every component, you can create a HOC.

```typescript
// Define a type for the props that the HOC will inject
interface WithLoggerProps {
  componentName: string;
}

// Define the HOC
function withLogger<P extends object>(
  WrappedComponent: React.ComponentType<P>,
  componentName: string
) {
  // Return a new functional component
  const WithLoggerComponent: React.FC<P> = (props) => {
    // Use an effect hook to log mount and update
    React.useEffect(() => {
      console.log(`[${componentName}] ${componentName} mounted.`);
      return () => {
        console.log(`[${componentName}] ${componentName} unmounted.`);
      };
    }, []); // Empty dependency array means this runs once on mount and cleanup on unmount

    React.useEffect(() => {
      console.log(`[${componentName}] ${componentName} updated.`);
    }); // No dependency array means this runs on every render

    // Render the original component, passing all its props
    return <WrappedComponent {...props} />;
  };

  // Give the new component a display name for easier debugging
  WithLoggerComponent.displayName = `withLogger(${componentName})`;

  return WithLoggerComponent;
}

// --- Usage ---

interface MyComponentProps {
  message: string;
}

const MyComponent: React.FC<MyComponentProps> = ({ message }) => {
  return <div>{message}</div>;
};

// Enhance MyComponent with the logger HOC
const EnhancedMyComponent = withLogger(MyComponent, 'MyComponent');

// In your App component:
const App: React.FC = () => {
  const [count, setCount] = React.useState(0);

  return (
    <div>
      <h1>HOC Example</h1>
      <EnhancedMyComponent message={`Hello from Enhanced Component! Count: ${count}`} />
      <button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>Increment Count</button>
    </div>
  );
};
```

When `App` renders `EnhancedMyComponent`, you'll see logs in the console indicating its mount, updates (when `App`'s state changes, causing a re-render), and unmount (if it were removed from the DOM).

## Code Example (TypeScript/JavaScript preferred)

```typescript
import React from 'react';

// 1. Define the props that the HOC will inject (if any)
interface WithLoadingProps {
  isLoading: boolean;
}

// 2. Define the HOC function
// It takes a component type and returns a new component type.
function withLoading<P extends object>(
  WrappedComponent: React.ComponentType<P>
): React.ComponentType<P & WithLoadingProps> {
  // The returned component is a functional component in this example
  const HOCComponent: React.FC<P & WithLoadingProps> = ({ isLoading, ...props }) => {
    if (isLoading) {
      return <div>Loading...</div>;
    }
    // Render the original component with its props
    return <WrappedComponent {...(props as P)} />;
  };

  // Set a display name for easier debugging in React DevTools
  HOCComponent.displayName = `withLoading(${getDisplayName(WrappedComponent)})`;

  return HOCComponent;
}

// Helper to get component display name
function getDisplayName<P>(WrappedComponent: React.ComponentType<P>) {
  return WrappedComponent.displayName || WrappedComponent.name || 'Component';
}

// --- Usage Example ---

// A simple component that will be wrapped
interface UserProfileProps {
  name: string;
  email: string;
}

const UserProfile: React.FC<UserProfileProps> = ({ name, email }) => {
  return (
    <div style={{ border: '1px solid gray', padding: '10px', margin: '10px' }}>
      <h3>{name}</h3>
      <p>Email: {email}</p>
    </div>
  );
};

// Create an enhanced component using the HOC
const UserProfileWithLoading = withLoading(UserProfile);

// --- Application Component ---
const App: React.FC = () => {
  const [userData, setUserData] = React.useState<{ name: string; email: string } | null>(null);
  const [loading, setLoading] = React.useState(true);

  React.useEffect(() => {
    // Simulate an API call
    setTimeout(() => {
      setUserData({ name: 'John Doe', email: 'john.doe@example.com' });
      setLoading(false);
    }, 2000);
  }, []);

  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Higher Order Component Example</h1>
      <UserProfileWithLoading
        isLoading={loading}
        name={userData?.name || ''}
        email={userData?.email || ''}
      />
      {/* Another instance, always loading */}
      <UserProfileWithLoading
        isLoading={true}
        name="Loading User"
        email="loading@example.com"
      />
    </div>
  );
};

export default App;
```

In this example, `withLoading` takes `UserProfile` and returns a new component `UserProfileWithLoading`. This new component checks the `isLoading` prop. If true, it displays a "Loading..." message; otherwise, it renders the original `UserProfile` component, passing through all other props.

## Key Takeaways
*   **Definition:** A function that takes a component and returns a new, enhanced component.
*   **Purpose:** Reuses component logic, abstracts state, manipulates props, and controls rendering.
*   **Composition over Inheritance:** HOCs are a powerful pattern for composition in React, avoiding the pitfalls of class inheritance for UI components.
*   **Prop Proxying:** HOCs typically render the wrapped component and pass through all props, potentially adding or modifying some.
*   **Naming Convention:** Often prefixed with `with` (e.g., `withRouter`, `withAuth`).
*   **Alternatives:** While powerful, HOCs can sometimes lead to prop name collisions or make the component tree harder to reason about. React Hooks (e.g., custom hooks) are now the primary and often preferred way to reuse stateful logic in functional components, offering a more direct and less nested approach. However, HOCs are still valid for certain use cases, especially with class components or when dealing with cross-cutting concerns that involve manipulating the component itself rather than just its data.

## Quick Summary
The Virtual DOM (VDOM) is a lightweight, in-memory representation of the actual DOM. It acts as an intermediate step between your component's render logic and the browser's DOM, significantly improving performance by minimizing direct manipulation of the slow real DOM.

## How It Works (with practical examples)
When a component's state or props change, instead of directly updating the browser's DOM, a new Virtual DOM tree is created. This new VDOM is then efficiently compared against the previous VDOM tree (a process called "diffing"). The diffing algorithm identifies the minimal set of changes required to synchronize the real DOM with the new state. Finally, only these identified changes are "batched" and applied to the actual browser DOM, leading to fewer and more targeted DOM manipulations.

**Practical Example:**
Imagine a list of 100 items where only one item's text changes.
1.  **Without Virtual DOM:** You might re-render the entire list, causing the browser to re-draw 100 DOM elements. This is inefficient.
2.  **With Virtual DOM:**
    *   A new VDOM tree is created representing the new state of the list.
    *   The diffing algorithm compares the new VDOM with the old VDOM. It quickly finds that 99 list items are identical and only one item's text content has changed.
    *   Only a single, targeted update is made to the real DOM element corresponding to the changed item. This is much faster.

## Code Example
While frameworks like React handle the Virtual DOM internally, we can illustrate the core concept of diffing and patching with a simplified example. This isn't how React's VDOM works exactly, but it demonstrates the principle of comparing two "virtual" structures and applying minimal real DOM updates.

```typescript
// Simplified representation of a Virtual Node
interface VNode {
  type: string;
  props: Record<string, any>;
  children: (VNode | string)[];
}

// Function to "create" a VNode (like React.createElement)
function h(type: string, props: Record<string, any>, ...children: (VNode | string)[]): VNode {
  return { type, props, children: children.flat() };
}

// Function to render a VNode to a real DOM element
function renderVNode(vNode: VNode | string): HTMLElement | Text {
  if (typeof vNode === 'string') {
    return document.createTextNode(vNode);
  }

  const el = document.createElement(vNode.type);
  for (const propName in vNode.props) {
    if (propName.startsWith('on') && typeof vNode.props[propName] === 'function') {
      el.addEventListener(propName.toLowerCase().substring(2), vNode.props[propName]);
    } else {
      el.setAttribute(propName, vNode.props[propName]);
    }
  }
  vNode.children.forEach(child => el.appendChild(renderVNode(child)));
  return el;
}

// Function to update properties on a real DOM element
function updateProps(target: HTMLElement, oldProps: Record<string, any>, newProps: Record<string, any>) {
  // Remove old props
  for (const propName in oldProps) {
    if (!(propName in newProps)) {
      if (propName.startsWith('on')) {
        target.removeEventListener(propName.toLowerCase().substring(2), oldProps[propName]);
      } else {
        target.removeAttribute(propName);
      }
    }
  }
  // Add/Update new props
  for (const propName in newProps) {
    if (oldProps[propName] !== newProps[propName]) {
      if (propName.startsWith('on') && typeof newProps[propName] === 'function') {
        if (typeof oldProps[propName] === 'function') {
          target.removeEventListener(propName.toLowerCase().substring(2), oldProps[propName]);
        }
        target.addEventListener(propName.toLowerCase().substring(2), newProps[propName]);
      } else {
        target.setAttribute(propName, newProps[propName]);
      }
    }
  }
}

// Simplified Diffing and Patching function
function patch(parent: HTMLElement, oldVNode: VNode | string | null, newVNode: VNode | string) {
  // Case 1: Old node doesn't exist (initial render)
  if (oldVNode === null) {
    parent.appendChild(renderVNode(newVNode));
    return;
  }

  // Case 2: New node is null/undefined (remove old node) - not covered in this minimal example
  // Case 3: Nodes are different types (replace)
  if (typeof oldVNode !== typeof newVNode || (typeof newVNode !== 'string' && oldVNode.type !== newVNode.type)) {
    parent.replaceChild(renderVNode(newVNode), parent.childNodes[0]); // Assuming single child for simplicity
    return;
  }

  // Case 4: Nodes are text nodes (update text content)
  if (typeof newVNode === 'string' && typeof oldVNode === 'string') {
    if (newVNode !== oldVNode) {
      parent.childNodes[0].nodeValue = newVNode;
    }
    return;
  }

  // Case 5: Nodes are element nodes (recursive diff)
  if (typeof newVNode !== 'string' && typeof oldVNode !== 'string') {
    const el = parent.childNodes[0] as HTMLElement; // Assuming single child
    updateProps(el, oldVNode.props, newVNode.props);

    // Diff children (very simplified: assumes same number of children, no keying)
    const oldChildren = oldVNode.children;
    const newChildren = newVNode.children;
    const minLength = Math.min(oldChildren.length, newChildren.length);

    for (let i = 0; i < minLength; i++) {
        patch(el, oldChildren[i], newChildren[i]);
    }
    // Handle adding/removing children (not fully implemented here for brevity)
  }
}

// --- Usage Example ---
let oldTree: VNode | null = null;
const appRoot = document.getElementById('app')!;

function render(newTree: VNode) {
    patch(appRoot, oldTree, newTree);
    oldTree = newTree;
}

let count = 0;
const increment = () => {
    count++;
    render(App());
};

const App = () => h('div', { id: 'container' },
  h('h1', null, 'Virtual DOM Demo'),
  h('p', null, 'Count: ', String(count)),
  h('button', { onClick: increment }, 'Increment')
);

// Initial render
render(App());

// Simulate a state update after 2 seconds
setTimeout(() => {
    console.log('Simulating state update...');
    count = 5; // Direct state change
    render(App()); // Re-render with new state
}, 2000);

setTimeout(() => {
    console.log('Simulating another state update...');
    count = 10;
    render(App());
}, 4000);
```

In the example:
1.  `h` creates a JavaScript object representing a DOM element (a VNode).
2.  `renderVNode` converts a VNode into a real DOM element for initial display.
3.  `patch` is our simplified diffing and patching function. It takes the parent DOM element, the old VNode tree, and the new VNode tree. It then compares them and applies only the necessary changes to the real DOM.
4.  Notice how `increment` only updates `count` and calls `render(App())`. The `render` function then uses `patch` to figure out that only the text content of the `<p>` tag needs to be updated in the real DOM, not the entire `div` or `h1`.

## Key Takeaways
*   **Performance Optimization:** The primary benefit is improved performance by reducing direct and costly manipulations of the real DOM.
*   **Abstraction:** It provides an abstraction layer, allowing developers to think about UI state rather than imperative DOM operations.
*   **Diffing Algorithm:** The core mechanism involves a fast comparison (diffing) between the old and new VDOM trees.
*   **Batching Updates:** Changes found during diffing are often batched and applied in a single pass to the real DOM, further optimizing performance.
*   **Framework Agnostic Concept:** While popularized by React, the concept is used in other frameworks like Vue.js (though Vue uses a slightly different approach with its reactivity system).
*   **Not Always Faster:** For very simple, static applications, the overhead of VDOM creation and diffing might actually be slightly slower than direct DOM manipulation. However, for complex, dynamic UIs, its benefits are significant.

## Quick Summary
The Event Loop is a fundamental mechanism in JavaScript (both browser and Node.js) that allows for asynchronous operations to be handled in a non-blocking way, despite JavaScript being single-threaded. It continuously checks if the call stack is empty and, if so, pushes tasks from the task queue (and microtask queue) onto the stack for execution.

## How It Works (with practical examples)
JavaScript engines have a single **Call Stack** where synchronous code is executed. When an asynchronous operation (like `setTimeout`, `fetch`, `fs.readFile`) is encountered, it's offloaded to a Web API (in browsers) or C++ APIs (in Node.js). Once the asynchronous operation completes, its callback function is not immediately pushed to the Call Stack. Instead, it's placed into a **Task Queue** (also known as MacroTask Queue) or **Microtask Queue**.

The **Event Loop** constantly monitors two things:
1.  Is the Call Stack empty?
2.  Are there pending tasks in the Microtask Queue or Task Queue?

The Event Loop prioritizes the **Microtask Queue** over the **Task Queue**. It will drain the *entire* Microtask Queue before taking *one* task from the Task Queue. This cycle repeats indefinitely.

**Order of Execution:**
1.  Synchronous code is executed and pushed onto the Call Stack.
2.  When the Call Stack is empty, the Event Loop checks the Microtask Queue.
3.  All pending microtasks are moved to the Call Stack and executed, one by one, until the Microtask Queue is empty.
4.  If the Call Stack is empty again, the Event Loop checks the Task Queue.
5.  One pending task is moved to the Call Stack and executed.
6.  The cycle then repeats from step 2 (drain microtasks, then one macrotask).

### Browser-specifics:
*   **Web APIs:** `setTimeout`, `setInterval`, `fetch`, DOM events (`click`, `onload`), `XMLHttpRequest`.
*   **Microtasks:** `Promise.then()`, `Promise.catch()`, `Promise.finally()`, `queueMicrotask()`, `MutationObserver`.
*   **Macrotasks:** `setTimeout`, `setInterval`, I/O, UI rendering, `requestAnimationFrame`.

### Node.js-specifics:
Node.js's Event Loop is more complex and phases-based, as it needs to handle server-side operations efficiently. It also uses `libuv` for asynchronous I/O.
The phases (simplified) are:
*   **timers:** Executes `setTimeout` and `setInterval` callbacks.
*   **pending callbacks:** Executes I/O callbacks deferred to the next loop iteration.
*   **idle, prepare:** Internal only.
*   **poll:** Retrieves new I/O events; executes I/O related callbacks (e.g., `fs.readFile`).
*   **check:** Executes `setImmediate()` callbacks.
*   **close callbacks:** Executes `close` event callbacks (e.g., `socket.on('close', ...)`).

**Node.js Microtasks:** `Promise.then()`, `process.nextTick()`.
`process.nextTick()` is *not* part of the Event Loop phases; it's executed even *before* microtasks within the current phase, and before the Event Loop moves to the next phase. It essentially drains *immediately* after the current operation and before the Event Loop determines whether to continue or move to the next phase.

**Example:**

```typescript
console.log('1. Start'); // Synchronous

setTimeout(() => {
  console.log('4. setTimeout (MacroTask)'); // MacroTask
}, 0);

Promise.resolve().then(() => {
  console.log('3. Promise (MicroTask)'); // MicroTask
});

// Node.js specific
if (typeof process !== 'undefined' && process.nextTick) {
  process.nextTick(() => {
    console.log('2. process.nextTick (Node.js specific, highest priority)'); // Node.js specific MicroTask
  });
}

console.log('5. End'); // Synchronous
```

**Expected Output (Browser):**
```
1. Start
5. End
3. Promise (MicroTask)
4. setTimeout (MacroTask)
```

**Expected Output (Node.js):**
```
1. Start
5. End
2. process.nextTick (Node.js specific, highest priority)
3. Promise (MicroTask)
4. setTimeout (MacroTask)
```
**Explanation:**
1.  `1. Start` is synchronous, executed immediately.
2.  `setTimeout` is offloaded to Web/Node.js APIs. Its callback is put into the **Task Queue**.
3.  `Promise.resolve().then()`'s callback is put into the **Microtask Queue**.
4.  `process.nextTick()` (Node.js only) is placed into a special queue that is processed *before* any other microtasks or macrotasks.
5.  `5. End` is synchronous, executed immediately.
6.  Call Stack is now empty.
7.  Event Loop checks for `process.nextTick()` (Node.js). If present, it executes.
8.  Event Loop checks the **Microtask Queue** and executes `Promise`'s callback.
9.  Event Loop checks the **Task Queue** and executes `setTimeout`'s callback.

## Code Example

```typescript
function simulateAsyncTask(name: string, delay: number, isMicrotask: boolean = false): void {
  if (isMicrotask) {
    // Using Promise for microtask simulation
    Promise.resolve().then(() => {
      console.log(`[Microtask] ${name} executed after ${delay}ms logical delay.`);
    });
  } else {
    // Using setTimeout for macrotask simulation
    setTimeout(() => {
      console.log(`[Macrotask] ${name} executed after ${delay}ms.`);
    }, delay);
  }
}

console.log('--- Start of Execution ---');

// Synchronous code
console.log('Synchronous task 1');

// Microtasks
simulateAsyncTask('Promise 1', 0, true);
simulateAsyncTask('Promise 2', 0, true);

// Macrotasks
simulateAsyncTask('Timeout 1 (delay 100ms)', 100);
simulateAsyncTask('Timeout 2 (delay 0ms)', 0);

// Node.js specific immediate microtask
if (typeof process !== 'undefined' && process.nextTick) {
  process.nextTick(() => {
    console.log('[Node.js nextTick] Highest priority microtask');
  });
}

// Another synchronous task
console.log('Synchronous task 2');

console.log('--- End of Execution ---');

// Expected Node.js Output Structure:
// --- Start of Execution ---
// Synchronous task 1
// Synchronous task 2
// --- End of Execution ---
// [Node.js nextTick] Highest priority microtask
// [Microtask] Promise 1 executed after 0ms logical delay.
// [Microtask] Promise 2 executed after 0ms logical delay.
// [Macrotask] Timeout 2 (delay 0ms) executed after 0ms.
// [Macrotask] Timeout 1 (delay 100ms) executed after 100ms.

// Expected Browser Output Structure:
// --- Start of Execution ---
// Synchronous task 1
// Synchronous task 2
// --- End of Execution ---
// [Microtask] Promise 1 executed after 0ms logical delay.
// [Microtask] Promise 2 executed after 0ms logical delay.
// [Macrotask] Timeout 2 (delay 0ms) executed after 0ms.
// [Macrotask] Timeout 1 (delay 100ms) executed after 100ms.
```

## Key Takeaways

*   **Single-threaded but Non-blocking:** JavaScript is single-threaded, but the Event Loop enables asynchronous, non-blocking I/O.
*   **Call Stack:** Executes synchronous code.
*   **Task Queues:** Hold callbacks for asynchronous operations once they complete.
    *   **Microtask Queue:** High priority (e.g., `Promise.then()`, `queueMicrotask()`, `process.nextTick()` in Node.js). Drained completely before a new macrotask.
    *   **Task/Macrotask Queue:** Lower priority (e.g., `setTimeout`, `setInterval`, I/O events). One task processed per Event Loop iteration.
*   **Event Loop's Role:** Continuously checks if the Call Stack is empty, then pushes tasks from microtask queue (all of them) or task queue (one at a time) onto the stack.
*   **Browser vs. Node.js:** Both share the core concept, but Node.js has additional phases and `process.nextTick()` which has even higher priority than regular microtasks.
*   **Priority:** `Synchronous Code` > `process.nextTick()` (Node.js) > `Microtasks` > `Macrotasks`.

Memory leaks are a common problem in software development, especially in long-running applications. In JavaScript, memory leaks occur when objects are no longer needed but are still referenced, preventing the garbage collector from reclaiming the memory they occupy. This leads to increased memory consumption over time, which can degrade performance and eventually crash the application.

## Quick Summary
A memory leak occurs when a program fails to release memory that is no longer needed, causing it to accumulate over time. In JavaScript, this typically happens when references to objects persist even after those objects are logically out of scope, preventing the garbage collector from reclaiming the memory.

## How It Works (with practical examples)
JavaScript engines use a garbage collector to automatically manage memory. It identifies and reclaims memory occupied by objects that are no longer reachable from the root (global object or active function stacks). A memory leak happens when an object, though no longer actively used by the application logic, remains reachable due to an unintentional reference.

Common causes of memory leaks in JavaScript:

1.  **Accidental Global Variables:**
    If you forget to declare a variable with `const`, `let`, or `var` inside a function, it becomes a global variable (in non-strict mode) or throws an error (in strict mode). Global variables are never garbage collected unless explicitly deleted or the page unloads.

    ```javascript
    function createLeak() {
        // 'data' becomes a global variable if not declared with var/let/const
        // In strict mode, this would throw a ReferenceError.
        // In non-strict mode (like old browsers), window.data would be created.
        data = new Array(1000000).join('x'); // Large string
    }
    createLeak();
    // 'data' is now on the global object (e.g., window.data in browsers)
    // and will not be garbage collected until the page unloads.
    ```

2.  **Detached DOM Elements:**
    When you remove DOM elements from the document, but still hold a reference to them in JavaScript, they won't be garbage collected. This includes their children and any data attached to them.

    ```javascript
    let elements = [];

    function addElement() {
        const ul = document.getElementById('myList');
        const li = document.createElement('li');
        li.textContent = 'Item ' + elements.length;
        ul.appendChild(li);
        elements.push(li); // We keep a reference to the element
    }

    function removeAllElements() {
        const ul = document.getElementById('myList');
        while (ul.firstChild) {
            ul.removeChild(ul.firstChild);
        }
        // At this point, all <li> elements are removed from the DOM.
        // HOWEVER, 'elements' array still holds references to them.
        // They are not garbage collected until 'elements' is cleared or goes out of scope.
        // To prevent leak: elements = [];
    }

    // Example Usage:
    // <ul id="myList"></ul>
    // <button onclick="addElement()">Add Item</button>
    // <button onclick="removeAllElements()">Remove All</button>
    ```

3.  **Timers (setInterval, setTimeout) that are not cleared:**
    If `setInterval` or `setTimeout` callbacks reference objects, and the timer is never cleared, those objects (and their closures) will remain in memory.

    ```javascript
    let heavyObject = {
        data: new Array(1000000).join('x'),
        id: 123
    };

    function startLeakyTimer() {
        // This timer will run indefinitely, and its closure will keep a reference
        // to 'heavyObject', preventing it from being garbage collected.
        setInterval(() => {
            console.log('Timer running for object ID:', heavyObject.id);
            // heavyObject will never be GC'd as long as this timer is active
        }, 1000);
    }

    // startLeakyTimer();
    // To prevent leak: Must store the interval ID and call clearInterval(id)
    ```

4.  **Event Listeners that are not removed:**
    If you attach event listeners to DOM elements (or other objects) and don't remove them when the elements/objects are no longer needed, the listener callback (and its closure) can keep the target object alive. This is particularly common in single-page applications where components are dynamically added and removed.

    ```javascript
    let elementRef;

    function createAndAttachListener() {
        const button = document.createElement('button');
        button.textContent = 'Click me';
        document.body.appendChild(button);

        // The handler function forms a closure that captures 'button'
        function handleClick() {
            console.log('Button clicked');
        }

        button.addEventListener('click', handleClick);
        elementRef = button; // Keep a reference to simulate it being "removed" from DOM later
        // If button is later removed from DOM, but elementRef still points to it,
        // and the event listener is still attached, it's a leak.
    }

    function removeElementButLeak() {
        if (elementRef) {
            document.body.removeChild(elementRef);
            // The button is removed from the DOM, but elementRef still holds a reference.
            // Crucially, the 'handleClick' closure (via the event listener) also
            // holds a reference to the button. So it's not GC'd.
            elementRef = null; // Even setting this to null isn't enough if listener persists
        }
    }

    // To prevent leak:
    // button.removeEventListener('click', handleClick);
    // elementRef = null;
    ```

5.  **Closures:**
    While powerful, closures can inadvertently lead to memory leaks if a closure captures a large object and the closure itself is kept alive longer than necessary (e.g., by being part of a long-lived object, a global array, or an uncleared timer/event listener).

    ```javascript
    const cache = [];

    function createLeakyClosure() {
        let largeData = new Array(1000000).join('y'); // Large string
        let someId = Math.random();

        const innerFunction = () => {
            // This closure captures 'largeData' and 'someId'
            console.log('Accessed data for ID:', someId);
            // If innerFunction is stored somewhere and never released,
            // 'largeData' will also never be released.
        };

        cache.push(innerFunction); // Adding to a global cache prevents GC
    }

    // createLeakyClosure(); // Call multiple times to fill cache
    // The 'largeData' from each call will remain in memory.
    // To prevent leak: Periodically clear the cache or remove specific functions.
    // cache = []; // To clear all
    ```

## Code Example (TypeScript/JavaScript preferred)

This example demonstrates a common memory leak scenario with detached DOM elements and event listeners, and how to fix it.

```typescript
// --- LEAKY CODE ---
let detachedElements: HTMLElement[] = []; // Global array to hold references

function createLeakyComponent(): void {
    const container = document.getElementById('app');
    if (!container) return;

    const div = document.createElement('div');
    div.classList.add('leaky-box');
    div.textContent = `Leaky Box ${detachedElements.length}`;

    // Attach a large object to the element to make the leak more prominent
    (div as any).largeData = new Array(1000000).join('x');

    // Attach an event listener that references the div itself
    // The callback forms a closure over 'div'
    div.addEventListener('click', function handler() {
        console.log(`Leaky box ${this.textContent} clicked!`);
        // If this listener isn't removed, 'div' won't be GC'd even if removed from DOM
    });

    container.appendChild(div);
    detachedElements.push(div); // Keep a reference
    console.log(`Created leaky component. Total: ${detachedElements.length}`);
}

function removeLeakyComponents(): void {
    const container = document.getElementById('app');
    if (!container) return;

    // Remove all children from the DOM
    while (container.firstChild) {
        container.removeChild(container.firstChild);
    }

    // At this point, all 'div' elements are removed from the DOM.
    // HOWEVER, the 'detachedElements' array still holds references,
    // AND the event listeners still hold references via their closures.
    // So, nothing is garbage collected.
    console.log(`Removed components from DOM. detachedElements length: ${detachedElements.length}`);
    console.log("Memory is still leaked because 'detachedElements' holds references and listeners persist.");
}

// --- NON-LEAKY (FIXED) CODE ---
let cleanElements: { element: HTMLElement, handler: EventListener }[] = [];

function createCleanComponent(): void {
    const container = document.getElementById('app');
    if (!container) return;

    const div = document.createElement('div');
    div.classList.add('clean-box');
    div.textContent = `Clean Box ${cleanElements.length}`;

    // Attach a large object to the element
    (div as any).largeData = new Array(1000000).join('x');

    // Define the handler separately to allow removal
    const handler = function(this: HTMLElement) {
        console.log(`Clean box ${this.textContent} clicked!`);
    };

    div.addEventListener('click', handler);

    container.appendChild(div);
    cleanElements.push({ element: div, handler: handler }); // Store element and handler
    console.log(`Created clean component. Total: ${cleanElements.length}`);
}

function removeCleanComponents(): void {
    const container = document.getElementById('app');
    if (!container) return;

    // First, remove event listeners and clear references
    cleanElements.forEach(({ element, handler }) => {
        element.removeEventListener('click', handler); // Crucial for preventing leak
        // Explicitly nullify large data if needed, though GC should handle after dereferencing
        (element as any).largeData = null;
    });
    cleanElements = []; // Clear the array to release references

    // Then, remove all children from the DOM
    while (container.firstChild) {
        container.removeChild(container.firstChild);
    }
    console.log(`Removed clean components from DOM and cleared references. cleanElements length: ${cleanElements.length}`);
    console.log("Memory should now be eligible for garbage collection.");
}

// HTML setup for testing:
/*
<div id="app" style="border: 1px solid black; padding: 10px; min-height: 50px;"></div>
<button onclick="createLeakyComponent()">Create Leaky Component</button>
<button onclick="removeLeakyComponents()">Remove Leaky Components (Leak!)</button>
<hr/>
<button onclick="createCleanComponent()">Create Clean Component</button>
<button onclick="removeCleanComponents()">Remove Clean Components (No Leak)</button>
*/
```

## How to Debug
Debugging memory leaks usually involves using browser developer tools.

1.  **Performance Monitor (Chrome DevTools):**
    *   Open DevTools (F12).
    *   Go to the "Performance" tab.
    *   Click the record button, interact with your application (e.g., repeatedly add/remove components that you suspect are leaking), then stop recording.
    *   Observe the "JS Heap" graph. A steadily increasing baseline in the "JS Heap" over time (without corresponding drops after operations that should free memory) is a strong indicator of a memory leak.

2.  **Memory Panel (Chrome DevTools):**
    *   Open DevTools.
    *   Go to the "Memory" tab.
    *   **Heap snapshots:** Take a heap snapshot *before* performing an action that might leak memory. Then perform the action (e.g., create 10 components). Take another snapshot. Perform the action again (create another 10 components). Take a third snapshot.
        *   Compare the snapshots (e.g., select Snapshot 2 and choose "Objects allocated between Snapshot 1 and Snapshot 2"). Look for objects that are unexpectedly retained or whose count keeps increasing.
        *   Filter by constructor name (e.g., `Detached HTMLDivElement`, `HTMLDivElement`, or your custom class names).
        *   Expand the retained tree to see *why* an object is being kept alive (which references point to it). This is the most powerful way to pinpoint the source of a leak.
    *   **Allocation instrumentation on timeline:** This records memory allocations over time and is useful for seeing where memory is being allocated in real-time.

## How to Prevent

1.  **Be Mindful of Global Variables:** Always declare variables using `const`, `let`, or `var`. Use strict mode (`'use strict';`) to prevent accidental global variable creation.
2.  **Clear Timers:** Always clear `setInterval` and `setTimeout` using `clearInterval()` and `clearTimeout()` respectively, especially when components unmount or become inactive.
3.  **Remove Event Listeners:** Always remove event listeners using `removeEventListener()` when the element or object they are attached to is no longer needed. This is crucial for dynamically created/destroyed components.
4.  **Dereference Detached DOM Elements:** When removing DOM elements, ensure that any JavaScript references to those elements (and their children) are also cleared (e.g., by setting variables to `null` or emptying arrays that held them).
5.  **Manage Caches and Data Structures:** If you're using custom caches or data structures, ensure that old or unused entries are properly removed. Consider using `WeakMap` or `WeakSet` if you need to associate data with objects without preventing them from being garbage collected (as long as the object itself is not strongly referenced elsewhere).
6.  **Avoid Unnecessary Closures:** While closures are fundamental, be aware that they capture their lexical environment. If a closure is stored for a long time and captures a large object, that object will not be garbage collected.
7.  **Use `WeakMap` and `WeakSet`:** These data structures hold "weak" references to objects. If the only reference to an object is from a `WeakMap` or `WeakSet`, that object can still be garbage collected. This is useful for associating metadata with objects without preventing their collection.
8.  **Profile Regularly:** Get into the habit of using browser developer tools (especially the Memory tab) to profile your application's memory usage, particularly after implementing new features or refactoring.

## Quick Summary
Garbage Collection in JavaScript is an automatic process that reclaims memory occupied by objects that are no longer referenced or reachable by the application. Its primary goal is to prevent memory leaks and allow developers to focus on application logic rather than manual memory management.

## How It Works
JavaScript engines (like V8 in Chrome or SpiderMonkey in Firefox) employ a "Mark-and-Sweep" algorithm as their primary garbage collection strategy, often with optimizations.

1.  **Mark Phase:** The garbage collector starts from a set of "roots." Roots are global objects (e.g., `window` or `global`), the currently executing function's local variables, and parameters. It then "marks" all objects reachable from these roots. This means if an object can be accessed by the running application, it's marked as "not garbage." It traverses the entire object graph, marking every object it encounters.

    *   **Practical Example:** If you have a `const user = { name: 'Alice' };` in your global scope, `user` is a root. The object `{ name: 'Alice' }` is reachable from `user`, so it's marked. If `user.address = { street: 'Main St' };` then the `{ street: 'Main St' }` object is reachable from `user.address`, which is reachable from `user`, so it's also marked.

2.  **Sweep Phase:** After all reachable objects have been marked, the garbage collector "sweeps" through the memory heap. Any object that was *not* marked during the mark phase is considered unreachable and therefore garbage. The memory occupied by these unmarked objects is then reclaimed and returned to the system for future allocations.

    *   **Practical Example:** If you later set `user = null;`, the original `{ name: 'Alice' }` object is no longer reachable from any root. In the next GC cycle, it won't be marked and will be swept away.

### Optimizations and Other Strategies:
*   **Generational Collection:** Most modern GCs categorize objects into "generations." Newly created objects (young generation) are often short-lived. The GC checks the young generation more frequently and with a faster algorithm. Objects that survive multiple young generation collections are promoted to the "old generation," which is collected less frequently with a more thorough (and slower) algorithm. This is based on the "weak generational hypothesis" that most objects die young.
*   **Incremental Collection:** To avoid "stop-the-world" pauses (where the application execution is halted during GC), modern collectors can perform the mark phase incrementally, breaking it into smaller chunks. This allows the application to continue running for short periods between GC chunks, leading to a smoother user experience.
*   **Concurrent/Parallel Collection:** Some parts of the GC process (like marking) can be run concurrently on separate threads without stopping the main application thread, or in parallel using multiple threads to speed up the process.

## Code Example
```typescript
// Global object, a root
let globalObject: { data: string | null } = { data: "I am reachable globally" };

function createAndLoseReference() {
    let localObject: { value: number } = { value: 123 }; // Local variable, reachable within this function

    const anotherObject = {
        id: 1,
        nested: {
            info: "This is deeply nested"
        }
    };
    // anotherObject and its nested properties are reachable here.

    console.log("Local object created:", localObject);
    console.log("Another object created:", anotherObject);

    // If we don't return or assign localObject to a global variable,
    // it becomes unreachable once the function scope exits.
    // The same applies to anotherObject.
}

function createAndKeepReference(input: string) {
    const keptObject = { message: `Hello, ${input}` };
    globalObject.data = JSON.stringify(keptObject); // Assign reference to a global object
    console.log("Kept object reference stored globally.");
}

console.log("--- Before GC example ---");
createAndLoseReference();
// At this point, `localObject` and `anotherObject` from `createAndLoseReference`
// are no longer reachable and are candidates for garbage collection.

createAndKeepReference("World");
// `keptObject` (specifically its stringified version) is now reachable via `globalObject.data`.

console.log("Global object after keeping reference:", globalObject);

// Manually trigger GC (not standard or guaranteed in browsers/Node.js,
// but conceptually represents a GC cycle).
// In Node.js, you can run with --expose-gc and then call global.gc();
// In browser dev tools, you can often force a GC cycle.
// For demonstration purposes, we'll just acknowledge it conceptually.

console.log("\n--- After conceptual GC cycle ---");
// The memory used by the objects from `createAndLoseReference` would ideally be reclaimed now.

// Later, if we remove the global reference:
globalObject.data = null;
console.log("Global object reference removed:", globalObject);
// Now the object previously referenced by `globalObject.data` is also a candidate for GC.
```

## Key Takeaways
*   **Automatic Memory Management:** JavaScript's GC is automatic, freeing developers from manual memory allocation and deallocation.
*   **Mark-and-Sweep:** The core algorithm identifies reachable objects (marks them) and then reclaims memory from unreachable ones (sweeps them).
*   **Roots of Reachability:** Objects are considered "reachable" if they can be accessed from a set of known roots (global objects, current call stack).
*   **Memory Leaks:** While automatic, memory leaks can still occur if references to objects are unintentionally held, preventing them from being garbage collected (e.g., forgotten event listeners, global caches that grow indefinitely).
*   **Optimizations:** Modern JavaScript engines use sophisticated optimizations like generational collection, incremental collection, and concurrent/parallel execution to improve performance and reduce "stop-the-world" pauses.

Let's break down Web Workers and Service Workers.

## Quick Summary
**Web Workers** are a way to run scripts in the background threads, separate from the main execution thread of a web page. This prevents long-running scripts from blocking the UI and making the page unresponsive. **Service Workers** are a specialized type of Web Worker that acts as a programmable network proxy, sitting between your web application and the network. They enable powerful features like offline experiences, push notifications, and asset caching.

## How It Works

### Web Workers
Web Workers operate in an isolated scope and communicate with the main thread via message passing. They have no direct access to the DOM or the `window` object of the main thread.

**Practical Examples:**
*   Performing complex calculations (e.g., cryptographic operations, image processing) without freezing the UI.
*   Loading and parsing large data sets in the background.
*   Running game logic or physics simulations in a separate thread.

### Service Workers
Service Workers are JavaScript files that run in the background, separate from the web page, and even when the browser is closed. They intercept network requests made by the page, allowing you to control how resources are fetched and cached. They operate over HTTPS for security reasons due to their powerful capabilities.

**Life Cycle:**
1.  **Registration:** The browser registers the Service Worker file.
2.  **Installation:** The Service Worker is downloaded and the `install` event is fired. This is a good place to precache essential assets.
3.  **Activation:** After installation, the `activate` event is fired. This is often used for cleaning up old caches.
4.  **Fetching:** Once active, the Service Worker intercepts network requests via the `fetch` event.

**Practical Examples:**
*   **Offline First:** Caching application shell and data to provide an instant, reliable experience even without a network connection.
*   **Push Notifications:** Receiving messages from a server and displaying notifications to the user.
*   **Background Sync:** Deferring actions (e.g., sending unsent messages) until the user has a stable internet connection.
*   **Custom Caching Strategies:** Implementing sophisticated caching rules (e.g., "cache, then network," "network, then cache").

## Code Example

### Web Worker Example

**`main.js` (main thread)**
```typescript
// Create a new Web Worker
const myWorker = new Worker('worker.js');

// Send data to the worker
myWorker.postMessage({ number: 1000000000 });

// Listen for messages from the worker
myWorker.onmessage = (event) => {
    console.log('Main thread received:', event.data);
    // Update UI with result (e.g., document.getElementById('result').textContent = event.data.result;)
};

// Handle errors from the worker
myWorker.onerror = (error) => {
    console.error('Worker error:', error);
};

console.log('Main thread continues to run...');
```

**`worker.js` (worker thread)**
```typescript
onmessage = (event) => {
    const { number } = event.data;
    console.log('Worker received:', number);

    // Perform a heavy computation
    let sum = 0;
    for (let i = 0; i < number; i++) {
        sum += i;
    }

    // Send the result back to the main thread
    postMessage({ result: sum });
};
```

### Service Worker Example

**`main.js` (main thread - registration)**
```typescript
if ('serviceWorker' in navigator) {
    window.addEventListener('load', () => {
        navigator.serviceWorker.register('/service-worker.js')
            .then(registration => {
                console.log('Service Worker registered with scope:', registration.scope);
            })
            .catch(error => {
                console.error('Service Worker registration failed:', error);
            });
    });
}
```

**`service-worker.js`**
```typescript
const CACHE_NAME = 'my-app-cache-v1';
const urlsToCache = [
    '/',
    '/index.html',
    '/styles.css',
    '/app.js',
    '/images/logo.png'
];

// Install event: precache assets
self.addEventListener('install', (event) => {
    console.log('[Service Worker] Installing...');
    event.waitUntil(
        caches.open(CACHE_NAME)
            .then((cache) => {
                console.log('[Service Worker] Caching app shell');
                return cache.addAll(urlsToCache);
            })
    );
});

// Activate event: clean up old caches
self.addEventListener('activate', (event) => {
    console.log('[Service Worker] Activating...');
    event.waitUntil(
        caches.keys().then((cacheNames) => {
            return Promise.all(
                cacheNames.map((cacheName) => {
                    if (cacheName !== CACHE_NAME) {
                        console.log('[Service Worker] Deleting old cache:', cacheName);
                        return caches.delete(cacheName);
                    }
                })
            );
        })
    );
    return self.clients.claim(); // Ensures the service worker controls clients immediately
});

// Fetch event: intercept network requests
self.addEventListener('fetch', (event) => {
    event.respondWith(
        caches.match(event.request)
            .then((response) => {
                // Cache hit - return response from cache
                if (response) {
                    console.log('[Service Worker] Serving from cache:', event.request.url);
                    return response;
                }
                // No cache hit - fetch from network
                console.log('[Service Worker] Fetching from network:', event.request.url);
                return fetch(event.request)
                    .then((networkResponse) => {
                        // Optionally, cache new responses
                        return caches.open(CACHE_NAME).then((cache) => {
                            // Don't cache POST requests or range requests, etc.
                            if (event.request.method === 'GET' && networkResponse.ok) {
                                cache.put(event.request, networkResponse.clone());
                            }
                            return networkResponse;
                        });
                    });
            })
            .catch((error) => {
                console.error('[Service Worker] Fetch failed:', error);
                // Can return an offline page or fallback asset here
                // return caches.match('/offline.html');
            })
    );
});
```

## Key Takeaways

*   **Web Workers for Performance:** Offload heavy computations from the main thread to keep the UI responsive.
*   **Service Workers for Reliability & Engagement:** Enable offline capabilities, push notifications, and background sync, transforming web apps into more robust and engaging experiences.
*   **Isolation and Messaging:** Both worker types run in separate threads and communicate with the main thread via `postMessage()` and `onmessage` listeners.
*   **No DOM Access:** Neither Web Workers nor Service Workers can directly access the DOM.
*   **Service Workers are Proxies:** They sit between the browser and the network, giving you fine-grained control over network requests.
*   **HTTPS Requirement:** Service Workers require HTTPS (or localhost) for security reasons.

## Quick Summary
**Reflow** (also known as Layout) is the process of calculating the position and size of all elements in the document. It's a very expensive operation as it often triggers a repaint. **Repaint** is the process of redrawing the pixels of an element on the screen after its visual properties have changed, but its layout (position and size) has not.

## How It Works (with practical examples)

### Reflow (Layout)
A reflow occurs when the browser has to recalculate the layout of part or all of the document. This happens when changes affect the geometry of elements, such as their width, height, position, or the content itself. Because elements often depend on each other, a change to one element can trigger a reflow for many other elements, and sometimes even the entire document. This is computationally expensive, as the browser needs to reconstruct the render tree and recalculate the layout.

**Triggers for Reflow:**
*   **DOM manipulation:** Adding, removing, or updating elements.
*   **Modifying CSS properties that affect layout:** `width`, `height`, `padding`, `margin`, `border`, `display`, `position`, `float`, `font-size`, `text-align`, `overflow`, etc.
*   **Window resizing:** Changing the browser window's dimensions.
*   **Activating pseudo-classes:** e.g., `:hover` that changes layout properties.
*   **Calculating styles:** Accessing certain computed style properties (e.g., `offsetHeight`, `offsetWidth`, `getComputedStyle()`) can force the browser to perform a reflow synchronously to ensure it returns an up-to-date value.
*   **Changing content:** A text input or image that changes its size.

**Example of Reflow:**
Changing an element's width will cause a reflow because it affects the geometry of the element and potentially its neighbors.

```typescript
const element = document.getElementById('myElement');
if (element) {
    // This will cause a Reflow (and then a Repaint)
    element.style.width = '200px';
}
```

### Repaint (Redraw)
A repaint occurs when changes are made to an element's visual properties that do not affect its layout or geometry. The browser doesn't need to recalculate the positions or sizes of other elements; it just needs to redraw the pixels for the changed element(s). Repaints are less expensive than reflows but should still be minimized.

**Triggers for Repaint:**
*   **Modifying CSS properties that only affect rendering, not layout:** `color`, `background-color`, `visibility`, `box-shadow`, `text-decoration`, `outline`, `border-radius` (if not affecting size), `transform` (if only translation/rotation without affecting layout box), `opacity`.

**Example of Repaint:**
Changing an element's background color will cause a repaint without a reflow.

```typescript
const element = document.getElementById('myElement');
if (element) {
    // This will cause a Repaint (no Reflow)
    element.style.backgroundColor = 'blue';
}
```

## Code Example

```typescript
// Assume we have an HTML structure like:
// <div id="container">
//   <div id="box" class="box-style"></div>
//   <div id="anotherBox" class="box-style"></div>
// </div>

const box = document.getElementById('box');
const anotherBox = document.getElementById('anotherBox');

if (box && anotherBox) {
    console.log("Initial state of boxes...");

    // --- Example 1: Triggering a Reflow (and subsequent Repaint) ---
    // Changing width affects geometry and layout of 'box' and potentially 'anotherBox'
    console.log("Changing width of #box - Triggers Reflow and Repaint.");
    box.style.width = '300px'; 
    // This might also cause 'anotherBox' to shift, leading to a wider reflow scope.

    // Accessing computed styles that require up-to-date layout can force a synchronous reflow
    // This is known as "layout thrashing" if done repeatedly in a loop.
    console.log("Forcing synchronous reflow by accessing offsetHeight:", box.offsetHeight);

    // --- Example 2: Triggering only a Repaint ---
    // Changing background-color only affects visual appearance, not layout
    console.log("Changing background-color of #anotherBox - Triggers only Repaint.");
    anotherBox.style.backgroundColor = 'lightgreen';

    // Changing opacity also triggers only a Repaint
    console.log("Changing opacity of #box - Triggers only Repaint.");
    box.style.opacity = '0.5';

    // --- Example 3: Batching DOM changes to minimize Reflows ---
    // It's generally good practice to make multiple layout-affecting changes
    // while the element is detached from the DOM, or using CSS classes.

    const container = document.getElementById('container');
    if (container) {
        console.log("Batching changes for #container to minimize reflows.");
        // Detach the element from the DOM
        const fragment = document.createDocumentFragment();
        fragment.appendChild(container);

        // Perform multiple layout changes while detached
        container.style.padding = '20px'; // Reflow
        container.style.border = '2px solid purple'; // Reflow
        container.style.marginBottom = '15px'; // Reflow

        // Re-attach the element (triggers a single reflow/repaint for all batched changes)
        document.body.appendChild(container); // Or its original parent
        console.log("Re-attached #container. One reflow/repaint occurred for batched changes.");
    }
}
```

## Key Takeaways
*   **Reflow (Layout) is expensive:** It recalculates the geometry of elements, potentially affecting many or all elements on the page.
*   **Repaint is less expensive:** It only redraws pixels for visual changes that don't affect layout.
*   **Reflow always triggers a Repaint:** If layout changes, the browser must redraw the affected elements.
*   **Optimize for performance:** Minimize both reflows and repaints, especially reflows.
    *   **Batch DOM changes:** Make multiple changes to an element off-DOM (e.g., using `DocumentFragment`) or by changing CSS classes.
    *   **Avoid layout thrashing:** Don't read a computed style property (e.g., `offsetHeight`, `getComputedStyle`) immediately after modifying a layout-affecting property in a loop. This forces synchronous reflows.
    *   **Use CSS transformations and opacity:** Properties like `transform` (for translation/rotation) and `opacity` can often be handled by the compositor, leading to much smoother animations without triggering reflows or even repaints on the main thread.

## Quick Summary
`keep-alive` is a built-in Vue component that allows you to conditionally cache component instances when dynamically switching between multiple components. Its primary use case is to preserve the state and avoid re-rendering of inactive components, improving performance and user experience, especially with tabbed interfaces or dynamic forms.

## How It Works
When you dynamically switch between components using the `<component :is="currentComponent"></component>` syntax, Vue by default destroys the inactive component instance and creates a new one when it's switched back. This means any local state, form input, or DOM manipulation within that component is lost.

`keep-alive` wraps around the dynamic component and intercepts this destruction process. Instead of destroying the inactive component, it caches its instance in memory. When you switch back to a cached component, `keep-alive` simply reuses the existing instance, preserving its state and avoiding the cost of re-initialization and re-rendering.

It exposes two lifecycle hooks specific to cached components:
*   `activated`: Called when a cached component is activated (becomes visible).
*   `deactivated`: Called when a cached component is deactivated (becomes hidden).

**Practical Example:**
Consider a tabbed interface where each tab contains a complex form. Without `keep-alive`, switching between tabs would reset the form inputs and state of the inactive tab. With `keep-alive`, you can fill out part of a form in Tab A, switch to Tab B, and then switch back to Tab A, finding your form inputs still intact.

## Code Example

```typescript
// Tab A Component
// components/TabA.vue
<template>
  <div>
    <h3>Tab A Content</h3>
    <input type="text" v-model="message" placeholder="Type something...">
    <p>Message: {{ message }}</p>
  </div>
</template>

<script lang="ts">
import { defineComponent, ref } from 'vue';

export default defineComponent({
  name: 'TabA',
  setup() {
    const message = ref('');
    return { message };
  },
  activated() {
    console.log('TabA activated!');
  },
  deactivated() {
    console.log('TabA deactivated!');
  }
});
</script>

// Tab B Component
// components/TabB.vue
<template>
  <div>
    <h3>Tab B Content</h3>
    <p>This is some content for Tab B.</p>
    <button @click="increment">Count: {{ count }}</button>
  </div>
</template>

<script lang="ts">
import { defineComponent, ref } from 'vue';

export default defineComponent({
  name: 'TabB',
  setup() {
    const count = ref(0);
    const increment = () => {
      count.value++;
    };
    return { count, increment };
  },
  activated() {
    console.log('TabB activated!');
  },
  deactivated() {
    console.log('TabB deactivated!');
  }
});
</script>

// Parent Component using keep-alive
// App.vue
<template>
  <div>
    <h1>Keep-Alive Example</h1>
    <button @click="activeTab = 'TabA'">Show Tab A</button>
    <button @click="activeTab = 'TabB'">Show Tab B</button>

    <hr>

    <!-- Without keep-alive, state would reset on tab switch -->
    <!-- <component :is="activeTab"></component> -->

    <!-- With keep-alive, state is preserved -->
    <keep-alive>
      <component :is="activeTab"></component>
    </keep-alive>
  </div>
</template>

<script lang="ts">
import { defineComponent, ref } from 'vue';
import TabA from './components/TabA.vue';
import TabB from './components/TabB.vue';

export default defineComponent({
  name: 'App',
  components: {
    TabA,
    TabB
  },
  setup() {
    const activeTab = ref('TabA');
    return { activeTab };
  }
});
</script>
```

In this example, if you type something into `TabA`'s input field, then switch to `TabB`, and then switch back to `TabA`, the input field's content will still be there because `keep-alive` preserved `TabA`'s instance. The `activated` and `deactivated` console logs will also demonstrate when the components are being cached/reused.

## Key Takeaways
*   **State Preservation:** Prevents components from being destroyed and re-created, preserving their local state and DOM.
*   **Performance Improvement:** Reduces rendering overhead by reusing existing component instances instead of re-initializing them.
*   **User Experience:** Provides a smoother experience in scenarios like tabbed interfaces or multi-step forms where users expect their progress to be maintained.
*   **Conditional Caching:** Can be configured with `include`, `exclude`, and `max` props to control which components are cached and the maximum number of cached instances.
*   **Lifecycle Hooks:** Introduces `activated` and `deactivated` hooks for logic specific to when a cached component becomes active or inactive.

## Quick Summary
React Fiber is a complete re-implementation of the React core algorithm, introduced in React 16. Its primary goal is to enable incremental rendering, allowing React to pause work and come back to it later. This improves the responsiveness of applications by preventing long-running rendering tasks from blocking the main thread, leading to a smoother user experience, especially for animations and user input.

## How It Works
Before Fiber, React's reconciliation process (diffing the virtual DOM and updating the real DOM) was a synchronous, blocking operation. Once it started, it couldn't be interrupted until it completed. If this process took too long, it would block the browser's main thread, making the UI unresponsive (janky).

Fiber addresses this by breaking down the rendering work into smaller, interruptible units. Each unit of work is a "Fiber" – a plain JavaScript object that represents a component's state, props, and its relationship to other components.

Here's a simplified breakdown of the Fiber reconciliation phases:

1.  **Render/Reconciliation Phase (Interruptible):**
    *   React traverses the component tree, building a "work-in-progress" Fiber tree.
    *   For each component, it performs tasks like calling `render()`, comparing old and new props, and determining what needs to be updated.
    *   This phase can be paused, interrupted, and resumed. React can yield control back to the browser if higher-priority tasks (like user input or animation frames) come in.
    *   Side effects (like DOM mutations) are **not** performed in this phase. Instead, they are collected.

2.  **Commit Phase (Synchronous):**
    *   Once the render phase completes without interruption, React has a complete list of all changes that need to be applied to the DOM.
    *   This phase is synchronous and uninterruptible because it's where the actual DOM updates and side effects (like `useEffect` callbacks, `componentDidMount`/`Update`) occur. It's crucial that these changes are applied all at once to prevent visual inconsistencies.

By splitting the work, Fiber allows React to prioritize updates. For example, if a user types into an input field, React can pause a lower-priority update (like rendering a large list) to process the input event and update the input field immediately, then resume the list rendering later. This is achieved through techniques like `requestIdleCallback` (conceptually) or `MessageChannel` internally, allowing React to schedule work when the browser is idle.

## Code Example
While Fiber itself is an internal implementation detail and not something you directly interact with via API, its effects are visible in features like `useState` with functional updates and `useTransition`/`useDeferredValue`.

Consider a scenario where you have a slow rendering component and a fast input. Without Fiber's scheduling, the input might feel janky. With Fiber, React can prioritize the input update.

```typescript
import React, { useState, useTransition } from 'react';

// A component that simulates slow rendering
const SlowComponent = React.memo(({ count }: { count: number }) => {
  console.log('Rendering SlowComponent with count:', count);
  let items: JSX.Element[] = [];
  for (let i = 0; i < 5000; i++) { // Simulate heavy computation/rendering
    items.push(<div key={i}>{count} - Item {i}</div>);
  }
  return (
    <div style={{ border: '1px solid red', padding: '10px', height: '200px', overflowY: 'auto' }}>
      <h3>Slow Component Displaying: {count}</h3>
      {items}
    </div>
  );
});

const FiberDemo: React.FC = () => {
  const [inputValue, setInputValue] = useState('');
  const [slowCount, setSlowCount] = useState(0);
  const [isPending, startTransition] = useTransition();

  const handleInputChange = (e: React.ChangeEvent<HTMLInputElement>) => {
    const value = e.target.value;
    setInputValue(value); // This update is high priority and immediate

    // This update is wrapped in startTransition, making it a low priority update
    // React can interrupt this if other high-priority tasks (like more typing) occur.
    startTransition(() => {
      setSlowCount(parseInt(value) || 0);
    });
  };

  return (
    <div>
      <h1>React Fiber Demo (with useTransition)</h1>
      <p>Type a number below. The input field will update immediately (high priority).</p>
      <p>The "Slow Component" will update with a slight delay (low priority via `useTransition`), allowing the input to remain responsive.</p>

      <input
        type="number"
        value={inputValue}
        onChange={handleInputChange}
        placeholder="Enter a number"
        style={{ padding: '10px', fontSize: '1.2em' }}
      />
      {isPending && <p>Loading slow component...</p>}

      <hr />

      <SlowComponent count={slowCount} />
    </div>
  );
};

export default FiberDemo;
```
In this example, `setInputValue` is a high-priority update. `setSlowCount` wrapped in `startTransition` is a lower-priority, interruptible update. This demonstrates how Fiber, exposed through hooks like `useTransition`, allows React to schedule and prioritize different updates, improving perceived performance.

## Key Takeaways
*   **Incremental Rendering:** Fiber enables React to break down rendering work into smaller units, allowing the browser to interrupt and prioritize high-priority tasks (e.g., user input, animations).
*   **Asynchronous Reconciliation:** Unlike the previous synchronous reconciliation, Fiber's render phase is asynchronous and interruptible.
*   **Improved User Experience:** Leads to more responsive UIs, preventing jank and ensuring a smoother feel, especially under heavy load or for complex applications.
*   **Internal Implementation:** Fiber is an internal re-architecture; you don't directly interact with it. However, its capabilities are exposed through features like `useState` (functional updates), `useTransition`, `useDeferredValue`, and concurrent mode.
*   **Two Phases:** It separates the "render/reconciliation" phase (interruptible, building the work-in-progress tree) from the "commit" phase (synchronous, applying DOM changes and side effects).

## Quick Summary
Pseudo-classes and pseudo-elements are CSS selectors that allow you to target specific states or parts of an element that cannot be targeted using simple selectors. They extend the power of CSS by enabling styling based on user interaction, document structure, or generating content without altering the HTML.

## How It Works
### Pseudo-Classes (`)`
Pseudo-classes select elements based on a special *state* or *condition*. They start with a single colon (`:`).
They allow you to style an element when it's in a particular state, such as when a user hovers over it, when it's the first child of its parent, or when a form input is focused.

**Practical Examples:**
*   **`:hover`**: Applies styles when the mouse pointer is over an element.
*   **`:active`**: Applies styles when an element is being activated by the user (e.g., clicked).
*   **`:focus`**: Applies styles when an element (like an input field) has focus.
*   **`:nth-child(n)`**: Selects an element that is the *n*-th child of its parent.
*   **`:first-child` / `:last-child`**: Selects the first/last child element.
*   **`:not(selector)`**: Selects elements that do *not* match the specified selector.

### Pseudo-Elements (`::`)
Pseudo-elements select a *part* of an element that can be styled independently. They start with a double colon (`::`), although for backward compatibility with older browsers, a single colon is often still used for some older pseudo-elements like `::before` and `::after`.

They allow you to style specific parts of an element's content or insert generated content before or after an element without adding extra HTML.

**Practical Examples:**
*   **`::before`**: Inserts content *before* the actual content of an element. Often used with the `content` property.
*   **`::after`**: Inserts content *after* the actual content of an element. Also often used with the `content` property.
*   **`::first-line`**: Styles the first line of a block-level element.
*   **`::first-letter`**: Styles the first letter of a block-level element.
*   **`::selection`**: Styles the portion of an element that is highlighted by the user (e.g., when text is selected with the mouse).

## Code Example

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Pseudo-Class and Pseudo-Element Example</title>
    <style>
        /* Pseudo-Class Examples */
        .my-button {
            background-color: #007bff;
            color: white;
            padding: 10px 15px;
            border: none;
            border-radius: 5px;
            cursor: pointer;
            transition: background-color 0.3s ease;
        }

        .my-button:hover { /* Styles when mouse is over the button */
            background-color: #0056b3;
        }

        .my-button:active { /* Styles when button is being clicked */
            background-color: #004085;
            transform: translateY(1px);
        }

        input[type="text"]:focus { /* Styles when input field has focus */
            border-color: #007bff;
            box-shadow: 0 0 0 0.2rem rgba(0, 123, 255, 0.25);
            outline: none;
        }

        ul li:nth-child(odd) { /* Styles every odd list item */
            background-color: #f2f2f2;
        }

        ul li:first-child { /* Styles the first list item */
            font-weight: bold;
            color: purple;
        }

        /* Pseudo-Element Examples */
        .quote::before { /* Inserts content before the quote text */
            content: "“ ";
            font-size: 1.2em;
            color: #555;
        }

        .quote::after { /* Inserts content after the quote text */
            content: " ”";
            font-size: 1.2em;
            color: #555;
        }

        .paragraph::first-letter { /* Styles the first letter of the paragraph */
            font-size: 2em;
            font-weight: bold;
            color: #d9534f;
            float: left;
            margin-right: 5px;
        }

        .paragraph::first-line { /* Styles the first line of the paragraph */
            font-style: italic;
            color: #337ab7;
        }

